const ASUBHA_DATA = [ 
{ text: `Stop, thoughts of sensual desire!<br>Stop, thoughts of ill-will!<br>Stop, thoughts of harmfulness!<br>Enough, thoughts of sensual desire!<br>Enough, thoughts of ill-will!<br>Enough, thoughts of harmfulness!`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 17 – Mahāsudassanasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn17/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“O good friends, here someone associates with sensual pleasures, associates with unwholesome states. After some time, that person hears the noble Dhamma, gives wise attention, and attains the true Dhamma and the Dhamma in accordance. And having heard the noble Dhamma, given wise attention, and attained the true Dhamma and the Dhamma in accordance, that person lives without associating with sensual pleasures, without associating with unwholesome states. By living without associating with sensual pleasures, without associating with unwholesome states, ease arises, and more than ease, gladness arises. O good friends, just as from comfort joy is born, so too, O good friends, by living without associating with sensual pleasures, without associating with unwholesome states, ease arises, and more than ease, gladness arises. O good friends, that is the first short path leading to ease, realized by the Blessed One, the Wise One, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 18 – Janavasabhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn18/en/sujato" },

{ text: `"O great king, when the eye sees a form, the monk does not grasp the general feature, does not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — that cause the monk restrains, guards the eye faculty, practices the restraint of the eye faculty."`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `"Those causes whereby, if the mind faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — that cause the monk restrains, guards the mind faculty, practices the restraint of the mind faculty. By means of this noble restraint of the faculties, he experiences an internal feeling of ease, unblemished."`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `"The monk, secluding himself from sensual desires, secluding himself from unwholesome states, enters and dwells in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and pleasure born of seclusion. He drenches, saturates, fills, and pervades his very body with the rapture and pleasure born of seclusion, so that no spot on his entire body is not pervaded by that rapture and pleasure born of seclusion."`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `"When the eye sees a form, the monk does not grasp the general feature, does not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — that cause the monk restrains, guards the eye faculty... By means of this noble restraint of the faculties, he experiences an internal feeling of ease, unblemished."`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then the Blessed One gave progressive instruction to the brahmin Pokkharasādi, namely: talk on giving, talk on virtue, talk on the heavens; he explained the danger, degradation, and defilement of sensual pleasures, and the benefit of renunciation. When the Blessed One knew that the brahmin Pokkharasādi’s mind was ready, pliant, free from hindrances, uplifted, and confident, he then taught the Dhamma that the Buddhas have realized, namely: suffering, origin, cessation, and path. Just as a clean cloth, freed from black stains, would properly absorb dye, so too, right there in that seat, the dust-free, stainless Dhamma-eye arose in the brahmin Pokkharasādi: ‘Whatever is subject to origination is all subject to cessation.’`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 3 – Ambaṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Poṭṭhapāda, when defiling states are eliminated, pure states increase; here and now, by direct knowledge, one realizes and abides in fully developed, vast wisdom. Then joy arises, gladness, tranquility, mindfulness, clear comprehension, and a pleasant abiding arise.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, thought: ‘This Dhamma that I have realized is deep, hard to see, hard to awaken to, peaceful, sublime, beyond the sphere of logic, subtle, to be understood by the wise. But this generation delights in sensual pleasures, is devoted to sensual pleasures, is fond of sensual pleasures. For a generation that delights in sensual pleasures, is devoted to sensual pleasures, is fond of sensual pleasures, it is hard to see this principle of specific conditionality (dependent origination); it is hard to see the principle that all formations are peaceful, that all substrates of rebirth are eliminated, that craving is destroyed, that there is dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna.’”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the Blessed One Vipassī, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, surveyed the world with the Buddha-eye and saw beings with little dust in their eyes and with much dust in their eyes, with sharp faculties and with dull faculties, with good dispositions and with bad dispositions, some easy to teach and some hard to teach, and a few who saw the danger in rebirth in another world and the danger of faulty actions. Just as in a blue lotus pond, a red lotus pond, or a white lotus pond, some blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, do not rise above the water, and are nourished underwater; some blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, and reach the water’s surface; some blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, rise up above the water and are not wetted by the water.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, as long as the community of monks is not dominated by craving — that craving which leads to another state of existence — then, monks, the community of monks can be expected to prosper and not decline.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Ānanda, here a monk abides contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having restrained covetousness and sorrow in the world; abides contemplating feelings as feelings … mind as mind … phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having restrained covetousness and sorrow in the world. Ānanda, thus a monk is an island unto himself, a refuge unto himself, seeking no other refuge; with the Dhamma as his island, with the Dhamma as his refuge, seeking no other refuge.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, it is because of not realizing, not penetrating four things that you and I have wandered for such a long time in this cycle of birth and death. What four? Monks, because of not realizing, not penetrating noble virtue, you and I have wandered for such a long time in this cycle of birth and death. Monks, because of not realizing, not penetrating noble concentration … noble wisdom … noble liberation, you and I have wandered for such a long time in this cycle of birth and death.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `All formations are impermanent,<br>Having arisen, they must cease;<br>Having arisen, they are subject to cessation,<br>Their calming is bliss.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 16 – Mahāparinibbānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Thus he abides contemplating the body as a body internally; or he abides contemplating the body as a body externally; or he abides contemplating the body as a body both internally and externally. Or he abides contemplating the nature of arising in the body; or he abides contemplating the nature of passing away in the body; or he abides contemplating the nature of both arising and passing away in the body. ‘There is a body,’ he establishes mindfulness just enough for knowledge and mindfulness. And he abides independent, not clinging to anything in the world. Thus, monks, a monk abides contemplating the body as a body.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, here a monk, when there is sensual desire in him, knows: ‘There is sensual desire in me’; or when there is no sensual desire in him, knows: ‘There is no sensual desire in me.’ And he knows how unarisen sensual desire arises; he knows how arisen sensual desire is abandoned; and he knows how abandoned sensual desire does not arise in the future.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, when craving arises, where does it arise? When it establishes itself, where does it establish itself? Whatever in the world is endearing and agreeable: In the world, the eye is endearing and agreeable. There this craving arises; there it establishes itself. The ear … the nose … the tongue … the body … the mind is endearing and agreeable. There this craving arises; there it establishes itself.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is Right Intention? Intention of renunciation, intention of non-ill-will, intention of harmlessness. Monks, this is called Right Intention.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is Right Effort? Monks, here a monk awakens desire for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He awakens desire for the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He awakens desire for the arising of unarisen wholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. He awakens desire for the continuance, non-disappearance, strengthening, increase, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states; he makes an effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives. This, monks, is called Right Effort.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is Right Mindfulness? Monks, here a monk abides contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having restrained covetousness and sorrow in the world; abides contemplating feelings as feelings … mind as mind … phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having restrained covetousness and sorrow in the world. This, monks, is called Right Mindfulness.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 22 – Mahāsatipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And Nigrodha, there are unwholesome states that have not been abandoned, that are defiling, leading to renewed existence, bringing suffering, resulting in pain, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Those states I teach for the purpose of abandoning them. If you practice in accordance with the teaching, then those defiling states will be abandoned, the pure states will increase, and you will personally know, realize, and attain to abiding here and now with perfect and complete wisdom.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 25 – Udumbarikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn25/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, how does a monk live as an island unto himself, a refuge unto himself, seeking no other refuge; with the Dhamma as his island, with the Dhamma as his refuge, seeking no other refuge? Monks, here a monk abides contemplating the body as a body internally, ardent, diligent, mindful, clearly comprehending, to remove covetousness and sorrow in the world; abides contemplating feelings as feelings … mind as mind … phenomena as phenomena, ardent, diligent, mindful, clearly comprehending, to remove covetousness and sorrow in the world. Thus, monks, a monk lives as an island unto himself, a refuge unto himself, seeking no other refuge; with the Dhamma as his island, with the Dhamma as his refuge, seeking no other refuge.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavattisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, wander in your own proper range, in your own ancestral territory. Monks, if you wander in your own proper range, in your own ancestral territory, then longevity will increase, beauty will increase, ease will increase, wealth will increase, power will increase.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 26 – Cakkavattisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Cunda, I do not teach merely for the sake of preventing defilements in the present life. Cunda, I do not teach the Dhamma only for the sake of eradicating defilements in the future. Cunda, I teach the Dhamma both for preventing defilements in the present life and for eradicating defilements in the future.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, Cunda, here a person is infatuated, addicted, living surrounded by the five strands of sensual pleasure; that is the fourth kind of pleasure. Cunda, these four kinds of pleasure are low, vulgar, worldly, ignoble, unbeneficial, not leading to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, and Nibbāna. Cunda, this is possible: wanderers of other sects might say: ‘The Sakyan ascetics are living addicted to these four kinds of pleasure.’ They should be answered: ‘That is not so; you speak wrongly. You misrepresent us, untruthfully, falsely.’”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 29 – Pāsādikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn29/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“The four right efforts: Here, venerable sirs, a monk awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states. He awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states. He awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the arising of unarisen wholesome states. He awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the continuance, non-disappearance, strengthening, increase, development, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable sirs, what is the effort of abandoning? Here, a monk does not consent to arisen sensual thought; he abandons, dispels, destroys, makes it non-existent. He does not consent to arisen ill-will thought … he does not consent to arisen harmful thought; he abandons, dispels, destroys, makes it non-existent. This, venerable sirs, is called the effort of abandoning.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 33 – Saṅgītisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn33/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what are the defilements that should be abandoned by restraint? Here, a monk, reflecting wisely, lives with the restraint of the eye faculty. Monks, if he lives without restraining the eye faculty, harmful, feverish defilements might arise. If he restrains the eye faculty, those harmful, feverish defilements are no more. These, monks, are called the defilements that should be abandoned by restraint.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, here a monk, reflecting wisely, does not consent to arisen sensual thought; he abandons, dispels, destroys, makes it non-existent. He does not consent to arisen ill-will thought … does not consent to arisen harmful thought; he abandons, dispels, destroys, makes it non-existent. He does not consent to any arisen evil, unwholesome states; he abandons, dispels, destroys, makes them non-existent.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, for a monk, those defilements that should be abandoned by direct knowledge have been abandoned by direct knowledge; those defilements that should be abandoned by restraint have been abandoned by restraint … That monk is called one who lives restrained by the restraint of all defilements, who has cut off craving, has shed the fetters, has rightly penetrated conceit, and has made an end of suffering.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 2 – Sabbāsavasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, good sirs, greed is an unwholesome state, and ill-will is also an unwholesome state. There is a Middle Way that abandons greed and abandons ill-will, giving rise to (pure) vision, giving rise to (true) knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. And what, good sirs, is that Middle Way that gives rise to vision, gives rise to knowledge, leads to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration. This, good sirs, is the Middle Way that gives rise to vision, gives rise to knowledge, leads to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 3 – Dhammadāyādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, venerable sir, a person has a stain and he truly knows: ‘There is a stain in me.’ For such a person, it can be expected: ‘He will arouse desire, make effort, arouse energy to abandon that stain. He will die without greed, without ill-will, without delusion, without stain, his mind unpolluted.’ Venerable sir, just as a bronze bowl brought from the market or from the smithy, covered with dust and grime, and the owner uses it, wipes it, and does not throw it into a dusty place – that bowl, after a time, becomes more purified and cleaner.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable sir, thus a person has a stain and truly knows: ‘There is a stain in me.’ For such a person, it can be expected: ‘He will arouse desire, make effort, arouse energy to abandon that stain. He will die without greed, without ill-will, without delusion, without stain, his mind unpolluted.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable sir, thus a person has no stain and truly knows: ‘There is no stain in me.’ For such a person, it can be expected: ‘He will not attend to the sign of the beautiful. By not attending to the sign of the beautiful, greed will not pollute his mind. He will die without greed, without ill-will, without delusion, without stain, his mind unpolluted.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, venerable sir, a person has no stain but does not truly know: ‘There is no stain in me.’ For such a person, it can be expected: ‘He will attend to the sign of the beautiful. By attending to the sign of the beautiful, greed will pollute his mind. He will die with greed, with ill-will, with delusion, with stain, his mind polluted.’ Venerable sir, just as a bronze bowl brought from the market or from the smithy, clean and pure, and the owner does not use it, does not wipe it, and throws it into a dusty place – that bowl, after a time, becomes more defiled and dustier.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable sir, thus a person has no stain but does not truly know: ‘There is no stain in me.’ For such a person, it can be expected: ‘He will attend to the sign of the beautiful. By attending to the sign of the beautiful, greed will pollute his mind. He will die with greed, with ill-will, with delusion, with stain, his mind polluted.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable sir, ‘stain’ is called a stain. What term is synonymous with what is called ‘stain’?”<br>“Venerable sir, evil, unwholesome states, the realm of sensual desire, are synonymous with what is called ‘stain.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 5 – Anaṅgaṇasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as a defiled, dust-covered cloth, when a dyer dips it in this or that dye – blue, yellow, red, or purple – will take the dye poorly and be unclean. Why is that? Because the cloth is not clean. So too, monks, a foul destination awaits a defiled mind. Monks, just as a clean, bright cloth, when a dyer dips it in this or that dye – blue, yellow, red, or purple – will take the dye well and be clean. Why is that? Because the cloth is clean. So too, monks, a good destination awaits an undefiled mind.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, are the defilements of the mind? Covetousness, unrighteous greed is a defilement of the mind; ill-will is a defilement of the mind; anger is a defilement of the mind; hostility is a defilement of the mind; hypocrisy, spite, envy, stinginess, deceit, fraud, obstinacy, impetuosity, conceit, arrogance, vanity, heedlessness are defilements of the mind.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, a monk who thinks: ‘Covetousness, unrighteous greed is a defilement of the mind’ and, knowing that, abandons the covetousness, unrighteous greed that is a defilement of the mind; thinks: ‘Ill-will is a defilement of the mind’ and, knowing that, abandons ill-will, the defilement of the mind; anger … hostility … hypocrisy … spite … envy … stinginess … deceit … fraud … obstinacy … impetuosity … conceit … arrogance … vanity; thinks: ‘Heedlessness is a defilement of the mind’ and, knowing that, abandons heedlessness, the defilement of the mind.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as a defiled, dusty cloth, if placed in clean water becomes clean, if placed in a furnace becomes clean. So too, monks, a monk of such virtue, such quality, such wisdom – even if he eats almsfood of choice rice with black grains removed, various soups and curries – that does not become an obstacle for him.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 7 – Vatthūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Cunda, just as all unwholesome states tend downward and all wholesome states tend upward. So too, Cunda: the harmless person is higher than the harmful person; the person who abstains from killing is higher than the killer; the person who abstains from taking what is not given is higher than the taker of what is not given; the person unsmeared by the world, not clinging to personal views, of easy disposition and equanimity, is higher than the person smeared by the world, clinging to personal views, of difficult disposition and lacking equanimity.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 8 – Sallekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn8/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Good sirs, what is suffering? Birth is suffering, aging is suffering, sickness is suffering, death is suffering, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, despair are suffering, not getting what one wants is suffering; in short, the five clinging-aggregates are suffering. This, good sirs, is called suffering. Good sirs, what is the origin of suffering? It is craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, delighting here and there; that is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence. This, good sirs, is called the origin of suffering.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Good sirs, what is the cessation of suffering? It is the remainderless fading away and cessation of that same craving, the abandoning and relinquishing of it, freedom from it, non-reliance on it. Good sirs, what is the path leading to the cessation of suffering? It is the Noble Eightfold Path that leads to the cessation of suffering, namely: Right View, Right Intention, Right Speech, Right Action, Right Livelihood, Right Effort, Right Mindfulness, Right Concentration.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 9 – Sammādiṭṭhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if anyone would develop these four foundations of mindfulness for just seven days, one of two fruits could be expected: either final knowledge here and now, or if there remains a trace of clinging, the state of non-return. Monks, this is the one-way path for the purification of beings, for the overcoming of sorrow and lamentation, for the disappearance of pain and grief, for the attainment of the true way, for the realization of Nibbāna – namely, the Four Foundations of Mindfulness.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 10 – Satipaṭṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn10/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, monks, with sensuality as the cause, sensuality as the source, sensuality as the basis, simply because of sensuality, king fights with king, noble warrior fights with noble warrior, brahmin fights with brahmin, householder fights with householder, mother fights with child, child fights with mother, father fights with child, child fights with father, brother fights with brother, brother fights with sister, sister fights with brother, friend fights with friend. Having engaged in quarrels, disputes, and battles, they attack one another with fists, with stones, with sticks, with swords. There they meet death or deadly suffering. Monks, such is the peril of sensuality, a mass of suffering visible here and now, with sensuality as the cause, sensuality as the source, sensuality as the basis – simply because of sensuality.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, monks, with sensuality as the cause, sensuality as the source, sensuality as the basis, simply because of sensuality, taking up shields and weapons, donning quiver and bow, they charge into battle with freshly plastered ramparts, and arrows are hurled, swords are drawn. There they are pierced by arrows, struck by spears, drenched with boiling dung, crushed by stones, and their heads are cut off by swords. There they meet death or deadly suffering. Monks, such is the peril of sensuality, a mass of suffering visible here and now, with sensuality as the cause, sensuality as the source, sensuality as the basis – simply because of sensuality.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, monks, with sensuality as the cause, sensuality as the source, sensuality as the basis, simply because of sensuality, they engage in misconduct of body, misconduct of speech, misconduct of mind. Having engaged in misconduct of body, speech, and mind, with the breakup of the body, after death, they are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. Monks, such is the peril of sensuality, leading to future suffering, a mass of suffering, with sensuality as the cause, sensuality as the source, sensuality as the basis – simply because of sensuality.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, such is the peril in the case of forms. Furthermore, monks, one sees that woman’s body thrown in the charnel ground, one, two, or three days dead – bloated, discolored, festering. What do you think, monks? Has the former charm and beauty disappeared and peril become evident?”<br>“Yes, venerable sir.”<br>“Monks, such is the peril in the case of forms.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, such is the peril in the case of forms. Furthermore, monks, one sees that woman’s body thrown in the charnel ground, just a skeleton with white bones like a shell … bones more than a year old … rotting bones reduced to powder. What do you think, monks? Has the former charm and beauty disappeared and peril become evident?”<br>“Yes, venerable sir.”<br>“Monks, such is the peril in the case of forms.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the peril in the case of feelings? Feelings are impermanent, suffering, subject to change – that is the peril in the case of feelings. And what, monks, is the escape in the case of feelings? The removal of desire and lust for feelings, the abandoning of desire and lust – that is the escape in the case of feelings.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Mahānāma, in the past, when I was still a bodhisatta, not yet fully enlightened, I saw with correct wisdom as it actually is: ‘Sensual pleasures are of little satisfaction, much suffering, much despair, and the peril is even greater.’ Yet, even though I saw that with correct wisdom, I did not attain the rapture and pleasure born of seclusion, of non-sensuality, of unwholesome states, or anything higher than that. And then I knew that I was not yet free from being dominated by sensual pleasures. Mahānāma, when I saw with correct wisdom as it actually is: ‘Sensual pleasures are of little satisfaction, much suffering, much despair, and the peril is even greater,’ and I attained the rapture and pleasure born of seclusion, of non-sensuality, of unwholesome states, or anything higher than that, then I knew that I was free from being dominated by sensual pleasures.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 14 – Cūḷadukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, Mahānāma, is the gratification of sensual pleasures? Mahānāma, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure: forms cognizable by the eye – desirable, pleasurable, agreeable, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing; sounds cognizable by the ear … odors cognizable by the nose … tastes cognizable by the tongue … tangibles cognizable by the body – desirable, pleasurable, agreeable, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. These, Mahānāma, are the five strands of sensual pleasure. The pleasure and joy that arise in dependence on these five strands of sensual pleasure – that is the gratification of sensual pleasures.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 14 – Cūḷadukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Good sirs, if, while reflecting, a monk sees clearly that all unarisen evil, unwholesome states are not yet abandoned within him, then he should arouse energy to abandon those evil, unwholesome states. Good sirs, if, while reflecting, a monk sees clearly that all evil, unwholesome states have been abandoned within him, then he should dwell with joyful mind, training in wholesome states day and night.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 15 – Anumānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn15/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What are the five mental shackles not yet cut off? Monks, here a monk is not free from lust, desire, affection, thirst, fever, craving for sensual pleasures. Monks, for a monk who is not free from lust … craving for sensual pleasures, his mind does not incline to exertion, commitment, persistence, striving. If one’s mind does not incline to exertion, commitment, persistence, striving, this is the first mental shackle not yet cut off.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 16 – Cetokhilasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, then I dwelt heedful, ardent, resolute. When a sensual thought arose, I understood: ‘This sensual thought has arisen in me, and it leads to my own harm, to others’ harm, to the harm of both, destroys wisdom, is part of vexation, does not lead to Nibbāna.’ Monks, as I reflected: ‘This sensual thought leads to my own harm’ – it subsided. As I reflected: ‘It leads to others’ harm’ – it subsided. As I reflected: ‘It leads to the harm of both’ – it subsided. As I reflected: ‘It destroys wisdom, is part of vexation, does not lead to Nibbāna’ – it subsided. Thus, monks, I continued to remove, abandon, and put an end to sensual thoughts.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, whatever a monk frequently thinks and ponders upon, that becomes the inclination of his mind. Monks, if a monk frequently thinks and ponders upon sensual thoughts, he has abandoned thoughts of renunciation. When his mind has become heavy with sensual thoughts, his mind inclines to sensual thoughts. Monks, if a monk frequently thinks and ponders upon thoughts of ill-will … thoughts of harmfulness, he has abandoned thoughts of non-harmfulness. When his mind has become heavy with harmful thoughts, his mind inclines to harmful thoughts.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as in the last month of the rainy season, in autumn, when the rice has ripened, a cowherd tending cows would poke the cows on this side and that with a stick, restraining and checking them. Why is that? Because the cowherd sees that otherwise there would be death, imprisonment, beating, or blame. Monks, even so, I saw the peril, the degradation, the defilement of unwholesome states, and I saw the escape, the benefit, the purification of wholesome states.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, while I was dwelling heedful, ardent, resolute, when a thought of renunciation arose, I understood: ‘This thought of renunciation has arisen in me, and it leads neither to my own harm, nor to others’ harm, nor to the harm of both, increases wisdom, is not part of vexation, leads to Nibbāna.’ Monks, if I thought and pondered upon it at night, I saw no fear from that cause. If I thought and pondered upon it by day, I saw no fear from that cause. If I thought and pondered upon it both night and day, I saw no fear from that cause. But if I thought and pondered too long, my body might become fatigued; when the body is fatigued, the mind becomes disturbed; when the mind is disturbed, it is far from concentration. Then, monks, I steadied my mind internally, calmed it, unified it, concentrated it. Why was that? So that my mind would not be disturbed.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as in a dense forest there is a large deep lake, and a great herd of deer lives near one side. Then a man comes who does not desire their welfare, does not desire their benefit, does not desire their security from bondage. He closes off the safe, secure path leading to happiness and opens a dangerous path, sets a male decoy and a female decoy. Monks, then that great herd of deer will later fall into bondage and decline. Monks, then a man comes who desires their welfare, desires their benefit, desires their security from bondage. He opens the safe, secure path, closes the dangerous path, removes the male decoy, and destroys the female decoy. Monks, then that great herd of deer will later increase, prosper, and become abundant.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the large deep lake refers to sensual pleasures. Monks, the great herd of deer refers to beings. Monks, the man who does not desire their welfare, benefit, security refers to Māra the Evil One. Monks, the dangerous path refers to the wrong eightfold path – wrong view, wrong intention, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, wrong concentration. Monks, the male decoy refers to delight and greed. Monks, the female decoy refers to ignorance. Monks, the man who desires their welfare, benefit, security refers to the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. The safe, secure path leading to happiness refers to the Noble Eightfold Path – right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, thus I have opened the safe, secure path leading to happiness, closed the dangerous path, removed the male decoy, destroyed the female decoy. Monks, whatever a teacher should do for his disciples out of compassion, that I have done for you out of compassion. Monks, here are the roots of trees, here are empty places. Meditate, do not be heedless, do not have cause for regret later. This is my instruction to you.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 19 – Dvedhāvitakkasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as a skilled carpenter or his apprentice might use a small peg to knock out, drive out, and remove a larger peg; so too, monks, when a monk attends to some sign and gives attention to it, if evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion arise, then that monk should attend to a different sign connected with what is wholesome, not that sign. By attending to a different sign connected with what is wholesome, those evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion are abandoned and subside. With their abandonment, the mind becomes steadied, settled, unified, and concentrated.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if that monk, while attending to a different wholesome sign, still has evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion arising, then that monk should examine the peril in those thoughts: ‘These thoughts are unwholesome, these thoughts are blameworthy, these thoughts lead to painful results.’ By examining the peril in those thoughts, those evil, unwholesome thoughts are abandoned and subside. With their abandonment, the mind becomes steadied, settled, unified, and concentrated.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as a young man or woman, youthful, fond of adornment, would be distressed, ashamed, and disgusted if the carcass of a snake, a dog, or a human were hung around their neck; so too, monks, that monk, examining the peril in those thoughts … the mind becomes steadied, settled, unified, and concentrated.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if that monk, while examining the peril in those thoughts, still has evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion arising, then that monk should not attend to, not give attention to those thoughts. By not attending to, not giving attention to those thoughts, those evil, unwholesome thoughts are abandoned and subside. With their abandonment, the mind becomes steadied, settled, unified, and concentrated. Monks, just as a person with eyes, not wanting to see forms within his range, would close his eyes or look away; so too, monks, that monk, by not attending … the mind becomes steadied, settled, unified, and concentrated.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if a monk, while attending to some sign and giving attention to it, has evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion arise. That monk attends to a different sign connected with what is wholesome, not that sign. Those evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, ill-will, and delusion are abandoned and subside. With their abandonment, the mind becomes steadied, settled, unified, and concentrated.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 20 – Vitakkasaṇṭhānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Therefore, monks, abandon the unwholesome and strive for the wholesome states. Thus you will achieve growth, prosperity, and increase in this Dhamma and Discipline. Monks, just as near a village or small town there is a large sala-tree forest overgrown with trumpet-flower creepers. Then a man comes who desires the welfare of that forest, its benefit, its security from bondage. He cuts down the crooked, weak branches, throws them out, and cleans the forest inside. He properly cares for the straight, well-grown sala saplings. Monks, after some time, that forest becomes grown, prosperous, and increased. So too, monks, abandon the unwholesome and strive for the wholesome states. Thus you will achieve growth, prosperity, and increase in this Dhamma and Discipline.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 21 – Kakacūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn21/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Truly, monks, it is impossible that one could enjoy sensual pleasures apart from sensual pleasures, apart from sensual perceptions, apart from sensual thoughts.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 22 – Alagaddūpamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these two kinds of search: the noble search and the ignoble search. And what, monks, is the ignoble search? Here, monks, a person being himself subject to birth seeks what is also subject to birth; being himself subject to aging seeks what is subject to aging; being subject to sickness … subject to death … subject to sorrow … subject to defilement seeks what is subject to defilement. And what, monks, do you call ‘subject to birth’? Wife and children are subject to birth; male and female slaves are subject to birth; goats and sheep are subject to birth; fowl and pigs are subject to birth; elephants, cattle, horses, mares are subject to birth; gold and silver are subject to birth. Monks, these attachments are subject to birth, and he, being himself subject to birth, being tied to them, infatuated, and utterly committed to them, seeks what is subject to birth.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the noble search? Here, monks, a person being himself subject to birth, having known the peril in what is subject to birth, seeks the unborn, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna; being himself subject to aging, having known the peril in aging, seeks the unaging, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna; being subject to sickness … the unailing … subject to death … the deathless … subject to sorrow … the sorrowless … subject to defilement, having known the peril in defilement, seeks the undefiled, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna. This, monks, is called the noble search.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I too, before my enlightenment, while still a bodhisatta, being myself subject to birth sought what is subject to birth; being subject to aging sought what is subject to aging; being subject to sickness … subject to death … subject to sorrow … subject to defilement sought what is subject to defilement. Then, monks, I thought: ‘Why do I, being subject to birth, seek what is subject to birth? … Suppose that I, being subject to birth, having known the peril in what is subject to birth, seek the unborn, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna; being subject to aging … the unaging … subject to sickness … the unailing … subject to death … the deathless … subject to sorrow … the sorrowless … subject to defilement, having known the peril in defilement, seek the undefiled, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, then I thought: ‘This Dhamma I have attained is deep, hard to see, hard to realize, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of mere logic, subtle, to be understood only by the wise. But this generation delights in sensual pleasures, is devoted to sensual pleasures, is fond of sensual pleasures. For a generation that delights, is devoted, and is fond of sensual pleasures, it is hard to see this principle of specific conditionality (dependent origination); it is also hard to see the stilling of all formations, the relinquishment of all substrates, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, having heard Brahmā’s request, out of compassion for beings, I surveyed the world with the Buddha-eye. With the Buddha-eye, I saw beings with little dust in their eyes and with much dust in their eyes, with sharp faculties and with dull faculties, with good dispositions and with bad dispositions, some easy to teach and some hard to teach, and a few who saw the danger in rebirth to another world and the danger of faulty actions. Just as in a blue lotus pond, a red lotus pond, or a white lotus pond, some blue lotuses, red lotuses, or white lotuses are born in the water, grow in the water, and do not rise above the water, being nourished underwater; some are born in the water, grow in the water, and reach the water’s surface; some are born in the water, grow in the water, and rise up above the water, not wetted by the water.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure. What five? Forms cognizable by the eye—these are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. Sounds cognizable by the ear … Odors cognizable by the nose … Tastes cognizable by the tongue … Tangibles cognizable by the body—these are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. These, monks, are the five strands of sensual pleasure.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, those ascetics or brahmins who are tied, infatuated, utterly committed to these five strands of sensual pleasure, who do not see their peril, who do not know the escape from them, and who enjoy them—they should be understood as having fallen into misfortune, into calamity, and are being used by Māra as he wishes. Monks, just as a forest deer that has fallen into a trap must lie down—that deer should be understood as having fallen into misfortune, into calamity, and is being used by the hunter as he wishes. When the hunter comes, the deer cannot leave as it wishes. So too, monks, those ascetics or brahmins who are tied … are being used by Māra as he wishes.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, those ascetics or brahmins who are not tied, infatuated, or utterly committed to these five strands of sensual pleasure, who see their peril, who know the escape from them, and who enjoy them—they should be understood as not fallen into misfortune, not fallen into calamity, and are not being used by Māra as he wishes. Monks, just as a forest deer that has not fallen into a trap does not have to lie down—that deer should be understood as not fallen into misfortune, not fallen into calamity, and is not being used by the hunter as he wishes. When the hunter comes, the deer can leave as it wishes. So too, monks, those ascetics or brahmins who are not tied … are not being used by Māra as he wishes.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as a forest deer, walking in the forest, walks confidently, stands confidently, sits confidently, lies down confidently. Why is that? Because it has escaped the hunter’s reach. So too, monks, a monk, secluding himself from sensual desires, secluding himself from unwholesome states, enters and dwells in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and pleasure born of seclusion. Monks, that monk is called one who has blinded Māra, who has destroyed his track, who has escaped the sight of Māra.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Having seen with wisdom, the defilements are abandoned. Monks, that monk is called one who has blinded Māra, destroyed his track, escaped the sight of Māra. He has crossed beyond all clinging in the world. He walks confidently, stands confidently, sits confidently, lies down confidently. Why is that? Because he has escaped the reach of Māra.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 26 – Ariyapariyesanāsutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what are the further things that should be done? ‘We must guard the sense faculties. When the eye sees a form, do not grasp the general feature, do not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise—we will restrain that cause, guard the eye, practice restraint of the eye. When the ear hears a sound … nose smells an odor … tongue tastes a flavor … body feels a touch … mind cognizes phenomena, do not grasp the general feature, do not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the mind faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise—we will restrain that cause, guard the mind, practice restraint of the mind.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, how is a monk a samana (ascetic)? He has quieted down evil, unwholesome states that are defiling, leading to renewed existence, fearful, producing painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, monks, a monk is a samana.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is a monk ‘washed clean’? He has washed away evil, unwholesome states that are defiling, leading to renewed existence, fearful, producing painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, monks, a monk is ‘washed clean.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is a monk ‘knowing and understanding’? He has known and understood evil, unwholesome states that are defiling, leading to renewed existence, fearful, producing painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, monks, a monk is ‘knowing and understanding.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is a monk ‘one who has learned’? He has destroyed evil, unwholesome states that are defiling, leading to renewed existence, fearful, producing painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, monks, a monk is ‘one who has learned.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is a monk called a ‘noble one’? He has made distant evil, unwholesome states that are defiling, leading to renewed existence, fearful, producing painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, monks, a monk is called a noble one.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is a monk called an arahant? He has made distant evil, unwholesome states that are defiling, leading to renewed existence, fearful, producing painful results, leading to future birth, aging, and death. Thus, monks, a monk is an arahant.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 39 – Mahāhatthipadopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, Mahānāma, does a noble disciple guard the sense faculties? Here, Mahānāma, when a noble disciple sees a form with the eye, he does not grasp the general feature, does not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise—he restrains that cause, guards the eye, practices restraint of the eye. When the ear hears a sound … nose smells an odor … tongue tastes a flavor … body feels a touch … mind cognizes phenomena, he does not grasp the general feature, does not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the mind faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise—he restrains that cause, guards the mind, practices restraint of the mind. Thus, Mahānāma, a noble disciple guards the sense faculties.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple has conscience (hiri): he is ashamed of bodily misconduct, verbal misconduct, mental misconduct, ashamed of evil, unwholesome states. He has fear of wrongdoing (ottappa): he fears bodily misconduct, verbal misconduct, mental misconduct, fears evil, unwholesome states.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, Mahānāma, a noble disciple dwells with aroused energy, abandoning unwholesome states and acquiring wholesome states, steadfast, vigorous, not shirking the burden of wholesome states. He has mindfulness, endowed with supreme mindfulness and discernment, recollecting and recalling what was done and said long ago. He has wisdom, endowed with wisdom regarding arising and passing away, noble and penetrating, leading to the complete destruction of suffering. Thus, Mahānāma, a noble disciple is endowed with noble qualities.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 53 – Sekhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn53/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Rāhula, when you wish to perform a bodily action, you should reflect upon that same bodily action: ‘Would this bodily action that I wish to do lead to my own harm, to the harm of others, or to the harm of both? Then this bodily action is unwholesome, leading to suffering, resulting in suffering.’ If, on reflection, you know: ‘This bodily action that I wish to do would lead to my own harm, to the harm of others, or to the harm of both; it is unwholesome, leading to suffering, resulting in suffering’—then such a bodily action you should certainly not do. If, on reflection, you know: ‘This bodily action that I wish to do does not lead to my own harm, nor to the harm of others, nor to the harm of both; it is wholesome, leading to ease, resulting in ease’—then such a bodily action you should do.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 61 – Ambalaṭṭhikārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn61/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Rāhula, develop the meditation on foulness. Rāhula, by developing the meditation on foulness, what is called lust is abandoned. Rāhula, develop the meditation on impermanence. Rāhula, by developing the meditation on impermanence, what is called the conceit ‘I am’ is abandoned.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 62 – Mahārāhulovādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn62/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, Ānanda, is the path, the way leading to the abandoning of the five lower fetters? Here, Ānanda, a monk, by the relinquishment of attachments (upadhiviveka), by the abandoning of unwholesome states, by the complete calming of bodily coarseness, secluded from sensual desires, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and dwells in the first jhāna, which is accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and pleasure born of seclusion.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 64 – Mahāmāluṅkyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn64/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“He contemplates all forms, feelings, perceptions, formations, and consciousness as impermanent, as suffering, as a disease, as a boil, as a dart, as misery, as an affliction, as alien, as disintegrating, as empty, as not-self. He turns his mind away from these states and directs it towards the deathless element: ‘This is peaceful, this is sublime—namely, the stilling of all formations, the relinquishment of all attachments, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation, Nibbāna.’ If he is firm in this, he attains the destruction of the defilements. If he does not yet attain the destruction of the defilements, then by that same Dhamma-lust, Dhamma-delight, and by the destruction of the five lower fetters, he becomes one who is reborn spontaneously (in the Pure Abodes) and there attains final Nibbāna, never to return from that world.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 64 – Mahāmāluṅkyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn64/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Then, while the Venerable Udāyi was in solitary retreat, this thought arose in his mind: ‘Indeed, the Blessed One has abandoned many painful states for us. Indeed, the Blessed One has brought us many pleasant states. Indeed, the Blessed One has abandoned many unwholesome states for us. Indeed, the Blessed One has brought us many wholesome states.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Udāyi, here some foolish person, when I say ‘Abandon this,’ says: ‘What is this trivial, petty thing? This ascetic is too strict about this restraint and elimination.’ They do not abandon it and they create discontent against me and against the monks who wish to train in the precepts. That, Udāyi, becomes for them a strong bond, a firm bond, a sturdy bond, a rotting not-less bond, a great log.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, Udāyi, a person lives aiming at the abandoning of attachments, the relinquishment of attachments. But while he lives aiming at the abandoning of attachments, the relinquishment of attachments, sometimes, from time to time, distorted thoughts, thoughts and considerations connected with attachments continue to arise. Udāyi, mindfulness arises slowly and he quickly abandons that thought, dispels it, ends it, destroys it. Udāyi, just as a man might drop two or three drops of water onto an iron pan that has been heated all day—slowly those drops fall, quickly they evaporate and vanish. Udāyi, I say: ‘This person is still bound, not freed.’ Why is that? Udāyi, the difference in his faculties has been fully understood by me.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“But here, Udāyi, a person thinks: ‘Attachment is the source of suffering.’ Having known this, he becomes unattached and liberated by the destruction of attachment. Udāyi, I say: ‘This person is not bound, not fettered.’ Why is that? Udāyi, the difference in his faculties has been fully understood by me.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Udāyi, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure. What five? Forms cognizable by the eye—desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. Sounds cognizable by the ear … Odors cognizable by the nose … Tastes cognizable by the tongue … Tangibles cognizable by the body—desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. These, Udāyi, are the five strands of sensual pleasure. Whatever pleasure or joy arises in dependence on these five strands of sensual pleasure, that is called sensual pleasure, defiled pleasure, worldling’s pleasure, ignoble pleasure. I say that such pleasure should not be pursued, should not be developed, should not be cultivated, should be feared.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 66 – Laṭukikopamasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Having gone forth, Anuruddhas, what should a clansman do? Anuruddhas, secluding himself from sensual desires, secluding himself from unwholesome states. If he does not attain rapture and pleasure or some other state more peaceful than that, then sensual lust invades his mind and remains; ill-will … sloth and torpor … restlessness and remorse … doubt … discontent … laziness invades his mind and remains. Anuruddhas, when he has not secluded himself from sensual desires, from unwholesome states, he does not attain rapture and pleasure or some other state more peaceful than that. Anuruddhas, when he does seclude himself from sensual desires, from unwholesome states, he attains rapture and pleasure or some other state more peaceful than that; then sensual lust does not invade his mind and remain; ill-will … sloth and torpor … restlessness and remorse … doubt … discontent … laziness does not invade his mind and remain. Anuruddhas, when he has secluded himself from sensual desires, from unwholesome states, he attains rapture and pleasure or some other state more peaceful than that.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 68 – Naḷakapānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn68/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“But this body, Aggivessana, is material, composed of the four great elements, born of father and mother, nourished with rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to rubbing, pressing, breaking, disintegration, dissolution. It should be contemplated as impermanent, as suffering, as a disease, as a boil, as a dart, as misery, as an affliction, as alien, as disintegrating, as empty, as not-self. When he contemplates this body as impermanent, as suffering, as a disease … as not-self, then bodily desire, bodily fondness, bodily subjection are abandoned.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 74 – Dīghanakhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn74/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Aggivessana, pleasant feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, subject to vanishing, subject to fading away, subject to cessation. Aggivessana, painful feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, subject to vanishing, subject to fading away, subject to cessation. Aggivessana, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen, subject to destruction, subject to vanishing, subject to fading away, subject to cessation.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 74 – Dīghanakhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn74/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What do you think, Māgandiya? Here, a person formerly was infatuated with forms cognizable by the eye that were desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. After some time, having known as they actually are the origination, the passing away, the gratification, the peril, and the escape in the case of forms, he abandons craving for forms, removes the fever for forms, and dwells with craving cut off, with mind inwardly peaceful.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgandiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Then I, after some time, having known as they actually are the origination, the passing away, the gratification, the peril, and the escape in the case of sensual pleasures, abandoned craving for sensual pleasures, removed the fever for sensual pleasures, and dwelt with craving cut off, with mind inwardly peaceful. Then I saw other beings who had not abandoned lust for sensual pleasures being consumed by craving for sensual pleasures, being burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, indulging in sensual pleasures. I did not envy them, nor did I delight in that. Why is that? Because, Māgandiya, there is this pleasure and rapture, apart from sensual pleasures, apart from unwholesome states, and having attained the heavenly pleasure, I dwell delighting in that. I do not envy what is inferior, nor do I delight in that.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgandiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“So too, Māgandiya, contact with sensual pleasures in the past was painful, very hot, very feverish; contact with sensual pleasures in the future will be painful, very hot, very feverish; contact with sensual pleasures in the present is painful, very hot, very feverish. And these beings who have not abandoned lust for sensual pleasures, being consumed by craving for sensual pleasures, burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, with corrupt faculties, perceive as pleasure that which is actually painful contact with sensual pleasures.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgandiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Māgandiya, suppose a leprous person with sores and blisters on his limbs, being devoured by worms, scratching the openings of his wounds with his nails, cauterizing his body over a charcoal pit. The more he scratches the wound openings and cauterizes his body, the more those wound openings become impure, foul-smelling, and infected, yet he feels some ease and satisfaction because of the itching of the wound openings. So too, Māgandiya, beings who have not abandoned lust for sensual pleasures, being consumed by craving for sensual pleasures, burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, indulge in sensual pleasures. The more they indulge in sensual pleasures, the more their craving for sensual pleasures increases, and the more they are burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, yet they feel some ease and satisfaction dependent on the five strands of sensual pleasure.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgandiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What do you think, Māgandiya? Have you ever seen or heard of a king or a king’s minister who, while enjoying the five strands of sensual pleasure fully and completely, without abandoning craving for sensual pleasures, without removing the fever of sensual pleasures, has dwelt, dwells, or will dwell with craving cut off and mind inwardly peaceful?”<br>“No, Master Gotama.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgandiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Good, Māgandiya. I too have never seen or heard of such a one. But, Māgandiya, those ascetics or brahmins who have dwelt, dwell, or will dwell with craving cut off and mind inwardly peaceful—all of them, having known as they actually are the origination, the passing away, the gratification, the peril, and the escape in the case of sensual pleasures, with craving for sensual pleasures abandoned and the fever of sensual pleasures removed, have dwelt, dwell, or will dwell with craving cut off and mind inwardly peaceful.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgandiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“So too, Māgandiya, if I were to teach you the Dhamma thus: ‘This is health, this is Nibbāna,’ you might know health and see Nibbāna. And with the arising of the eye (of wisdom) in you, lust for the five aggregates of clinging would be abandoned, and you might think: ‘For a long time indeed I have been deceived, cheated, and fooled by this mind! For I clung to form, I clung to feeling, I clung to perception, I clung to formations, I clung to consciousness. Because of that clinging, there is becoming for me; because of becoming, birth; because of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origin of this whole mass of suffering.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgandiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Therefore, Māgandiya, associate with true persons. By associating with true persons, you will hear the true Dhamma. By hearing the true Dhamma, you will live in accordance with the Dhamma and the proper Dhamma. By living in accordance with the Dhamma and the proper Dhamma, you will know and see for yourself: ‘These are diseases, boils, darts. Here, these diseases, boils, darts are abandoned without remainder. Because clinging ceases in me, becoming ceases; because becoming ceases, birth ceases; because birth ceases, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Thus is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 75 – Māgandiyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Sunakkhatta, I give this simile to make the meaning clear. The meaning here is this: The wound, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for the six sense-bases (phassayatana). The poison, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for ignorance. The dart, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for craving. The probing tool, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for mindfulness. The knife, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for noble wisdom. The surgeon, Sunakkhatta, is a synonym for the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Indeed, Sunakkhatta, a monk who guards himself in regard to the six sense-bases, knowing that ‘Attachment (upadhi) is the root of suffering,’ becomes unattached and liberated by the destruction of attachment. It does not happen that he would still focus his body on attachment or direct his mind to attachment.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 105 – Sunakkhattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn105/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Sunakkhatta, suppose there is a bronze cup of drink, beautiful and fragrant, but mixed with poison. Then a man comes who desires to live, not to die, who desires happiness and loathes suffering. What do you think, Sunakkhatta? Would that man drink from that bronze cup if he knew: ‘If I drink from this, I will meet death or deadly suffering’?”<br>“No, venerable sir.”<br>“So too, Sunakkhatta, a monk should surely guard himself in regard to the six sense-bases. Knowing that ‘Attachment is the root of suffering,’ he becomes unattached and liberated by the destruction of attachment. It does not happen that he would still focus his body on attachment or direct his mind to attachment.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 105 – Sunakkhattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn105/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Sunakkhatta, suppose there is a very poisonous viper. Then a man comes who desires to live, not to die, who desires happiness and loathes suffering. What do you think, Sunakkhatta? Would that man give his hand or his foot to that viper if he knew: ‘If I am bitten by this snake, I will meet death or deadly suffering’?”<br>“No, venerable sir.”<br>“So too, Sunakkhatta, a monk should surely guard himself in regard to the six sense-bases. Knowing that ‘Attachment is the root of suffering,’ he becomes unattached and liberated by the destruction of attachment. It does not happen that he would still focus his body on attachment or direct his mind to attachment.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 105 – Sunakkhattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn105/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Good sirs, what is the pursuit of the past? ‘My eye in the past was such and such, forms were such and such, and consciousness there was bound by desire and lust. Because consciousness is bound by desire and lust, he delights in that. Delighting in that, he pursues the past. My ear in the past … nose … tongue … body … mind in the past was such and such, phenomena were such and such, and consciousness there was bound by desire and lust. Because consciousness is bound by desire and lust, he delights in that. Delighting in that, he pursues the past.’ This, good sirs, is the pursuit of the past.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 133 – Mahākaccānabhaddekarattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn133/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘How, monks, should a monk contemplate so that his consciousness is not distracted or scattered externally, and does not abide internally, and is not agitated by clinging? If his consciousness is not distracted or scattered externally, does not abide internally, and is not agitated by clinging, then there is no arising, origination of suffering regarding future birth, aging, and death.’ Good sirs, how is consciousness distracted and scattered externally? Here, good sirs, when a monk sees a form with the eye, consciousness pursues the sign of form, is tied to the enjoyment of the sign of form, is bound by the fetter of the enjoyment of the sign of form—this is called consciousness distracted and scattered externally. When he hears a sound with the ear … smells an odor with the nose … tastes a flavor with the tongue … feels a touch with the body … cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, consciousness pursues the sign of phenomenon, is tied to the enjoyment of the sign of phenomenon, is bound by the fetter of the enjoyment of the sign of phenomenon—this is called consciousness distracted and scattered externally. Thus, good sirs, is consciousness distracted and scattered externally.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 138 – Uddesavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn138/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure. What five? Forms cognizable by the eye—desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. Sounds cognizable by the ear … Odors cognizable by the nose … Tastes cognizable by the tongue … Tangibles cognizable by the body—desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. These, monks, are the five strands of sensual pleasure. The pleasure and joy that arise dependent on these five strands of sensual pleasure—this is called sensual pleasure, defiled pleasure, worldling’s pleasure, ignoble pleasure. ‘I say that this kind of pleasure should not be pursued, should not be developed, should not be cultivated, should be feared.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 139 – Araṇavibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn139/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, not knowing and not seeing the eye as it actually is; not knowing and not seeing forms … eye-consciousness … eye-contact as it actually is; not knowing and not seeing the feeling—whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant—that arises dependent on eye-contact as it actually is, then he becomes attached to the eye, to forms, to eye-consciousness, to eye-contact. Dependent on eye-contact, the feeling—pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant—arises; he becomes attached to that feeling. When he dwells contemplating gratification, attached, tied, infatuated, the five aggregates of clinging accumulate for the future. And his craving—which leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, delighting here and there—increases. His bodily torments increase, his mental torments increase, his bodily fevers increase, his mental fevers increase, his bodily pains increase, his mental pains increase. He experiences bodily suffering and mental suffering.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 149 – Mahāsaḷāyatanikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn149/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householders, if those wanderers of other sects ask you: ‘By what basis, by what tradition, do you speak of those venerable ones as follows: Surely those venerable ones are free from lust, or are on the path to subduing lust; free from ill-will, or on the path to subduing ill-will; free from delusion, or on the path to subduing delusion?’—when asked thus, householders, you should answer those wanderers of other sects: ‘Those venerable ones dwell in remote lodgings in isolated forests. But in such places there are no forms cognizable by the eye that they could see and then delight in; no sounds cognizable by the ear … no odors cognizable by the nose … no tastes cognizable by the tongue … no tangibles cognizable by the body that they could feel and then delight in. Good sirs, by this basis, by this tradition, we speak of those venerable ones as follows: Surely those venerable ones are free from lust, or are on the path to subduing lust; free from ill-will … free from delusion, or on the path to subduing delusion.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 150 – Nagaravindeyyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn150/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monk, ‘ant-hill’ is a synonym for this body composed of the four great elements, born of father and mother, nourished with rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to rubbing, pressing, breaking, disintegration, dissolution. ‘Smoking by day and blazing by night’—what belongs to daytime work, reflected upon at night—that is ‘smoking by night.’ What, after reflecting at night, is practiced during the day by body, speech, and mind—that is ‘blazing by day.’ ‘Brahmin’ is a synonym for the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. ‘Wise man’ is a synonym for a monk in higher training. ‘Sword’ is a synonym for noble wisdom. ‘Digging up’ is a synonym for arousing effort, striving. ‘Door-bolt’ is a synonym for ignorance; ‘lifting the door-bolt’ means abandoning that ignorance. ‘The wise man, taking the sword, dug up’ is the meaning.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 23 – Vammikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn23/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monk, ‘butcher’s knife’ is a synonym for the five strands of sensual pleasure; ‘lifting the butcher’s knife’ means abandoning these five strands of sensual pleasure. ‘The wise man, taking the sword, dug up’ is the meaning. ‘Piece of meat’ is a synonym for delight and lust; ‘lifting the piece of meat’ means abandoning that delight and lust. ‘The wise man, taking the sword, dug up’ is the meaning. ‘Viper’ is a synonym for a monk who has destroyed the defilements; ‘let the viper be, do not touch the viper, pay homage to the viper’ is the meaning.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 23 – Vammikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn23/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, ‘bait’ is a synonym for the five strands of sensual pleasure. ‘Hunter’ is a synonym for Māra. ‘Hunter’s followers’ are a synonym for Māra’s followers. ‘Herd of deer’ is a synonym for ascetics and brahmins. Here, monks, the first kind of ascetics and brahmins, entering and indulging, eat the bait cast by Māra and the world’s offerings. Having entered and indulged, they eat those foods, become infatuated; from infatuation, they become heedless; from heedlessness, they become subject to Māra’s will among that bait and those offerings. Thus, monks, these first ascetics and brahmins have not escaped Māra’s power.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 25 – Nivāpasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn25/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, monks, the second kind of ascetics and brahmins think: ‘These first ascetics and brahmins, entering and indulging, ate the bait … and have not escaped Māra’s power. Suppose we completely abandon the bait and the world’s offerings, abandon what is fearful, go into the forest and dwell.’ They completely abandon the bait and the world’s offerings, abandon what is fearful, go into the forest and dwell. There they become grass-eaters, millet-eaters, raw-rice eaters, Nivara-seed eaters, crust-eaters, husk-eaters, rice-scum eaters, sesame-seed eaters, grass-eaters, cow-dung eaters, forest roots and fruits eaters, fallen-fruit eaters. At the end of the summer, when water and grass become scarce, their bodies become extremely emaciated. Because their bodies become extremely emaciated, their energy for striving is exhausted. Because their energy is exhausted, their mind’s liberation is exhausted. Because their mind’s liberation is exhausted, they return to the bait cast by Māra and the world’s offerings. There they again enter, indulge, and eat those foods. By entering, indulging, and eating, they become infatuated; from infatuation, heedless; from heedlessness, subject to Māra’s will. Thus, monks, these second ascetics and brahmins have not escaped Māra’s power.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 25 – Nivāpasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn25/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, monks, the third kind of ascetics and brahmins think: ‘Those first ascetics and brahmins … have not escaped Māra’s power. Suppose we make a hiding place near the bait cast by Māra and the world’s offerings. Having made a hiding place, without entering, without indulging, we will eat the bait and the world’s offerings. By not entering, not indulging, we will not become infatuated; not infatuated, we will not become heedless; not heedless, we will not become subject to Māra’s will among that bait and offerings.’ These ascetics and brahmins make a hiding place near the bait and offerings. Having done so, without entering, without indulging, they eat the bait and offerings. Not entering, not indulging, they do not become infatuated; not infatuated, they do not become heedless; not heedless, they do not become subject to Māra’s will. But then they have such wrong views as: ‘The world is eternal; the world is not eternal; the world is finite; the world is infinite …’ Thus, monks, these third ascetics and brahmins have not escaped Māra’s power.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 25 – Nivāpasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn25/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, how is it that Māra and his followers cannot reach? Here, monks, a monk, secluding himself from sensual desires, secluding himself from unwholesome states, enters and dwells in the first jhāna, accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and pleasure born of seclusion. This, monks, is called a monk who has blinded Māra, obliterated Māra’s track, leaving no trace, making Māra unable to find his path. Furthermore, monks, a monk, with the stilling of initial and sustained thought, enters and dwells in the second jhāna, which has internal confidence and unification of mind, without initial and sustained thought, with rapture and pleasure born of concentration. This is called a monk who has blinded Māra, obliterated Māra’s track, leaving no trace, making Māra unable to find his path.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 25 – Nivāpasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn25/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is a monk one who does not bind up the wound? Here, monks, when a monk sees a form with the eye, he grasps the general feature, grasps the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise—he does not restrain that cause, does not guard the eye, does not practice restraint of the eye. When he hears a sound with the ear … smells an odor with the nose … tastes a flavor with the tongue … feels a touch with the body … cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, he grasps the general feature, grasps the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the mind faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise—he does not restrain that cause, does not guard the mind, does not practice restraint of the mind. Thus, monks, is a monk who does not bind up the wound.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 33 – Mahāgopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn33/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, how is a monk one who does not know forms? Here, monks, a monk does not know as it actually is all form, namely the four great elements and form derived from the four great elements. Thus, monks, a monk does not know forms. Monks, how is a monk one who is not skillful in characteristics? Here, monks, a monk does not know as it actually is the fool and the characteristics of a fool, the wise person and the characteristics of a wise person. Thus, monks, a monk is not skillful in characteristics. Monks, how is a monk one who does not remove the eggs of the gadfly? Here, monks, a monk indulges in arisen sensual thoughts; he does not abandon, dispel, end, or destroy them. He indulges in arisen ill-will thoughts … harmful thoughts … evil, unwholesome states that have arisen; he does not abandon, dispel, end, or destroy them. Thus, monks, is a monk who does not remove the eggs of the gadfly.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 33 – Mahāgopālakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn33/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Aggivessana, what is untrained body and untrained mind? Here, Aggivessana, an untaught ordinary person experiences a pleasant feeling. Having felt that pleasant feeling, he lusts after it and falls into lust for pleasure. If that pleasant feeling ceases, and due to its cessation, a painful feeling arises, he sorrows, grieves, laments, beats his breast, and becomes distraught. Aggivessana, that pleasant feeling arises for him and invades his mind and remains because the body is untrained. That painful feeling arises and invades his mind and remains because the mind is untrained. In this manner, for a person in whom either way — pleasant feeling arises and invades his mind because the body is untrained, and painful feeling arises and invades his mind because the mind is untrained — he is one with untrained body and untrained mind.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 36 – Mahāsaccakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn36/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, Aggivessana, is trained body and trained mind? Here, Aggivessana, a well-taught noble disciple experiences a pleasant feeling. Having felt that pleasant feeling, he does not lust after it, does not fall into lust for pleasure. If that pleasant feeling ceases, and due to its cessation, a painful feeling arises, he does not sorrow, grieve, lament, beat his breast, or become distraught. Aggivessana, that pleasant feeling arises for him but does not invade his mind and remain because the body is trained. That painful feeling arises for him but does not invade his mind and remain because the mind is trained. In this manner, for a person in whom either way — pleasant feeling arises and does not invade his mind because the body is trained, and painful feeling arises and does not invade his mind because the mind is trained — he is one with trained body and trained mind.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 36 – Mahāsaccakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn36/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, when the child grows up and his faculties become mature, he enjoys the five strands of sensual pleasure fully: forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing; sounds cognizable by the ear … odors cognizable by the nose … tastes cognizable by the tongue … tangibles cognizable by the body that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. When he sees a form with the eye, he lusts after a pleasing form and dislikes a displeasing form. He dwells with mindfulness not established on the body, with a limited mind. He does not know as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom where those evil, unwholesome states cease without remainder. Thus, in relation to the body, whichever feeling arises — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — he delights in that feeling, welcomes it, and clings to it. Because he delights, welcomes, and clings, delight in sensual pleasure arises. With delight in sensual pleasure, there is clinging. With clinging as condition, becoming; with becoming as condition, birth; with birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Thus is the origin of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 38 – Mahātaṇhāsaṅkhayasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn38/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, how does a monk practice the qualities befitting an ascetic? Here, monks, for a monk, when the mind of sensual desire exists, that sensual desire is abandoned; when the mind of ill-will exists, that ill-will is abandoned; when the mind of anger exists, that anger is abandoned; when the mind of hostility … hypocrisy … spite … envy … stinginess … deceit … fraud … obstinacy … impetuosity … conceit … arrogance … vanity … heedlessness exists, that heedlessness is abandoned … Monks, I say that if he practices the qualities befitting an ascetic, he can abandon the defilements that are stains of an ascetic, blemishes of an ascetic, faults of an ascetic, leading to a plane of misery, to a bad destination, to the taking up of an evil realm. He sees himself cleansed of all those evil, unwholesome states and sees himself liberated. Because he sees himself cleansed of all those evil, unwholesome states and sees himself liberated, gladness arises; from gladness, joy; from joy, the body becomes tranquil; from bodily tranquility, he experiences ease; from ease, the mind becomes concentrated. I say that it is because of inner mental concentration that he practices the qualities befitting an ascetic.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 40 – Cūḷa-Assapurasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn40/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable sir, how does future rebirth occur?” “Venerable sir, when beings are shrouded by ignorance and bound by craving, delighting here and there, thus future rebirth occurs.” “Venerable sir, how does future rebirth not occur?” “Venerable sir, when ignorance is abandoned, knowledge arises, and craving is destroyed, thus future rebirth does not occur.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 43 – Mahāvedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn43/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable sir, what is the first jhāna?” “Here, venerable sir, a monk, secluded from sensual desires, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and dwells in the first jhāna, accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and pleasure born of seclusion. This, venerable sir, is called the first jhāna.” “Venerable sir, how many factors does the first jhāna have?” “Venerable sir, the first jhāna has five factors. Here, a monk in the first jhāna has initial thought, sustained thought, rapture, pleasure, and unification of mind. Thus, venerable sir, the first jhāna has five factors.” “Venerable sir, how many factors does the first jhāna abandon and how many does it possess?” “Venerable sir, the first jhāna abandons five factors and possesses five factors. Here, a monk in the first jhāna has abandoned sensual desire, abandoned ill-will, abandoned sloth and torpor, abandoned restlessness and remorse, abandoned doubt; he possesses initial thought, sustained thought, rapture, pleasure, and unification of mind. Thus, venerable sir, the first jhāna abandons five factors and possesses five factors.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 43 – Mahāvedallasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn43/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is a course of practice that is pleasant in the present but yields painful results in the future? Monks, there are some ascetics and brahmins who hold such a doctrine, such a view: ‘There is no fault in sensual pleasures.’ They indulge in sensual pleasures. Having indulged, at the breakup of the body, after death, they are reborn in a plane of misery, a bad destination, a lower realm, hell. There they experience painful, sharp, severe feelings. They say: ‘Those venerable ascetics and brahmins who see the future danger in sensual pleasures, who speak of the abandoning of sensual pleasures, who describe the full understanding of sensual pleasures—but we, with these sensual pleasures as the cause, as the condition, experience these painful, sharp, severe feelings.’ Monks, this is called a course of practice that is pleasant in the present but yields painful results in the future.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 45 – Cūḷadhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn45/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is a course of practice that is painful in the present but yields pleasant results in the future? Here, monks, a person by nature has strong lust, and he constantly experiences painful and grievous feelings born of lust. By nature he has strong ill-will, and constantly experiences painful and grievous feelings born of ill-will. By nature he has strong delusion, and constantly experiences painful and grievous feelings born of delusion. With pain and grief, with tearful face and crying, he lives the holy life that is fully complete and pure. At the breakup of the body, after death, he is reborn in a good destination, a heavenly world, in this realm. This, monks, is called a course of practice that is painful in the present but yields pleasant results in the future.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 45 – Cūḷadhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn45/en/sujato" },


{ text: `“Monks, suppose there is a bitter gourd mixed with poison. Then a man comes who desires to live, not to die, who desires happiness and loathes suffering. Someone says to him: ‘Good man, this bitter gourd is mixed with poison. If you wish, eat it. While eating, you will not find delight in its color, smell, or taste. After eating, you may meet death or deadly suffering.’ That man might eat it without reflection, without refusal. While eating, he does not find delight in its color, smell, or taste. After eating, he meets death or deadly suffering. Monks, I say that this course of practice is like that simile — namely, a course of practice that is painful in the present and also has painful results in the future.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 46 – Mahādhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn46/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, suppose there is a bronze cup of drinking water that has color, smell, and taste, and that drinking water is mixed with poison. Then a man comes who desires to live, not to die, who desires happiness and loathes suffering. Someone says to him: ‘Good man, this bronze cup of drinking water has color, smell, and taste, and it is mixed with poison. If you wish, drink it. While drinking, you will delight in its color, smell, and taste. After drinking, you may meet death or deadly suffering.’ That man might drink it without reflection, without refusal. While drinking, he delights in its color, smell, and taste. After drinking, he meets death or deadly suffering. Monks, I say that this course of practice is like that simile — namely, a course of practice that is pleasant in the present but has painful results in the future.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 46 – Mahādhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn46/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, suppose there is urine mixed with various medicines. Then a person with jaundice comes, and someone says to him: ‘Good man, this urine is mixed with various medicines. If you wish, drink it. While drinking, you will not delight in its color, smell, or taste. But after drinking, you will be at ease.’ That person might drink it after reflection, without refusal. While drinking, he does not delight in its color, smell, or taste. But after drinking, he is at ease. Monks, I say that this course of practice is like that simile — namely, a course of practice that is painful in the present but has pleasant results in the future.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 46 – Mahādhammasamādānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn46/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, suppose there is a hungry, weak dog at a slaughterhouse. A skilled butcher or his apprentice throws it a bone that has been well-scraped, thoroughly scraped, with no meat left, only smeared with blood. What do you think, householder? Would that dog, by gnawing on that bone — well-scraped, thoroughly scraped, with no meat, only smeared with blood — be able to dispel its hunger and weakness?” “No, venerable sir. Why is that? Because that bone is well-scraped, thoroughly scraped, with no meat, only smeared with blood; the dog would only get weary and distressed.” “So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: ‘The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a bone — of much suffering, much despair, and the peril is even greater.’ Having seen this as it actually is with perfect wisdom, having abandoned the equanimity based on diversity, dependent on diversity, and having cultivated the equanimity based on unity, dependent on unity, where all clinging to the world’s materials is completely abandoned without remainder, he cultivates such equanimity.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, suppose a vulture, a kite, or a hawk seizes a piece of meat and flies up. Then other vultures, kites, or hawks chase after it, attacking and tearing at that piece of meat. What do you think, householder? If that vulture, kite, or hawk does not quickly let go of that piece of meat, would it thereby meet death or deadly suffering?” “Yes, venerable sir.” … “So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: ‘The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a piece of meat — of much suffering, much despair, and the peril is even greater.’ Having seen this as it actually is with perfect wisdom, having abandoned the equanimity based on diversity … he cultivates such equanimity.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, suppose a man carries a blazing grass torch against the wind. What do you think, householder? If that man does not quickly let go of that blazing torch, could it burn his hand, his arm, or some part of his body, and would he thereby meet death or deadly suffering?” “Yes, venerable sir.” … “So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: ‘The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a grass torch — of much suffering, much despair, and the peril is even greater.’ Having seen this as it actually is with perfect wisdom … he cultivates such equanimity.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, suppose there is a pit of glowing embers, deeper than a man’s height, filled with glowing embers that are neither flaming nor smoking. Then a man comes who desires to live, not to die, who desires happiness and loathes suffering. Two strong men grab him by both arms and drag him toward that pit of embers. What do you think, householder? Would that man twist his body this way and that?” “Yes, venerable sir. Why is that? Because he knows: ‘If I fall into this pit of embers, I will thereby meet death or deadly suffering.’” “So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: ‘The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a pit of embers — of much suffering, much despair, and the peril is even greater.’ Having seen this as it actually is with perfect wisdom … he cultivates such equanimity.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, suppose a person borrows goods — luxurious vehicles, fine jewelry and ornaments — and with those borrowed goods he goes through the market, being honored and surrounded by many people. The crowd sees him and says: ‘This person is truly wealthy, and the wealthy enjoy such things.’ But wherever the owners see him, they take back their possessions. What do you think, householder? Is that person’s disguise then ended?” “Yes, venerable sir. Why is that? Because the owners take back their possessions.” … “So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: ‘The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like borrowed goods — of much suffering, much despair, and the peril is even greater.’ Having seen this as it actually is with perfect wisdom … he cultivates such equanimity.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, suppose near a village or town there is a forest grove. In it there is a tree full of ripe fruits, but none have fallen to the ground. Then a man comes, wishing for fruit, seeking fruit, wandering here and there for fruit. He enters that forest, sees that tree full of ripe fruits, and thinks: ‘This tree is full of ripe fruits, but none have fallen. I know how to climb trees. Suppose I climb this tree, eat my fill, and fill my clothes.’ Then he climbs the tree, eats his fill, and fills his clothes. Then a second man comes, wishing for fruit, seeking fruit, wandering here and there for fruit, carrying a sharp axe. He enters that forest, sees that tree full of ripe fruits, and thinks: ‘This tree is full of ripe fruits, but none have fallen. I don’t know how to climb trees. Suppose I cut this tree down at the root, eat my fill, and fill my clothes.’ Then he cuts the tree down at the root. What do you think, householder? If the first man does not climb down quickly, when the tree falls, will it not break his hand, foot, or some part of his body, and will he not thereby meet death or deadly suffering?” “Yes, venerable sir.” “So too, householder, a noble disciple reflects: ‘The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are like a fruit tree — of much suffering, much despair, and the peril is even greater.’ Having seen this as it actually is with perfect wisdom … he cultivates such equanimity.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 54 – Potaliyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Having abandoned sensual desires in the world,<br>Homeless, gone forth into renunciation,<br>Having abandoned sensual desire and existence,<br>That one I call a true brahmin.<br><br>Having abandoned greed and ill-will in the world,<br>Homeless, gone forth into renunciation,<br>Having abandoned ill-will and existence,<br>That one I call a true brahmin.<br><br>Who has abandoned the human yoke<br>And transcended the heavenly yoke,<br>Having abandoned all yokes,<br>Released from all bondage —<br>That one I call a true brahmin.<br><br>Having abandoned pleasure and displeasure,<br>Cooled, without substratum,<br>A hero who has conquered all worlds,<br>Mighty and courageous —<br>That one I call a true brahmin.<br><br>Who fully and truly knows<br>The passing away and rebirth of beings,<br>Not clinging, well-gone, awakened,<br>Attained to perfect enlightenment —<br>That one I call a true brahmin.<br><br>Who has no clinging to the past,<br>The future, or the present,<br>Not clinging, without possessions —<br>That one I call a true brahmin.<br><br>Who knows his former abodes,<br>Sees heavenly and evil destinations,<br>And has attained the destruction of birth —<br>That one I call a true brahmin.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 98 – Vāseṭṭhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn98/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householders, those venerable ascetics and brahmins do not see the peril, the degradation, the defilement of unwholesome states, nor the escape, the benefit, and the purification of wholesome states.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 60 – Apaṇṇakasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn60/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And, Carpenter, how do these unwholesome thoughts arise? Their arising has also been taught. It should be said that they arise from perception. What is perception? There are various perceptions, many and diverse: sensual perception, ill-will perception, harmfulness perception. From these, unwholesome thoughts arise.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 78 – Samaṇamuṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn78/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And, Carpenter, where are these unwholesome thoughts abandoned without remainder? Their abandoning has also been taught. Here, Carpenter, a monk, secluded from sensual desires, secluded from unwholesome states, enters and dwells in the first jhāna, accompanied by initial and sustained thought, with rapture and pleasure born of seclusion. Here, those unwholesome thoughts are abandoned without remainder.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 78 – Samaṇamuṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn78/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And, Carpenter, what is the practice that leads to the abandoning of unwholesome thoughts? Here, a monk awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives so that unarisen evil, unwholesome states do not arise … so that arisen evil, unwholesome states are abandoned … so that unarisen wholesome states arise … so that arisen wholesome states are maintained, not confused, increased, expanded, developed, and fulfilled. Such is the practice that leads to the abandoning of unwholesome thoughts.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 78 – Samaṇamuṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn78/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Carpenter, what are wholesome thoughts? Renunciation thought, non-ill-will thought, harmlessness thought. These, Carpenter, are called wholesome thoughts.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 78 – Samaṇamuṇḍikasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn78/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘The world is deficient, longing, a slave to craving’ — that, great king, is the fourth exposition of the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. Having known, seen, and heard that exposition, I went forth from the household life into homelessness.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Behold this decorated image —<br>A heap of wounds, a collection of sores,<br>Diseased, the object of many lustful thoughts,<br>Nothing stable or permanent here.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Behold this decorated image —<br>A heap of wounds, a collection of sores,<br>Diseased, the object of many lustful thoughts,<br>Nothing stable or permanent here.<br><br>Behold this adorned appearance,<br>With jewels and earrings,<br>A skeleton covered by skin,<br>Made beautiful by clothes.<br><br>The feet are painted with lac and dye,<br>The face is smeared with powder and paste —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.<br><br>The hair is curled in seven rings,<br>The eyes are rubbed with collyrium and rouge —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Like a newly decorated medicine box,<br>This foul body is adorned for the occasion —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.<br><br>The hunter set his trap and snare,<br>The wise deer does not approach,<br>Having eaten the crops, we go our way,<br>Leaving the trapper to lament.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Behold this decorated image —<br>A heap of wounds, a collection of sores,<br>Diseased, the object of many lustful thoughts,<br>Nothing stable or permanent here.<br><br>Behold this adorned appearance,<br>With jewels and earrings,<br>A skeleton covered by skin,<br>Made beautiful by clothes.<br><br>The feet are painted with lac and dye,<br>The face is smeared with powder and paste —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.<br><br>The hair is curled in seven rings,<br>The eyes are rubbed with collyrium and rouge —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.<br><br>Like a newly decorated medicine box,<br>This foul body is adorned for the occasion —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.<br><br>The hunter set his trap and snare,<br>The wise deer does not approach,<br>Having eaten the crops, we go our way,<br>Leaving the trapper to lament.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Behold this adorned appearance,<br>With jewels and earrings,<br>A skeleton covered by skin,<br>Made beautiful by clothes.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The feet are painted with lac and dye,<br>The face is smeared with powder and paste —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The hair is curled in seven rings,<br>The eyes are rubbed with collyrium and rouge —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Like a newly decorated medicine box,<br>This foul body is adorned for the occasion —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>But not one who seeks the far shore.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The hunter set his trap and snare,<br>The wise deer does not approach,<br>Having eaten the crops, we go our way,<br>Leaving the trapper to lament.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Sensual desires are many, sweet, and agreeable,<br>Disquieting the mind in many ways.<br>Seeing the danger in these strands of pleasure,<br>I went forth, great king!<br>Like fruits falling from a tree,<br>Both young and old, when the body breaks,<br>Seeing this, I went forth,<br>The ascetic life is supreme,<br>Great king!`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 82 – Raṭṭhapālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Who once was heedless, but later is not,<br>Illuminates this world like the moon freed from clouds.<br>Whoever stops an evil deed by a wholesome one,<br>Illuminates this world like the moon freed from clouds.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 86 – Aṅgulimālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn86/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The foolish, ignorant person delights in heedlessness,<br>But the wise one guards heedlessness as his greatest treasure.<br>Do not yield to heedlessness, do not yield to sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 86 – Aṅgulimālasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn86/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, sensual pleasures are impermanent, empty, false, of a delusive nature. Monks, this is the mere greeting of a fool built upon deception. Sensual pleasures present and future, perceptions of sensual pleasure present and future — both belong to Māra’s realm, Māra’s domain, Māra’s bait, Māra’s food.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, these evil, unwholesome intentions of sensual desire, ill-will, and agitation are a hindrance for the noble disciple in training. Here, monks, a noble disciple reflects: ‘Sensual pleasures present and future, perceptions of sensual pleasure present and future — both belong to Māra’s realm, Māra’s domain, Māra’s bait, Māra’s food. Suppose I dwell with a mind that is expansive, great, having conquered the world and established the mind’s position. When I dwell with a mind that is expansive, great, having conquered the world and established the mind’s position, then those evil, unwholesome intentions of sensual desire, ill-will, and agitation will not arise; with their abandonment, my mind does not become confined, but rather immeasurable and well-developed.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, monks, a noble disciple reflects: ‘Whatever sensual pleasures present and future, whatever perceptions of sensual pleasure present and future, whatever forms present and future — all are the four great elements and form derived from the four great elements.’ While he practices thus, dwells often thus, his mind becomes serene in that element. With serene mind, he attains the Imperturbable (āneñja) either in this very life or he becomes strongly inclined to wisdom. At the breakup of the body, after death, it is possible that his consciousness, proceeding accordingly, may attain the Imperturbable.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, monks, a noble disciple reflects: ‘Sensual pleasures present and future, perceptions of sensual pleasure present and future, forms present and future, perceptions of forms present and future — both are impermanent. What is impermanent is not fit to delight in, not fit to welcome, not fit to cling to.’ While he practices thus, dwells often thus, his mind becomes serene in that element. With serene mind, he attains the Imperturbable either in this very life or he becomes strongly inclined to wisdom. At the breakup of the body, after death, it is possible that his consciousness, proceeding accordingly, may attain the Imperturbable.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 106 – Āneñjasappāyasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn106/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘Come, monk, guard the sense faculties. When you see a form with the eye, do not grasp the general feature, do not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — restrain that cause, guard the eye, practice restraint of the eye. When you hear a sound with the ear … smell an odor with the nose … taste a flavor with the tongue … feel a touch with the body … cognize a phenomenon with the mind, do not grasp the general feature, do not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the mind faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — restrain that cause, guard the mind, practice restraint of the mind.’”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 107 – Gaṇakamoggallānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn107/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Ānanda, I do not see any form where delight and pleasure are subject to change, alteration, and do not give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Ānanda, he reflects: ‘Those low, vulgar, worldly, ignoble thoughts that are not connected with the goal and do not lead to disenchantment, dispassion, cessation, peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna — such as sensual thoughts, ill-will thoughts, harmfulness thoughts — I will not think those thoughts.’ In this way, he is clearly aware of that.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Ānanda, those noble thoughts that are conducive to progress and lead to the complete destruction of suffering — such as renunciation thoughts, non-ill-will thoughts, harmlessness thoughts — he reflects: ‘I will think these thoughts.’ In this way, he is clearly aware of that.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 122 – Mahāsuññatasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn122/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What benefit could there be, Aggivessana? Prince Jayasenna, living amidst sensual pleasures, enjoying sensual pleasures, being consumed by sensual thoughts, burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, ardently pursuing sensual pleasures — could he know, see, or attain the state that can only be known, seen, attained, or realized through seclusion from sensual pleasures? Such a thing does not occur.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 125 – Dantabhūmisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn125/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Though warned by the divine messengers,<br>Young men remain heedless,<br>They sorrow for a long time,<br>Born in a low state.<br>But the true person here,<br>Warned by the divine messengers,<br>Is never heedless<br>In the noble Dhamma.<br>Seeing fear in clinging,<br>In birth and death,<br>Released from clinging,<br>Birth and death are ended.<br>Attaining security and bliss,<br>Here and now fully extinguished,<br>All enmity and fear —<br>They have overcome all.<br>All pain and sorrow —<br>All are transcended.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 130 – Devadūtasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn130/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Do not pursue the past,<br>Do not long for the future.<br>The past is left behind,<br>The future has not yet come.<br>Only the present Dhamma —<br>See it clearly here and now.<br>Unmoved, unshaken —<br>Knowing this, cultivate it.<br>Make an effort today —<br>Who knows death tomorrow?<br>No one can negotiate<br>With the great army of Death.<br>Living thus ardently,<br>Both day and night untiring —<br>That is called the Sage of the One Night,<br>The peaceful, the calm.`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 131 – Bhaddekarattasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn131/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And craving, previously unknowing — which is of sensual desire, of defilement — that state is abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, unable to arise again in the future. And anger, previously unknowing — which is of ill-will, of fault — that state is abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, unable to arise again in the future. And ignorance, previously unknowing — which is of delusion, of fault — that state is abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, unable to arise again in the future. Therefore, a monk thus attained has attained the supreme peace of the peaceful state. Monks, this is the supreme noble peace — namely, the peace of greed, hatred, and delusion.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 140 – Dhātuvibhaṅgasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn140/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, Sāriputta, a monk should reflect: ‘Have I abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure?’ Sāriputta, if a monk, on reflection, knows: ‘I have not yet abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure,’ then he should strive to abandon them. But if, on reflection, he knows: ‘I have abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure,’ then he should dwell with joy and gladness, training day and night in wholesome states.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 151 – Piṇḍapātapārisuddhisutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn151/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Venerable sir, how did you cross the flood?”<br>- “Friend, by not halting and not straining, I crossed the flood.”<br>- “But how, venerable sir, did you cross the flood by not halting and not straining?”<br>- “When I halted, friend, I sank. When I strained, I was swept away. So, friend, by not halting and not straining, I crossed the flood.”<br>(The deity):<br>After a long time I see<br>A brahmin who is fully extinguished —<br>By not halting, not straining,<br>He has crossed all clinging in the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Venerable sir, do you know the release, the escape, the seclusion for beings?”<br>- “Friend, I know the release, the escape, the seclusion for beings.”<br>- “But how, venerable sir, do you know the release, the escape, the seclusion for beings?”<br>The destruction of delight in renewed existence,<br>The cessation of perception and consciousness,<br>The stilling of feelings —<br>Thus, friend, I know the release,<br>The escape and seclusion<br>For all kinds of beings.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `… Standing to one side, that deity recited this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Life is swept along,<br>Short is the lifespan —<br>To old age we are led,<br>There is no stopping place.<br>Seeing this danger in death,<br>Do meritorious deeds<br>That bring true happiness.<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>Life is swept along,<br>Short is the lifespan —<br>To old age we are led,<br>There is no stopping place.<br>Seeing this danger in death,<br>Seeking peace, abandon worldly hopes.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Those who are intoxicated with states,<br>Bewildered and confused,<br>Led astray into wrong courses,<br>Wandering amidst various views —<br>They sleep on and on,<br>They do not wake up.<br>Now indeed the time has come<br>For them to awaken.<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>Those who are not intoxicated with states,<br>Not bewildered or confused,<br>Not led astray into wrong courses,<br>Wandering amidst various views —<br>They have attained perfect enlightenment,<br>They have fully understood.<br>On the uneven path,<br>They walk evenly.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.8/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Friend, I do not abandon the present to chase after things subject to time. But, friend, I abandon things subject to time to chase after the present. The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are subject to time, of great suffering, of great despair — the peril in them is even greater. This Dhamma is visible here and now, not subject to time, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be directly experienced by the wise.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `… (At Sāvatthi). Standing to one side, that deity recited this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>As if struck by a sword,<br>As if fire blazed on the head —<br>Mindful, a monk should go forth,<br>Abandoning lust for sensual pleasures.<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>As if struck by a sword,<br>As if fire blazed on the head —<br>Mindful, a monk should go forth,<br>Abandoning identity view.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.21/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The inner fetter and the outer fetter —<br>Beings are entangled in these fetters.<br>I ask Gotama about this:<br>Who can escape these fetters?<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>One established in virtue, wise,<br>Developing mind and wisdom,<br>Ardent and discreet —<br>That monk can escape the fetters.<br>One who has abandoned greed,<br>Hatred, and ignorance,<br>The defilement-free arahant —<br>He has escaped the fetters.<br>Where name-and-form is destroyed<br>Without remainder,<br>Where the hindrance and perceptions of form are destroyed —<br>There the fetters are cut.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.23/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Where the mind is restrained,<br>There suffering ends.<br>If the mind is fully restrained,<br>One is fully freed from suffering.<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>One should not restrain the mind<br>Completely in every way.<br>Do not restrain the mind<br>When self-control is attained.<br>Where evil states arise,<br>There one should restrain the mind.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.24/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Four wheels, nine doors,<br>Full of defilement, tied by greed —<br>Mired in mud,<br>O great hero,<br>What will be the future state<br>Of such a human birth?<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>Having cut off delight and bondage,<br>Sensual desire and evil,<br>Having destroyed the root of craving —<br>Such will be his future state.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.29/en/sujato" },


{ text: `Standing to one side, a deity recited this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Among us humans,<br>Sensual pleasures are impermanent.<br>Whoever enjoys them here,<br>Is tied, bound by them.<br>Heedless regarding them,<br>Hard to escape from them —<br>One who cannot escape easily<br>Is conquered by Death.<br>Danger arises from sensual desire,<br>Suffering arises from sensual desire.<br>If sensual desire is subdued,<br>Then danger is subdued,<br>When danger is subdued,<br>Suffering is subdued.<br>The various objects in the world<br>Are not the sensual desires themselves —<br>It is the thought of greed<br>That is the sensual desire of humans.<br>The various objects remain<br>As they are in the world,<br>Therefore the wise<br>Subdue their sensual desires.<br>Abandon anger,<br>Subdue conceit,<br>Overcome all<br>Fetters that bind.<br>Do not cling excessively<br>To that name-and-form —<br>Suffering cannot reach<br>One who has nothing.<br>Give up calculations,<br>Do not chase after false thoughts,<br>Cut off all craving<br>For name-and-form in the world.<br>That one, free from defilements,<br>Without anxiety, without craving —<br>Gods and humans,<br>In this life or the next,<br>In heavenly realms<br>Or any dwelling place,<br>Seeking but not finding<br>The trace of that one —<br>They search but do not see<br>The one thus liberated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.34", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.34/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What gives birth to a person?<br>What always runs about?<br>What undergoes rebirth?<br>What does a person fear?<br>- Craving gives birth to a person,<br>The mind itself always runs about,<br>Beings undergo rebirth,<br>Suffering is what a person fears.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.55/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What gives birth to a person?<br>What always runs about?<br>What undergoes rebirth?<br>Because of what is there no liberation?<br>- Craving gives birth to a person,<br>The mind itself always runs about,<br>Beings undergo rebirth,<br>Because of suffering, there is no liberation.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.56/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What gives birth to a person?<br>What always runs about?<br>What undergoes rebirth?<br>What does a person rely on?<br>- Craving gives birth to a person,<br>The mind itself always runs about,<br>Beings undergo rebirth,<br>Kamma is what a person relies on.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.57/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What is called the wrong path?<br>What destroys day and night?<br>What defiles the holy life?<br>What is a bath without water?<br>- Greed is called the wrong path,<br>Aging destroys day and night,<br>Women defile the holy life,<br>Ensnaring humankind —<br>Austerities and the holy life<br>Are a bath without water.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.58/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What binds the world?<br>What leads the world?<br>By abandoning what thing<br>Is Nibbāna called?<br>- Delight binds the world,<br>Seeking leads the world,<br>By abandoning craving,<br>Is Nibbāna called.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.64/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What fetters the world?<br>What leads the world?<br>By abandoning what thing<br>Are all fetters cut?<br>- Delight fetters the world,<br>Seeking leads the world,<br>By abandoning craving,<br>All fetters are cut.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.65/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What oppresses the world?<br>What envelops the world?<br>What arrow pierces the world?<br>With what is it always smeared?<br>- Death oppresses the world,<br>Aging envelops the world,<br>The arrow of craving pierces the world,<br>With sensual desires it is always smeared.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What hangs up the world?<br>What envelops the world?<br>What closes in the world?<br>Upon what does the world stand?<br>- Craving hangs up the world,<br>Aging envelops the world,<br>Death closes in the world,<br>Upon suffering the world stands.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.67", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.67/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What closes in the world?<br>Upon what does the world stand?<br>What hangs up the world?<br>What envelops the world?<br>- Death closes in the world,<br>Upon suffering the world stands,<br>Craving hangs up the world,<br>Aging envelops the world.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.68/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- What binds the world?<br>By subduing what is one freed?<br>By abandoning what thing<br>Are all bonds destroyed?<br>- Wish binds the world,<br>By subduing sensual desire one is freed,<br>By abandoning wish,<br>All fetters are destroyed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.69/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- Who ages, who does not age?<br>What is called the wrong path?<br>What is an obstacle to the Dhamma?<br>What destroys day and night?<br>What defiles the holy life?<br>What is a bath without water?<br>How many openings in the world<br>Upon which the mind does not dwell?<br>I have come to ask the Blessed One —<br>Please tell me the answers!<br>- Form in beings ages,<br>The name-nature does not age,<br>Greed is called the wrong path,<br>Craving is an obstacle to the Dhamma.<br>Aging destroys day and night,<br>Women defile the holy life —<br>Ensnared in this defilement<br>Are all beings.<br>Austerities and the holy life<br>Are a bath without water.<br>There are six openings in the world<br>Upon which the mind does not dwell:<br>Laziness and heedlessness,<br>Lethargy and lack of self-control,<br>Drowsiness and sloth —<br>These six openings should be<br>Completely abandoned.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.76/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Standing to one side, the deity Tayana recited this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br><br>O brahmin, striving, cut the stream,<br>Abandon and destroy<br>All clinging to sensual desires.<br>Without cutting sensual desires,<br>A sage cannot attain unification of mind.<br>If you do what should be done,<br>Be steadfast and energetic.<br>If a goer-forth is lazy,<br>He scatters even more dust.<br>Not doing is better than doing badly —<br>Doing badly leads to suffering afterward.<br>Having done, do it well —<br>Doing well brings no suffering.<br>Like holding grass the wrong way,<br>It can cut your hand,<br>So too, the ascetic life wrongly practiced<br>Drags one to hell.<br>Any lazy conduct,<br>Any defiled practice,<br>Any evil action in the holy life<br>Does not yield great fruit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.8/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Standing to one side, the deity Candana recited this verse to the Blessed One:<br>How can one cross the flood,<br>Steadfast and persevering day and night?<br>Without stalling, without clinging —<br>Who does not sink in the abyss?<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>One who always has virtue,<br>Wisdom, and is well-concentrated,<br>With aroused energy and strength —<br>That one crosses the hard-to-cross flood.<br>One who has abandoned perception of lust,<br>Who has crossed beyond the fetter of form,<br>Who has destroyed delight and craving for existence —<br>That one does not sink in the abyss.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.15/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Standing to one side, the deity Sudatta recited this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>As if struck by a sword,<br>As if fire blazed on the head —<br>A mindful monk should go forth,<br>Abandoning lust for sensual pleasures.<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>As if struck by a sword,<br>As if fire blazed on the head —<br>A mindful monk should go forth,<br>Abandoning identity view.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Standing to one side, the deity Subrahmā recited this verse to the Blessed One:<br>This mind is always afraid,<br>This mind is always agitated,<br>What is wished does not arise,<br>What is not wished does arise.<br>If there is a way to be without fear,<br>Please tell me what I ask.<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>Apart from enlightenment and austerity,<br>Apart from sense restraint,<br>Apart from abandoning all —<br>I see these things<br>That lead to safety<br>For all beings.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.17/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Standing to one side, the deity Uttara recited this verse in the presence of the Blessed One:<br>Life is swept along,<br>Short is the lifespan —<br>To old age we are led,<br>There is no stopping place.<br>Seeing this danger in death,<br>Do meritorious deeds<br>That bring true happiness.<br><br>Life is swept along,<br>Short is the lifespan —<br>To old age we are led,<br>There is no stopping place.<br>Seeing this danger in death,<br>Seeking peace, abandon worldly hopes.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Four wheels, nine doors,<br>Full of defilement, tied by greed —<br>Mired in mud,<br>O great hero,<br>What will be the future state<br>Of such a human birth?<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>Having cut off delight and bondage,<br>Sensual desire and evil,<br>Having destroyed the root of craving —<br>Such will be his future state.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.28/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then the Blessed One, knowing that it was Māra the Evil One, recited this verse to Māra:<br><br>Whatever forms there are,<br>In this world or the next,<br>With excellent colors,<br>Shining brightly in the sky —<br>All those forms,<br>Praised by Māra,<br>Are just bait cast out<br>To destroy the fish.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn2.30/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Greed, hatred, delusion — these three,<br>Are evil minds for a person,<br>They damage one’s own self,<br>They produce one’s own self,<br>Like the rind and core of a tree,<br>Producing its own fruit.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“That is so, great king. Few are those in the world who, having obtained abundant, great wealth, do not become infatuated, do not become intoxicated, do not fall into heedlessness regarding sensual pleasures, and do not act wrongly toward others. But many are those in the world who, having obtained abundant, great wealth, become infatuated, intoxicated, fall into heedlessness regarding sensual pleasures, and act wrongly toward others.<br><br>Bemused by wealth and sensual pleasures,<br>People are greedy and deluded,<br>In the midst of sensual pleasures,<br>Without clear awareness,<br>They are overly intoxicated,<br>Like a deer unaware of the trap set —<br>Later they suffer,<br>Experiencing the results of evil deeds.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Bemused by wealth and sensual pleasures,<br>People are greedy and deluded,<br>In the midst of sensual pleasures,<br>Without clear awareness,<br>They are overly intoxicated,<br>Like a fish unaware of the trap set —<br>Later they suffer,<br>Experiencing the results of evil deeds.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Sitting down to one side, those monks said to the Blessed One:<br>- Here, venerable sir, King Pasenadi of Kosala has had many people bound. Some are bound with ropes, some with chains, some with shackles.<br><br>Then the Blessed One, understanding the meaning of this, on that occasion recited this verse:<br>The wise say that such binding<br>Is not strong —<br>Binding with iron, with ropes,<br>With wooden shackles —<br>But infatuation with sensual pleasures,<br>With jewels and ornaments,<br>And anxious thoughts<br>Directed toward children and wives —<br>The wise say this binding<br>Is truly strong.<br>Though it drags one down,<br>Subtle and hard to escape,<br>True renunciants cut it in two,<br>Without wishing or longing,<br>Abandoning all sensual pleasures.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.10/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“That is so, great king. That is so, great king. All beings are subject to death, end in death, and do not escape death. Just as, great king, all the pots made by a potter, whether unfired or fired, are subject to breakage, end in breakage, and do not escape breakage — so too, great king, all beings are subject to death, end in death, and do not escape death.<br><br>All beings will die,<br>Life ends with death,<br>According to their kamma they go,<br>Reaping fruits of good and evil —<br>Evil kamma leads to hell,<br>Good kamma to heaven.<br>Therefore do good,<br>Accumulate for the future life,<br>Merits for the future life<br>Are a support for beings.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Great king, there are three things in the world which, when they arise, lead to harm, suffering, and discomfort. What three? Great king, greed is a thing in the world which, when it arises, leads to harm, suffering, and discomfort. Great king, hatred is a thing in the world which, when it arises, leads to harm, suffering, and discomfort. Great king, delusion is a thing in the world which, when it arises, leads to harm, suffering, and discomfort. These three things in the world, when they arise, bring harm, suffering, and discomfort.<br><br>Greed, hatred, delusion — these three,<br>Are evil minds for a person,<br>They damage one’s own self,<br>They produce one’s own self,<br>Like the rind and core of a tree,<br>Producing its own fruit.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.23/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Like a great rocky mountain,<br>Standing up to the sky,<br>Advancing and surrounding,<br>Crushing everything on all sides —<br>So too, aging and death<br>Advance upon beings.<br>Warriors, brahmins, merchants,<br>Workers, outcasts,<br>Those who collect rubbish and feces —<br>No one can escape.<br>All are conquered.<br>No elephant corps,<br>No chariot corps, no infantry,<br>No battle of spells,<br>No battle of wealth<br>Can help one win<br>Against aging and death.<br>Therefore, the wise person,<br>Seeing what is good for oneself,<br>Places faith<br>In the Buddha, Dhamma, and Saṅgha.<br>Whoever by body, speech, and mind<br>Practices in accordance with the Dhamma,<br>Is praised in this life<br>And in the next enjoys heavenly bliss.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 3.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn3.25/en/sujato" },

{ text: `(The Blessed One):<br>I am freed<br>From Māra’s trap,<br>Freed from the bonds of sensual pleasures,<br>Both heavenly and human.<br>I am freed<br>From Māra’s fetter.<br>O Death, you are<br>Defeated.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I am freed from all traps, both heavenly and human. Monks, you too are freed from all traps, both heavenly and human. Monks, wander for the happiness of the many, for the welfare of the many, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, happiness, and welfare of gods and humans. Do not go two by the same road. Monks, teach the Dhamma that is good in the beginning, good in the middle, good in the end, with the meaning and the phrasing. Proclaim the holy life that is utterly perfect and pure. There are beings with little dust in their eyes who, if they do not hear the Dhamma, will decline. They will become those who understand the Dhamma. Monks, I will go to Uruvelā, the town of Senā, to teach the Dhamma.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, short indeed is the lifespan of humans in this world — one must go on to the future. Do good, live the holy life. For nothing that is born is without death. Monks, a long-lived person lives only a hundred years, or a little more or less.<br><br>Human life is short,<br>The good person should be concerned,<br>Live as if the head is on fire —<br>Death will surely come.<br><br>Days and nights pass by,<br>Life span comes to an end,<br>Human life dries up<br>Like a stream in the mountains.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then the Blessed One, knowing “This is Māra the Evil One,” recited this verse to Māra:<br>Forms, sounds, tastes, and smells,<br>And all contacts, all phenomena —<br>These are terrifying things,<br>Bewildering beings in the world.<br>A disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One,<br>Mindful, transcends them all,<br>Transcending Māra’s power,<br>Shining like the sun.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.17/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then Māra, having transformed himself into a brahmin with a large topknot, wearing an antelope skin, old, bent like a rafter, breathing heavily, carrying a udumbara staff, approached those monks. Having approached, he said to them:<br>- “Venerable sirs, you have gone forth too young, in the prime of youth, with black hair, in the bloom of youth, at the early stage of life, without having enjoyed sensual pleasures. Venerable sirs, enjoy human sensual pleasures. Do not abandon the present to chase after what is subject to time.”<br><br>- “Brahmin, we do not abandon the present to chase after what is subject to time. And, brahmin, we abandon what is subject to time to chase after the present. The Blessed One has said that sensual pleasures are subject to time, of great suffering, of great despair — the peril in them is even greater. This Dhamma is visible here and now, not subject to time, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be directly experienced by the wise.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.21/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then the female demon Arati (Discontent) recited this verse to the Blessed One:<br>How does a monk,<br>Living amidst many obstacles,<br>Having crossed the five floods,<br>Strive to cross the sixth?<br>How can he meditate,<br>Amidst many sensual perceptions,<br>So that they remain outside him,<br>Not catching him?<br><br>(The Blessed One):<br>With body tranquilized,<br>With mind well liberated,<br>With no more activities,<br>Mindful, without clinging,<br>Knowing the Dhamma,<br>Without thought, meditating —<br>Without anger, without distraction,<br>Without drowsiness, without laziness —<br>Thus the monk,<br>Living amidst many obstacles,<br>Having crossed the five floods,<br>Strives to cross the sixth.<br>Thus he meditates,<br>Amidst many sensual perceptions,<br>They remain outside him,<br>Not catching him.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 4.25", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn4.25/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The nun Alavikā, knowing “That is Māra,” recited this verse:<br><br>There is an escape in the world —<br>I have realized it through wisdom.<br>O heedless relative (Māra),<br>How could you know that Dhamma?<br>Sensual desires are like swords and spears,<br>The aggregates are a chopping block.<br>What you call sensual pleasure,<br>I call no pleasure at all.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The nun Vijayā, thinking “This is Māra,” recited this verse to Māra:<br><br>Forms, sounds, tastes, smells, contacts —<br>They delude the mind —<br>I return them to you, Māra —<br>I have no need for them.<br>Regarding this impure body,<br>Easily broken and fragile,<br>I am humiliated and ashamed —<br>Craving for sensual desire is destroyed.<br>Those reborn in the form realm,<br>Those aspiring to the formless realm,<br>And those who attain peaceful concentration —<br>Everywhere, darkness is destroyed.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `(Calā):<br>Having been born, one must die,<br>Seeing suffering in birth,<br>Fetters and afflictions —<br>Therefore I do not delight in birth.<br>The Buddha has taught the Dhamma<br>That leads beyond renewed existence,<br>Abolishing all suffering —<br>He has established me in truth.<br>Beings headed for the form realm,<br>Those aspiring to the formless realm,<br>If they do not know cessation,<br>They go to renewed existence.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 5.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn5.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The inner fetter and the outer fetter —<br>Beings are entangled in these fetters.<br>I ask Gotama about this —<br>Who can escape these fetters?<br><br>(The Blessed One)<br>A person established in virtue, wise,<br>Developing mind and wisdom,<br>Ardent and discreet —<br>That monk can escape the fetters.<br>One who has abandoned greed,<br>Hatred, and ignorance,<br>The defilement-free arahant —<br>He has escaped the fetters.<br>Where name-and-form is destroyed<br>Without remainder,<br>Where the hindrance and perceptions of form are destroyed —<br>There the fetters are cut.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 7.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn7.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa, having personally abandoned discontent and aroused satisfaction, on that occasion recited this verse:<br><br>I abandon pleasure and displeasure,<br>All household thoughts,<br>Making no place anywhere<br>That could become a basis for sensual desire.<br>One who has escaped the forest of greed,<br>Escaped all sensual desire,<br>Free from greed, not clinging —<br>He is truly called a monk.<br>Whatever earth element, space element,<br>All the form realm in the world —<br>All things are subject to change,<br>All things are impermanent.<br>Whoever understands this,<br>His conduct is true.<br>Beings are always attached<br>To various attachments —<br>To what they see, hear,<br>Smell, taste, touch.<br>Whoever abandons desire here,<br>With mind undefiled,<br>Not clinging here or there —<br>He is called a sage (muni).<br>Concerning the sixty views<br>Belonging to wrong thoughts —<br>Worldlings cling to them,<br>Grasp and cling.<br>The monk who has no defilements,<br>Speaks no evil words,<br>Clear-minded, always concentrated,<br>Without deceit, careful —<br>Escaped from all craving.<br>The sage who has attained<br>The peaceful state of Nibbāna,<br>Awaiting the time of his end,<br>With mind perfectly still,<br>Serenely passes into Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then the Venerable Vaṅgīsa recited this verse to the Venerable Ānanda:<br>Sensual desire burns me,<br>My mind is on fire.<br>It is good, O disciple of Gotama,<br>Out of compassion,<br>Teach me the Dhamma to extinguish the blaze.<br><br>(Ānanda):<br>It is because of distorted perception<br>That your mind is on fire.<br>Abandon the sign of the beautiful<br>That is connected with sensual desire.<br>See formations as impermanent,<br>Suffering, and not-self —<br>Extinguish great sensual desire,<br>Do not be burned again and again.<br>Develop the mind on foulness,<br>Unified, well-concentrated,<br>Practice mindfulness of the body,<br>Develop much disenchantment.<br>Practice the signless,<br>Destroy the underlying tendency to conceit,<br>And by thoroughly penetrating conceit,<br>Your practice will be at peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 8.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn8.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, shrouded by ignorance and bound by craving, this body of the fool is generated. That ignorance the fool has not abandoned. That craving the fool has not destroyed. Why is that? Monks, the fool does not live the holy life for the complete destruction of suffering. Therefore, with the breakup of the body, after death, the fool goes to another body. Having gone to another body, he is not freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is not freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And, monks, shrouded by ignorance and bound by craving, this body of the wise person is generated. That ignorance the wise person abandons. That craving the wise person destroys. Why is that? Monks, the wise person lives the holy life for the complete destruction of suffering. Therefore, with the breakup of the body, after death, the wise person does not go to another body. Not going to another body, he is freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what one intends, what one plans, and what one has a tendency towards — that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, there is an establishment of consciousness. When consciousness is established and grows, there is a production of future renewed existence. When there is future renewed existence, future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Such is the origin of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.38/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if one does not intend, does not plan, but still has a tendency towards something, that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, there is an establishment of consciousness. When consciousness is established and grows, there is a production of future renewed existence. When there is future renewed existence, future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Such is the origin of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.38/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if one does not intend, does not plan, and has no tendency towards anything, there is no basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is no basis, consciousness does not become established. When consciousness is not established and does not grow, there is no production of future renewed existence. When there is no future renewed existence, future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Such is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.38/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what one intends, what one plans, and what one has a tendency towards — that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, there is an establishment of consciousness. When consciousness is established and grows, there is the descent of name-and-form. With name-and-form as condition, the six sense-bases; with the six sense-bases as condition, contact; with contact as condition, feeling … craving … clinging … existence … birth; aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Such is the origin of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if one does not intend, does not plan but still has a tendency towards something, that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, there is an establishment of consciousness. When consciousness is established and grows, there is the descent of name-and-form. With name-and-form as condition, the six sense-bases … such is the origin of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if one does not intend, does not plan, and has no tendency towards anything, there is no basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is no basis, consciousness does not become established. When consciousness is not established and does not grow, there is no descent of name-and-form. With the cessation of name-and-form, the six sense-bases cease … such is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, monks, a monk reflects, reflects thus: ‘The various sufferings of many kinds that arise in the world, such as aging and death — what is their cause, what is their origin, what gives them birth, what brings them into existence? When what exists does aging and death come to be? When what does not exist does aging and death not come to be?’<br><br>Reflecting thus, he understands: ‘The various sufferings of many kinds that arise in the world, such as aging and death — birth is their cause, birth is their origin, birth gives them birth, birth brings them into existence. When birth exists, aging and death come to be. When birth does not exist, aging and death do not come to be.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, when a monk has abandoned ignorance and aroused true knowledge, then with the abandonment of ignorance and the arising of true knowledge, he does not form any volitional formation, does not generate any kamma. Without forming, without generating, he does not cling to anything in the world. Without clinging, he is not agitated. Without agitation, he personally attains Nibbāna. He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“If he feels a pleasant feeling, he understands that it is impermanent, he understands that it is not to be clung to, he understands that it is not to be delighted in. If he feels a painful feeling … If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he understands that it is impermanent, he understands that it is not to be clung to, he understands that it is not to be delighted in. If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it with a mind free from attachment. If he feels a painful feeling … If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it with a mind free from attachment.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, an untaught ordinary person might become disenchanted, dispassionate, and liberated regarding this body composed of the four great elements. Why is that? Because he sees this body composed of the four great elements increasing and decreasing, being taken up and discarded. Therefore, an untaught ordinary person might become disenchanted, dispassionate, and liberated regarding it. But regarding that which is called mind, intellect, consciousness — here, an untaught ordinary person is not capable of disenchantment, not capable of dispassion, not capable of liberation. Why is that? For a long time, monks, an untaught ordinary person has been attached, regarded as ‘mine,’ grasped at: ‘This is mine, this I am, this is my self.’ Therefore, he is not capable of disenchantment, dispassion, or liberation regarding it.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.61/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, those ascetics or brahmins in the past … in the future … in the present who regard whatever in the world is agreeable and enticing as permanent, as happiness, as healthy, as safe, as self — they increase craving. Those who increase craving, increase attachment. Those who increase attachment, increase suffering. Those who increase suffering are not freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that they are not freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, those ascetics or brahmins in the past … in the future … in the present who regard whatever in the world is agreeable and enticing as impermanent, as suffering, as not-self, as a disease, as fearful — they abandon craving. Those who abandon craving, abandon attachment. Those who abandon attachment, abandon suffering. Those who abandon suffering are freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that they are freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, the form element is the home of consciousness. Consciousness bound by lust for the form element, householder, is called ‘wandering with a home.’ The feeling element is the home of consciousness. Consciousness bound by lust for the feeling element … The perception element … The formation element … The consciousness element is the home of consciousness. Consciousness bound by lust for the consciousness element, householder, is called ‘wandering with a home.’ Thus, householder, is wandering with a home.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, householder, is wandering without a home? Regarding the form element, householder, whatever there is of desire, lust, delight, craving, any engagement and clinging, mental standpoints, attachments, underlying tendencies — the Tathāgata has abandoned them, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, made them non-existent, so that they cannot arise again in the future. Therefore, the Tathāgata is called ‘one who wanders without a home.’ Regarding the feeling element … perception element … formation element … consciousness element — the Tathāgata has abandoned them … Therefore, the Tathāgata is called ‘one who wanders without a home.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What is wandering without a standing place? The bondage of standing and clinging to the sign of forms, householder, has been abandoned by the Tathāgata, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, so that it cannot arise again in the future. Therefore, the Tathāgata is called ‘one who wanders without a standing place.’ The bondage of standing and clinging to the sign of sounds … smells … tastes … touches … phenomena, householder, has been abandoned by the Tathāgata … Therefore, the Tathāgata is called ‘one who wanders without a standing place.’ Thus, householder, is wandering without a standing place.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is the origination of form? What is the origination of feeling? What is the origination of perception? What is the origination of formations? What is the origination of consciousness? Here, monks, a monk delights, welcomes, and remains attached. What does he delight in, welcome, and remain attached to? He delights, welcomes, and remains attached to form. Because of his delight, welcome, and attachment to form, delight in form arises. Because of delight in form, clinging to form arises. With clinging to form as condition, becoming arises; with becoming as condition, birth arises; with birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Such is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.<br><br>He delights, welcomes, and remains attached to feeling … perception … formations … consciousness. Because of his delight, welcome, and attachment to consciousness, delight in consciousness arises. Because of delight in consciousness, clinging to consciousness arises … Such is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. This, monks, is the origination of form, the origination of feeling, the origination of perception, the origination of formations, the origination of consciousness.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is clinging and worry? Here, monks, an untaught ordinary person, not seeing the noble ones, not skilled in the noble Dhamma, not trained in the noble Dhamma, not seeing the true persons, not skilled in the true Dhamma, not trained in the true Dhamma, regards form as self, or self as possessing form, or form as in self, or self as in form. For him, that form changes and alters. Because of the change and alteration of form, his consciousness follows that change in form. Worrying states arise from that consciousness following the change in form, invading his mind and remaining. Because his mind is invaded, he is terrified, distressed, and full of longing and worry.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is non-clinging and non-worry? Here, monks, a well-taught noble disciple regards form as: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ For him, that form changes and alters. When form changes and alters, no sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, or despair arise in him. He regards feeling … perception … formations … consciousness as: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ For him, that consciousness changes and alters. When consciousness changes and alters, no sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, or despair arise in him. Thus, monks, is non-clinging and non-worry.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.8/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, form is impermanent, both in the past and in the future, not to mention the present. Seeing this, monks, a well-taught noble disciple has no regret for past form, does not delight in future form, and practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present form. Feeling is impermanent … Perception is impermanent … Formations are impermanent … Consciousness is impermanent, both in the past and in the future, not to mention the present. Seeing this, monks, a well-taught noble disciple has no regret for past consciousness, does not delight in future consciousness, and practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present consciousness.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, form is suffering, both in the past and in the future, not to mention the present. Seeing this, monks, a well-taught noble disciple has no regret for past form, does not delight in future form, and practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present form. Feeling is suffering … Perception is suffering … Formations are suffering … Consciousness is suffering, both in the past and in the future, not to mention the present. Seeing this, monks, a well-taught noble disciple has no regret for past consciousness, does not delight in future consciousness, and practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present consciousness.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.10/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, form is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it really is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Feeling … Perception … Formations … Consciousness is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it really is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Seeing thus, monks, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form … disenchanted with feeling … disenchanted with perception … disenchanted with formations … disenchanted with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate. Through dispassion, he is liberated. In liberation, there is knowledge: ‘Liberated.’ He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.15/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, form is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it really is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Feeling … Perception … Formations … Consciousness is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it really is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Seeing thus, monks, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form … disenchanted with feeling … disenchanted with perception … disenchanted with formations … disenchanted with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate. Through dispassion, he is liberated … ‘… there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what is the burden? The five aggregates of clinging are the answer. What five? The form aggregate of clinging, the feeling aggregate of clinging, the perception aggregate of clinging, the formation aggregate of clinging, the consciousness aggregate of clinging. This, monks, is called the burden. And what, monks, is the bearer of the burden? The person — the venerable one of such a name and such a clan. This, monks, is called the bearer of the burden. And what, monks, is the taking up of the burden? It is this craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, delighting here and there — that is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence. This, monks, is called the taking up of the burden. And what, monks, is the laying down of the burden? It is the remainderless fading away and cessation of that same craving, the abandoning and relinquishing of it, freedom from it, non-reliance. This, monks, is called the laying down of the burden.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The five aggregates are the burden,<br>The bearer of the burden is the person.<br>Taking up the burden is suffering in the world,<br>Laying down the burden is happiness, free from suffering.<br>Having laid down the heavy burden,<br>One takes up no other burden.<br>Having pulled out craving, root and all,<br>One is free from hunger and thirst,<br>Fully extinguished, at peace.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.22", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.22/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, are the things that should be fully understood? Form, monks, is a thing that should be fully understood; feeling … perception … formations … consciousness is a thing that should be fully understood. These, monks, are the things that should be fully understood. And what, monks, is full understanding? The destruction of greed, the destruction of hatred, the destruction of delusion — this, monks, is called full understanding.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.23/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, before my enlightenment, while I was still a bodhisatta, not yet fully enlightened, I thought: ‘What is the gratification, what is the peril, what is the escape in the case of form? … in the case of feeling? … perception? … formations? … consciousness?’ Then, monks, I thought: ‘The pleasure and joy that arise dependent on form — that is the gratification of form. That form is impermanent, suffering, subject to change — that is the peril of form. The removal and abandonment of desire and lust for form — that is the escape from form.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if there were no gratification in form, beings would not become attached to form. But because there is gratification in form, beings become attached to form. If there were no peril in form, beings would not become disenchanted with form. But because there is peril in form, beings become disenchanted with form. And, monks, as long as beings do not directly know as it actually is the gratification as gratification, the peril as peril, and the escape as escape in regard to these five aggregates of clinging, they have not, monks, escaped from this world with its devas, Māras, Brahmās, with its ascetics and brahmins, with its gods and humans; they are not free from it, not detached, not liberated, their minds are not at ease. But when they directly know these five aggregates … as they actually are, then they have escaped … their minds are at ease.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.28/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, when form is born, subsists, arises, and becomes manifest — that is the birth of suffering, the subsisting of disease, the manifestation of aging and death. When feeling … perception … formations … consciousness is born, subsists, arises, and becomes manifest — that is the birth of suffering, the subsisting of disease, the manifestation of aging and death. When form ceases, subsides, and passes away — that is the cessation of suffering, the subsiding of disease, the passing away of aging and death. When feeling … perception … formations … consciousness ceases, subsides, and passes away — that is the cessation of suffering, the subsiding of disease, the passing away of aging and death.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.30/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I will teach about suffering and the root of suffering. Listen … And what, monks, is suffering? Form, monks, is suffering; feeling is suffering; perception is suffering; formations are suffering; consciousness is suffering. This, monks, is called suffering. And what, monks, is the root of suffering? It is this craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, delighting here and there — that is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.31", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.31/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, whatever is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being. And what, monks, is not yours? Form, monks, is not yours — abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being. Feeling … Perception … Formations … Consciousness is not yours — abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.33/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“For a monk practicing the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma, this is in accordance with the Dhamma: he dwells often in disenchantment toward form, toward feeling, toward perception, toward formations, toward consciousness. Dwelling often in disenchantment toward form … toward consciousness, he fully understands form … feeling … perception … formations … consciousness. By fully understanding them, he is freed from form, freed from feeling, freed from perception, freed from formations, freed from consciousness, freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, knowing form as impermanent … knowing feeling as impermanent … knowing perception as impermanent … knowing formations as impermanent … knowing consciousness as impermanent, changing, fading, ceasing — he sees all consciousness, past and present, as impermanent, suffering, subject to change. Seeing thus with correct wisdom as it actually is, all sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are abandoned. Being abandoned, he does not become distressed. Not being distressed, he dwells at ease. Dwelling at ease, that monk is called ‘one who has stilled all signs and is wholly inclined toward Nibbāna.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.43/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, form is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it really is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Seeing thus with correct wisdom as it actually is, the mind becomes dispassionate and liberated, not grasping the defilements.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.45/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if a monk has a mind that is dispassionate and liberated regarding the form element, not grasping the defilements; regarding the feeling element … perception element … formation element … consciousness element, he has a mind that is dispassionate and liberated, not grasping the defilements. Being liberated, he is firmly established. Being firmly established, he is content. Being content, he is not agitated. Being not agitated, he personally attains Nibbāna. He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.45", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.45/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, form is burning; feeling is burning; perception is burning; formations are burning; consciousness is burning. Seeing thus, monks, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form … with feeling … with perception … with formations … with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate. Through dispassion, he is liberated. In liberation, knowledge arises: ‘Liberated.’ He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.61/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monk, whoever thinks about form is bound by Māra. Whoever does not think about form is freed from the Evil One. Whoever thinks about feeling … perception … formations … consciousness is bound by Māra. Whoever does not think about consciousness is freed from the Evil One. This brief saying of mine, monk, should be understood in detail.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.64/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Rādha, whatever form there is, past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — all form should be seen as it really is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Whatever feeling … perception … formations … consciousness there is, past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — all consciousness should be seen as it really is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Rādha, knowing thus, seeing thus, regarding this conscious body and all external signs, there is no ‘I-making, mine-making, or underlying tendency to conceit.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.71", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.71/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, why is it called form? It is deformed (ruppati), monks, therefore it is called form. Deformed by what? Deformed by cold, deformed by heat, deformed by hunger, deformed by thirst, deformed by contact with flies, mosquitoes, wind, heat, and serpents. It is deformed, monks, therefore it is called form. And why, monks, is it called feeling? It feels (vedeti), monks, therefore it is called feeling. What does it feel? It feels pleasure, it feels pain, it feels neither-pain-nor-pleasure. It feels, monks, therefore it is called feeling. And why, monks, is it called perception? It perceives (sañjānāti), monks, therefore it is called perception. What does it perceive? It perceives blue, it perceives yellow, it perceives red, it perceives white. It perceives, monks, therefore it is called perception.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.79/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, monks, a well-taught noble disciple reflects: ‘Now I am being overwhelmed by form. In the past, I was also overwhelmed by form just as I am now being overwhelmed by present form. If I were to delight in future form, then in the future I would be overwhelmed by form just as I am now being overwhelmed by present form.’ Reflecting thus, he has no regret for past form, no delight in future form, and practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding present form.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.79", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.79/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Thus, monks, a clansman goes forth. He has desire for sensual pleasures, ardent craving, a mind of ill-will, defiled thoughts, lacking mindfulness, not clearly comprehending, not concentrated, with distracted mind, with uncontrolled faculties. Monks, like a charnel-fire brand that is burning at both ends and smeared with feces in the middle, not used as fuel in the village nor in the forest — with that simile, I describe that person, who has lost both the householder’s enjoyment and the goal of the ascetic life.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.80/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these three unwholesome thoughts: sensual thought, ill-will thought, harmful thought. And these three unwholesome thoughts are abandoned without remainder in one whose mind is well established in the four foundations of mindfulness or who develops the signless concentration. Monks, develop the signless concentration well. When the signless concentration is developed and cultivated, it brings great fruit and great benefit.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.80", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.80/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, for an untaught ordinary person, contacted by feeling born of contact with ignorance, craving arises. From that craving, volitional formation arises. Thus, monks, that formation is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That craving is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That feeling is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That contact is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. That ignorance is impermanent, conditioned, dependently arisen. Monks, knowing thus, seeing thus, the defilements are immediately destroyed.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.81", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.81/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, suppose the Ganges river carries along a great pile of foam. A person with good eyesight would look at it, reflect, and examine it. Looking, reflecting, examining, the foam would appear empty, hollow, insubstantial. For what substance could there be in a pile of foam? So too, monks, whatever form there is, past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near — a monk sees form, reflects, examines it. Seeing, reflecting, examining, form appears empty, hollow, insubstantial. For what substance could there be in form?”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.95/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Form is like a lump of foam,<br>Feeling like a water bubble,<br>Perception like a mirage,<br>Formations like a banana tree,<br>Consciousness like a magic trick —<br>So taught the Kinsman of the Sun.<br><br>If one reflects appropriately,<br>And rightly examines,<br>Seeing things as they really are,<br>Emptiness is clearly seen.<br><br>Beginning with this body,<br>As taught by the Great Sage,<br>When three things are abandoned,<br>Form is seen as discarded.<br><br>This body is discarded, unaware,<br>Not feeling, just heat and consciousness —<br>When thrown away, it lies,<br>Food for others.<br><br>This continuous body,<br>A magic trick, said the fool,<br>Is called a murderer —<br>No core can be found.<br><br>Thus should a monk contemplate the aggregates,<br>Ardent,<br>Both by day and by night,<br>Mindful and clearly comprehending.<br><br>He should abandon all fetters,<br>Make a refuge for himself,<br>Live as if his head were on fire,<br>Aspiring to the imperturbable state.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.95/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there is no form that is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change, that will remain forever. There is no feeling … perception … formation … consciousness that is permanent, everlasting, eternal, not subject to change, that will remain forever.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.98/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, this saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning. A first point cannot be discerned of beings wandering and roaming on, shrouded by ignorance and bound by craving. It is possible, monks, that the great ocean might dry up, be exhausted, and cease to exist. But I say that beings shrouded by ignorance and bound by craving, wandering and roaming on, will not have made an end of suffering. It is possible, monks, that Sineru, the king of mountains, might be destroyed and cease to exist. But I say that beings shrouded by ignorance … will not have made an end of suffering. It is possible, monks, that the great earth might be destroyed and cease to exist. But I say that beings shrouded by ignorance and bound by craving, wandering and roaming on, will not have made an end of suffering!”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.99/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, this saṃsāra is without discoverable beginning. A first point cannot be discerned of beings wandering and roaming on, shrouded by ignorance and bound by craving. Monks, suppose a dog was tied by a leash to a strong post or pillar. If it walks, it walks close to that post or pillar. If it stands, it stands close to that post or pillar. If it sits, it sits close to that post or pillar. If it lies down, it lies down close to that post or pillar. So too, monks, an untaught ordinary person regards form as: ‘This is mine, this I am, this is my self.’ He regards feeling … perception … formations … consciousness as: ‘This is mine, this I am, this is my self.’ If he walks, he walks close to these five aggregates of clinging. If he stands, he stands close to them. If he sits, he sits close to them. If he lies down, he lies close to them. Therefore, monks, one should constantly reflect on one’s own mind thus: ‘For a long time, this mind has been defiled by greed, hatred, and delusion. Through the defilement of the mind, beings are defiled. Through the purification of the mind, beings are purified.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.100/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, have you seen a painting called ‘The Wandering One’?” “Yes, venerable sir.” “Monks, that painting was created by the mind. Yet the mind is even more diverse than that painting. Therefore, monks, one should constantly reflect on one’s own mind thus: ‘For a long time, this mind has been defiled by greed, hatred, and delusion. Through the defilement of the mind, beings are defiled. Through the purification of the mind, beings are purified.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.100/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I do not see any other class of things that is as diverse as the mind. Those beings in the animal realm — such beings are diverse because of their minds. Therefore, monks, one should constantly reflect on one’s own mind thus: ‘For a long time, this mind has been defiled by greed, hatred, and delusion. Through the defilement of the mind, beings are defiled. Through the purification of the mind, beings are purified.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.100", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.100/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if a monk lives without ardor in his practice, though he may wish: ‘May my mind be liberated from the defilements without clinging,’ yet his mind is not liberated from the defilements without clinging. Why is that? It is because he has not developed. Not developed what? He has not developed the four foundations of mindfulness. He has not developed the four right efforts. He has not developed the four bases of spiritual power. He has not developed the five faculties. He has not developed the five powers. He has not developed the seven factors of enlightenment. He has not developed the Noble Eightfold Path.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.101/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“By developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence, all lust for sensual pleasures is abandoned, all lust for form is abandoned, all lust for existence is abandoned, all ignorance is abandoned, all conceit ‘I am’ is abandoned. Monks, just as a farmer in autumn, using a large plow, cuts through all the roots while plowing — so too, by developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence … all conceit ‘I am’ is abandoned. Monks, just as a grass-cutter cuts down grass, takes it by the top, shakes it up and down, left and right, and then throws it away — so too, by developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence … all conceit ‘I am’ is abandoned. Monks, just as when a bunch of mangoes is cut from its stalk, all the mangoes that were attached to the stalk are cut off with it — so too, by developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence … all conceit ‘I am’ is abandoned.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.102/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as in the autumn, when the sky is clear and free of clouds, the sun, rising in the sky, dispels all darkness from space, shines, glows, and blazes — so too, by developing and cultivating the perception of impermanence, all lust for sensual pleasures is abandoned, all lust for form is abandoned, all lust for existence is abandoned, all ignorance is abandoned, all conceit ‘I am’ is abandoned. And how, monks, is the perception of impermanence developed and cultivated so that … all conceit ‘I am’ is abandoned? ‘This is form, this is the arising of form, this is the cessation of form. This is feeling … this is perception … these are formations … this is consciousness, this is the arising of consciousness, this is the cessation of consciousness.’ It is when the perception of impermanence is developed and cultivated in this way, monks, that all lust for sensual pleasures is abandoned … all conceit ‘I am’ is abandoned.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.102", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.102/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I will teach you about suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the path leading to the cessation of suffering. Listen. And what, monks, is suffering? It should be said: the five aggregates of clinging. What five? The form aggregate of clinging … the consciousness aggregate of clinging. This, monks, is called suffering. And what, monks, is the origin of suffering? It is this craving that leads to renewed existence … craving for non-existence. This, monks, is called the origin of suffering. And what, monks, is the cessation of suffering? It is the remainderless fading away and cessation of that same craving, the abandoning and relinquishing of it, freedom from it, non-reliance. This, monks, is called the cessation of suffering. And what, monks, is the path leading to the cessation of suffering? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view … right concentration. This, monks, is called the path leading to the cessation of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.104", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.104/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I will teach you about things that are bound and about binding. Listen. And what, monks, are the things that are bound? What is binding? Form, monks, is a thing that is bound. Desire and lust for form is the binding of form. Feeling … Perception … Formations … Consciousness, monks, is a thing that is bound. Desire and lust for consciousness is the binding of consciousness. These, monks, are called the things that are bound. This is the binding.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.120/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Venerable Sāriputta, what things should a virtuous monk attend to wisely?” - “Venerable Koṭṭhika, a virtuous monk should attend wisely to the five aggregates of clinging as impermanent, as suffering, as a disease, as a boil, as a dart, as misery, as an affliction, as alien, as disintegrating, as empty, as not-self. What five? The form aggregate of clinging, the feeling aggregate of clinging, the perception aggregate of clinging, the formation aggregate of clinging, the consciousness aggregate of clinging. Venerable Koṭṭhika, a virtuous monk should attend wisely to these five aggregates of clinging as impermanent … as not-self.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.122", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.122/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘Ignorance, ignorance,’ venerable sir, is said. What, venerable sir, is ignorance? And to what extent is one called ignorant?” - “Here, monk, an untaught ordinary person does not know as it actually is: ‘Form is subject to origination’ as form is subject to origination; he does not know as it actually is: ‘Form is subject to cessation’ as form is subject to cessation; he does not know as it actually is: ‘Form is subject to origination and cessation’ as form is subject to origination and cessation. This, monk, is called ignorance. And to that extent one is called ignorant.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.126", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.126/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Form is a lump of glowing ember, monks! Feeling is a lump of glowing ember! Perception is a lump of glowing ember! Formations are lumps of glowing ember! Consciousness is a lump of glowing ember! Seeing thus, monks, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form, disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perception, disenchanted with formations, disenchanted with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate. Through dispassion, he is liberated. In liberation, knowledge arises: ‘Liberated.’ He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.136/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, whatever is impermanent, you should abandon your desire for it. And what, monks, is impermanent? Form, monks, is impermanent … Feeling … Perception … Formations … Consciousness is impermanent — there you should abandon your desire. Whatever is impermanent, monks, there you should abandon your desire.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.137", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.137/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, for a clansman who has gone forth out of faith, this is the Dhamma in accordance with the Dhamma: dwell often in disenchantment toward form … toward feeling … toward perception … toward formations, dwell often in disenchantment toward consciousness. One who dwells often in disenchantment toward form … toward consciousness fully understands form … feeling … perception … formations … fully understands consciousness. One who fully understands form, fully understands feeling, fully understands perception, fully understands formations, fully understands consciousness, is freed from form, freed from feeling, freed from perception, freed from formations, freed from consciousness, freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.146", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.146/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Venerable sir, right view — for what purpose is it?” - “Right view, Rādha, is for the purpose of disenchantment.” - “Venerable sir, disenchantment — for what purpose is it?” - “Disenchantment, Rādha, is for the purpose of dispassion.” - “Venerable sir, dispassion — for what purpose is it?” - “Dispassion, Rādha, is for the purpose of liberation.” - “Venerable sir, liberation — for what purpose is it?” - “Liberation, Rādha, is for the purpose of Nibbāna.” - “Venerable sir, Nibbāna — for what purpose is it?” - “Rādha, you have gone beyond the range of this question. For the purpose of entering Nibbāna, Rādha, is the holy life lived; Nibbāna is its final goal, Nibbāna is its end.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“If there is form, Rādha, then there is death, or a killer, or being killed. Therefore, Rādha, you should see form as death, see it as a killer, see it as being killed, see it as a disease, see it as a boil, see it as a dart, see it as misery, see it as its own misery. One who sees form thus sees rightly.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Suppose, Rādha, young boys or girls are playing with sandcastles. As long as their desire, lust, love, thirst, passion, and craving for those sandcastles are not fully abandoned, they still cling to them, delight in them, treasure them, and are attached to them. But when their desire, lust, love, thirst, passion, and craving for those sandcastles are fully abandoned, then they smash them, scatter them, demolish them with their hands and feet and no longer play with them. So too, Rādha, you should smash, scatter, demolish form and not play with it, being intent on the destruction of craving for form. The destruction of craving, Rādha, is Nibbāna.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘A being, a being,’ venerable sir, is said. To what extent, venerable sir, is one called a being?” - “Rādha, whatever desire, lust, delight, craving there is for form — entanglement there, immersion there — thus one is called a being. For feeling … perception … formations … for consciousness — entanglement there, immersion there — thus one is called a being.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘The destruction of the cord of continued existence, the destruction of the cord of continued existence,’ venerable sir, is said. What, venerable sir, is the cord of continued existence? What is the destruction of the cord of continued existence?” - “Rādha, whatever desire, lust, delight, craving, any engagement and clinging, any mental standpoints, attachments, underlying tendencies there are regarding form — that is called the cord of continued existence. Their destruction is the destruction of the cord of continued existence. Regarding feeling … perception … formations … Regarding consciousness, whatever desire, lust, delight, craving, any engagement and clinging, any mental standpoints, attachments, underlying tendencies there are — that is called the cord of continued existence. Their destruction is the destruction of the cord of continued existence.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Rādha, whatever desire, lust, delight, craving there is for form — abandon it. Thus that form will be abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, so that it cannot arise again in the future. Regarding feeling … perception … formations … Rādha, whatever desire, lust, delight, craving there is for consciousness — abandon it. Thus that consciousness will be abandoned, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, so that it cannot arise again in the future.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the arising, the continuation, the production, the manifestation of the eye is the arising of suffering, the continuation of disease, the manifestation of aging and death. The arising … of the ear … of the nose … of the tongue … of the body … of the mind is the arising of suffering, the continuation of disease, the manifestation of aging and death. The cessation, the stilling, the ending of the eye is the cessation of suffering, the stilling of disease, the ending of aging and death. The cessation … of the ear … of the nose … of the tongue … of the body … of the mind is the cessation of suffering, the stilling of disease, the ending of aging and death.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 26.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn26.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, desire and lust for the eye is a defilement of the mind. Desire and lust for the ear … for the nose … for the tongue … for the body … for the mind is a defilement of the mind. When a monk has abandoned these defilements in regard to these six sense bases, his mind inclines to renunciation. Having been fully saturated with renunciation, his mind becomes wieldy and he directly knows the things to be fully known.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 27.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn27.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, one who delights in forms delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. One who delights in sounds … in odors … in tastes … in touches … One who delights in phenomena delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. One who does not delight in forms, monks, does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering. One who does not delight in sounds … odors … tastes … touches … One who does not delight in phenomena does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the eye is burning. Forms are burning. Eye-consciousness is burning. Eye-contact is burning. Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact — whether pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is burning. Burning with what? Burning with the fire of greed, the fire of hatred, the fire of delusion. I say it is burning with birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. The ear … The nose … The tongue is burning. Tastes are burning. Tongue-consciousness is burning. Tongue-contact is burning … The body … The mind is burning. Phenomena are burning. Mind-consciousness is burning. Mind-contact is burning. Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact … that feeling is burning. Burning with the fire of greed, the fire of hatred, the fire of delusion. I say it is burning with birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.28", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.28/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “How, venerable sir, should one know, how should one see, so that ignorance is abandoned and true knowledge arises?” - “Monk, knowing and seeing the eye as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and true knowledge arises. Knowing and seeing forms as impermanent … eye-consciousness … eye-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact … knowing and seeing that feeling as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and true knowledge arises. The ear … The nose … The tongue … The body … Knowing and seeing the mind as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and true knowledge arises. Phenomena … mind-consciousness … mind-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact … knowing and seeing that feeling as impermanent, ignorance is abandoned and true knowledge arises. Knowing thus, seeing thus, monks, ignorance is abandoned and true knowledge arises.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.53/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the Dhamma leading to the full understanding of all clinging? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling. Seeing thus, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with the eye, with forms, with eye-consciousness, with eye-contact, with feeling. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate. Through dispassion, he is liberated. By being liberated, he knows: ‘I have fully understood clinging.’ Dependent on the ear and sounds … on the nose and odors … on the tongue and tastes … on the body and touches … Dependent on the mind and phenomena, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling. Seeing thus, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with the mind, with phenomena, with mind-consciousness, with mind-contact, with feeling. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate. Through dispassion, he is liberated. By being liberated, he knows: ‘I have fully understood clinging.’ This, monks, is the Dhamma leading to the full understanding of all clinging.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.60/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Migajāla, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk delights in them, praises them, and dwells with lust for them, then because he delights, praises, and dwells with lust, delight arises. With the arising of delight, lust arises. With the arising of lust, bondage arises. Bound by the bondage of delight, Migajāla, that monk is called ‘one who dwells with a companion.’ Even if he lives in remote lodgings, in forests, in groves, in quiet places, with little sound, little noise, free from people’s breath, secluded, suitable for seclusion — still he is called ‘one who dwells with a companion.’ Why? Because craving, the companion, has not been abandoned by him. Therefore he is called ‘one who dwells with a companion.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And, Migajāla, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable … enticing. If a monk does not delight in them, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them, then because he does not delight, does not praise, and dwells without lust, delight ceases. With the cessation of delight, lust ceases. With the cessation of lust, bondage ceases. Not being bound by the bondage of delight, Migajāla, that monk is called ‘one who dwells alone.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Migajāla, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable … enticing. If a monk does not delight in them, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them, then delight ceases. With the cessation of delight, lust ceases. With the cessation of lust, bondage ceases. Not being bound by the bondage of delight, Migajāla, that monk is called ‘one who dwells alone.’ Even if he lives in the midst of a village crowded with monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, kings, royal ministers, ascetics of other sects and their disciples — still he is called ‘one who dwells alone.’ Why? Because craving, the companion, has been abandoned by him. Therefore he is called ‘one who dwells alone.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Migajāla, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk delights in them, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — because of that, delight arises. Migajāla, I say that with the arising of delight, suffering arises. Sounds … Odors … Tastes … Touches … Migajāla, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind … If a monk delights in them, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — because of that, delight arises. Migajāla, I say that with the arising of delight, suffering arises.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.64/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Migajāla, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable … enticing. If a monk does not delight in them, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them — then delight ceases. Migajāla, I say that with the cessation of delight, suffering ceases. Sounds … Odors … Tastes … Touches … Migajāla, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind … If a monk does not delight in them, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them — then delight ceases. Migajāla, I say that with the cessation of delight, suffering ceases.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.64", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.64/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘Visible here and now, visible here and now (sanditthiko),’ venerable sir, is said. To what extent, venerable sir, is the Dhamma visible here and now, immediate, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be directly experienced by the wise?” - “Here, Upavāna, having seen a form with the eye, a monk experiences the form but does not experience lust for the form, and there is no inner lust for forms. He knows: ‘There is no inner lust for forms in me.’ As long as, Upavāna, having seen a form with the eye, a monk experiences the form but does not experience lust for the form, and there is no inner lust for forms — he knows that — thus, Upavāna, the Dhamma is visible here and now, immediate, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be directly experienced by the wise.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.70/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Venerable sir, I do not understand the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One regarding the purpose of purity of virtue.” - “Monk, if you do not understand the Dhamma I have taught regarding the purpose of purity of virtue, then how, monk, do you understand the Dhamma I have taught?” - “Venerable sir, I understand the Dhamma taught by the Blessed One as greed and the removal of greed.” - “Good, good, monk! Good, monk! You understand the Dhamma taught by me as greed and the removal of greed. It is for the purpose of greed and the removal of greed, monk, that the Dhamma is taught by me. What do you think, monk: Is the eye permanent or impermanent?” - “Impermanent, venerable sir.” - “The ear … The nose … The tongue … The body … Is the mind permanent or impermanent?” - “Impermanent, venerable sir.” - “What is impermanent — is that suffering or happiness?” - “Suffering, venerable sir.” - “What is impermanent, suffering, subject to change — is it fitting to regard it as: ‘This is mine, this I am, this is my self’?” - “No, venerable sir.” - “Seeing thus, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with the eye … disenchanted with the mind … Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate … He knows: ‘… there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.74/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Sitting down to one side, the Venerable Rādha said to the Blessed One: “Good, venerable sir, if the Blessed One would teach me the Dhamma in brief. Having heard the Dhamma from the Blessed One, I will dwell alone, secluded, heedful, ardent, and resolute.” - “Rādha, whatever is impermanent — there you should abandon your desire. And what, Rādha, is impermanent? The eye, Rādha, is impermanent — there you should abandon your desire. Forms are impermanent … Eye-consciousness … Eye-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is impermanent. There you should abandon your desire. The ear … The nose … The tongue … The body … The mind is impermanent — there you should abandon your desire. Phenomena … Mind-consciousness … Mind-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is impermanent. There you should abandon your desire. Whatever is impermanent, Rādha — there you should abandon your desire.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.76/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Rādha, whatever is suffering — there you should abandon your desire. And what, Rādha, is suffering? The eye, Rādha, is suffering — there you should abandon your desire. Forms … Eye-consciousness … Eye-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact … that feeling is suffering. There you should abandon your desire. The ear … The nose … The tongue … The body … The mind … Phenomena … Mind-consciousness … Mind-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact … that feeling is suffering. There you should abandon your desire. Whatever is suffering, Rādha — there you should abandon your desire.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.77/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘Empty is the world, empty is the world,’ venerable sir, is said. To what extent, venerable sir, is it said that the world is empty?” - “Ānanda, because the world is empty of self and anything belonging to self, therefore it is said that the world is empty. And what, Ānanda, is empty of self and anything belonging to self? The eye, Ānanda, is empty of self and anything belonging to self. Forms are empty of self and anything belonging to self. Eye-consciousness … Eye-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact … that feeling is empty of self and anything belonging to self. The ear … The nose … The tongue … The body … The mind … Phenomena … Mind-consciousness … Mind-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact … that feeling is empty of self and anything belonging to self. And because it is empty of self and anything belonging to self, Ānanda, it is said that the world is empty.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.85/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, defilement is a disease; defilement is a boil; defilement is a dart. Therefore, monks, the Tathāgata dwells without defilement, free from the dart. Therefore, monks, if any monk has a wish, let him wish to dwell without defilement, free from the dart. Do not conceive about the eye, do not conceive in the eye, do not conceive from the eye, do not conceive ‘the eye is mine.’ Do not conceive about forms … Do not conceive about eye-consciousness … Do not conceive about eye-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact … do not conceive about that feeling, do not conceive in it, do not conceive from it, do not conceive ‘that feeling is mine.’ Do not conceive about everything, do not conceive in everything, do not conceive from everything, do not conceive ‘everything is mine.’ Not conceiving thus, he does not cling to anything in the world. Not clinging, he is not agitated. Not agitated, he personally attains Nibbāna. He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.90/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these six sense bases — unguarded, unprotected, unguarded, unrestrained — bring suffering. What six? The eye sense base, monks — unguarded, unprotected, unguarded, unrestrained — brings suffering. The ear … The nose … The tongue … The body … The mind sense base, monks — unguarded, unprotected, unguarded, unrestrained — brings suffering. These six sense bases, monks — unguarded, unprotected, unguarded, unrestrained — bring suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.94/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these six sense bases — well-guarded, well-protected, well-guarded, well-restrained — bring happiness. What six? The eye sense base, monks — well-guarded, well-protected, well-guarded, well-restrained — brings happiness. The ear … The nose … The tongue … The body … The mind sense base, monks — well-guarded, well-protected, well-guarded, well-restrained — brings happiness. These six sense bases, monks — well-guarded, well-protected, well-guarded, well-restrained — bring happiness.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.94/en/sujato" },

{ text: `O monks, these six sense bases —<br>Where they are unrestrained,<br>There suffering comes to be.<br>Those who learn to guard them,<br>To restrain and protect them,<br>With faith as their companion,<br>Dwell freed from sensual lust.<br><br>Seeing forms that are pleasing,<br>Seeing forms that are displeasing,<br>Restrain the path of lust<br>For forms that are pleasing —<br>Do not let the mind be defiled,<br>Thinking: ‘I do not delight in forms.’<br><br>Having heard sounds —<br>Pleasing and displeasing,<br>Do not be infatuated with pleasing sounds.<br>Restrain the mind’s aversion<br>For sounds that are displeasing,<br>Do not let the mind be defiled,<br>Thinking: ‘I do not delight in sounds.’<br><br>Having smelled fragrant, delightful odors,<br>Having smelled foul, loathsome odors —<br>Restrain aversion for loathsome odors,<br>And for delightful ones,<br>Do not let desire dominate.<br><br>Having tasted sweet flavors,<br>And also flavors that are not sweet,<br>Do not develop greed<br>When enjoying a sweet taste,<br>Do not utter words of opposition<br>When tasting what is not sweet.<br><br>When touched by pleasant contact,<br>Do not be infatuated with lust;<br>When touched by painful contact,<br>Do not be violently shaken.<br>For both contacts — pleasant and painful —<br>Remain equanimous,<br>Without approval or opposition,<br>Whatever contact may arise.<br><br>Those who follow proliferated perceptions,<br>Who are lost in conceptual proliferation,<br>Who act upon false thoughts —<br>Abandon all household activities<br>Born of the mind,<br>Practice restraint in your actions,<br>Directing yourself to the path of seclusion.<br><br>Thus, with the mind well-developed<br>Regarding these six sense bases,<br>Whatever contact occurs,<br>The mind is not disturbed.<br>Having subdued both greed and hatred,<br>O monk, go to the far shore,<br>Beyond the bonds of birth and death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.94", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.94/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “What do you think, Mālukyaputta? Regarding forms cognizable by the eye that you have not seen, never saw before, do not see now, and do not wish to see — do you have any desire, lust, or craving for them?” - “No, venerable sir.” - “Regarding sounds cognizable by the ear … odors cognizable by the nose … tastes cognizable by the tongue … touches cognizable by the body that you have not felt, never felt before, do not feel now, and do not wish to feel — do you have any desire, lust, or craving for them?” - “No, venerable sir.”<br><br>Seeing a form, if one’s mind is infatuated,<br>Attending to a pleasing sign,<br>The mind is attached to the feeling,<br>Clinging to the form remains.<br>His feelings increase,<br>Manyfold, born from form —<br>Greed and hurtful thoughts<br>Harm his mind.<br>Thus accumulating suffering,<br>He is said to be far from Nibbāna.<br><br>Hearing a sound, mind infatuated …<br>Smelling an odor …<br>Tasting a flavor …<br>If one’s mind is infatuated,<br>Attending to a pleasing sign,<br>The mind attached to the feeling,<br>Clinging to the flavor remains.<br>His feelings increase,<br>Manyfold, born from flavor —<br>Greed and hurtful thoughts<br>Harm his mind.<br>Thus accumulating suffering,<br>He is said to be far from Nibbāna.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.95/en/sujato" },

{ text: `One who does not lust for forms,<br>Seeing a form, does not cling,<br>His mind does not adhere to the feeling,<br>He does not remain attached to forms.<br>As he sees forms,<br>Feeling feelings accordingly,<br>It wanes away, not accumulated —<br>Thus mindful he practices.<br>Thus suffering is not stored up,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>One who does not lust for sounds,<br>Hearing a sound, does not cling …<br>One who does not lust for odors,<br>Smelling an odor, does not cling …<br>One who does not lust for tastes,<br>Tasting a flavor, does not cling …<br>One who does not lust for touches,<br>Feeling a touch, does not cling …`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.95/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is dwelling heedfully? If one lives without restraint of the eye faculty, monks, his mind is defiled by forms cognizable by the eye. For one with a defiled mind, there is no gladness. Without gladness, there is no rapture. Without rapture, there is no tranquility. Without tranquility, suffering remains. For one who is suffering, the mind does not become concentrated. When the mind is not concentrated, phenomena are not clearly seen. When phenomena are not clearly seen, he is called ‘one who dwells heedfully’ … the ear faculty … the nose faculty … the tongue faculty … the body faculty … If one lives without restraint of the mind faculty, his mind is defiled by phenomena cognizable by the mind. For one with a defiled mind, there is no gladness … he is called ‘one who dwells heedfully.’ Thus, monks, is dwelling heedfully.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.97", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.97/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is dwelling heedfully? If one lives with restraint of the eye faculty, monks, his mind is not defiled by forms cognizable by the eye. For one with an undefiled mind, gladness arises. With gladness, rapture arises. With rapture, the body becomes tranquil. With a tranquil body, he experiences ease. For one at ease, the mind becomes concentrated. When the mind is concentrated, phenomena are clearly seen. When phenomena are clearly seen, he is called ‘one who dwells heedfully’ … the ear faculty … the nose faculty … the tongue faculty … the body faculty … If one lives with restraint of the mind faculty, his mind is not defiled by phenomena cognizable by the mind. For one with an undefiled mind, gladness arises … he is called ‘one who dwells heedfully.’ Thus, monks, is dwelling heedfully.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.97", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.97/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is non-restraint? Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk delights in those forms, praises them, and dwells with lust for them, then that monk, monks, should understand: ‘I have fallen away from wholesome states.’ The Tathāgata calls this ‘falling away.’ … There are sounds cognizable by the ear … odors … tastes … touches … There are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable … enticing. If a monk delights in those phenomena, praises them, and dwells with lust for them, then that monk should understand: ‘I have fallen away from wholesome states.’ The Tathāgata calls this ‘falling away.’ Thus, monks, is non-restraint.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.98/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is restraint? Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable … enticing. If a monk does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them, then that monk, monks, should understand: ‘I have not fallen away from wholesome states.’ The Tathāgata calls this ‘not falling away.’ … There are sounds … odors … tastes … touches … There are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable … enticing. If a monk does not delight in those phenomena, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them, then that monk should understand: ‘I have not fallen away from wholesome states.’ The Tathāgata calls this ‘not falling away.’ Thus, monks, is restraint.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.98/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, whatever is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being. And what, monks, is not yours? The eye, monks, is not yours — abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being. Forms are not yours — abandon them. Eye-consciousness is not yours — abandon it. Eye-contact is not yours — abandon it. Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is not yours. Abandon it. The ear … The nose … The tongue … The body … The mind is not yours — abandon it. Phenomena are not yours — abandon them. Mind-consciousness is not yours — abandon it. Mind-contact is not yours — abandon it. Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is not yours. Abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.101/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the origin of suffering? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling. With feeling as condition, craving. This is the origin of suffering. Dependent on the ear … on the nose … on the tongue … on the body … Dependent on the mind and phenomena, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling. With feeling as condition, craving. This, monks, is the origin of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.106", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.106/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the cessation of suffering? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling. With feeling as condition, craving. But with the remainderless fading away and cessation of that same craving, clinging ceases. With the cessation of clinging, existence ceases. With the cessation of existence, birth ceases. With the cessation of birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair cease. Such is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering. This is the cessation of suffering. Dependent on the ear … on the nose … on the tongue … on the body … Dependent on the mind and phenomena, mind-consciousness arises … With the cessation of craving, clinging ceases … Such is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering. This is the cessation of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.106", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.106/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the origination of the world? Dependent on the eye and forms, eye-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling. With feeling as condition, craving. With craving as condition, clinging. With clinging as condition, existence. With existence as condition, birth. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. This is the origination of the world. Dependent on the ear … on the nose … on the tongue … on the body … Dependent on the mind and phenomena, mind-consciousness arises. The meeting of the three is contact. With contact as condition, feeling. With feeling as condition, craving. With craving as condition, clinging. With clinging as condition, existence. With existence as condition, birth. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. This, monks, is the origination of the world.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.107", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.107/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk delights in those forms, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — then, monks, this is called a monk who has gone into Māra’s domain, who has come under Māra’s control. Māra’s net has surrounded him. Bound by Māra, he is subject to the Evil One’s will … Monks, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable … enticing. If a monk delights in those phenomena, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — then, monks, this is called a monk who has gone into Māra’s domain, who has come under Māra’s control. Māra’s net has surrounded him. Bound by Māra, he is subject to the Evil One’s will.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.114/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, before my enlightenment, while I was still a bodhisatta, not yet fully enlightened, I thought: ‘The five strands of sensual pleasure that this mind formerly experienced — now past, ceased, changed — regarding them, my mind becomes inflamed when they are present, and diminishes when they are future, not yet attained.’ Then, monks, I thought: ‘The five strands of sensual pleasure that this mind formerly experienced — now past, ceased, changed — regarding them, for my own benefit, I will dwell heedful, protecting my mind with mindfulness.’ Therefore, monks, regarding the five strands of sensual pleasure that your minds formerly experienced — now past, ceased, changed — your minds become inflamed when they are present, and diminish when they are future, not yet attained. Therefore, monks, regarding the five strands of sensual pleasure that your minds formerly experienced — now past, ceased, changed — for your own benefit, dwell heedful, protecting your minds with mindfulness.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.117/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And, lord of gods, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them — then, because he does not delight, does not praise, and dwells without lust, not depending on them, consciousness arises without clinging to them. Without clinging, lord of gods, that monk attains Nibbāna. There are sounds cognizable by the ear … odors … tastes … touches … Lord of gods, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable … enticing. If a monk does not delight in those phenomena, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them — then, because he does not delight, does not praise, and dwells without lust, not depending on them, consciousness arises without clinging to them. Without clinging, lord of gods, that monk attains Nibbāna. This, lord of gods, is the cause, this is the reason why some beings here and now attain Nibbāna.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.118", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.118/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Sitting down to one side, that monk said to the Venerable Sāriputta: “Venerable Sāriputta, a monk who is my companion has abandoned the training and returned to the lower life.” - “That comes to be, friend, for one who does not guard the sense faculties, does not know moderation in eating, and is not committed to wakefulness. For such a person, it is impossible that he would continue the perfectly pure holy life for his whole life. Friend, a monk who does guard the sense faculties, knows moderation in eating, and is committed to wakefulness — it is possible that he would continue the perfectly pure holy life for his whole life. Therefore, friend, you should train thus: ‘We will guard the sense faculties, know moderation in eating, and be committed to wakefulness.’ Thus, friend, you should train.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.120/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, friend, does one guard the sense faculties? Here, friend, when a monk sees a form with the eye, he does not grasp the general feature, does not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — he restrains that cause, guards the eye, practices restraint of the eye. When he hears a sound with the ear … smells an odor with the nose … tastes a flavor with the tongue … feels a touch with the body … cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, he does not grasp the general feature, does not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the mind faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — he restrains that cause, guards the mind, practices restraint of the mind. Thus, friend, is the guarding of the sense faculties.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.120/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Venerable Bharadvāja, what is the cause, what is the reason why these young monks, youthful, with black hair, endowed with the blessing of youth, in the prime of life, do not indulge in sensual pleasures and live the perfectly pure holy life for their whole life, completing it fully?” - “Great king, the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, has said: ‘Come, monks, regarding those who are like mothers, establish a mother’s mind. Regarding those who are like sisters, establish a sister’s mind. Regarding those who are like daughters, establish a daughter’s mind.’ This, great king, is the cause, this is the reason why these young monks … live the holy life completely.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.127", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.127/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Lust, Venerable Bharadvāja, is the mind. Sometimes, even toward those who are like mothers, lust arises. Toward those like sisters, lust arises. Toward those like daughters, lust arises. Bharadvāja, is there another cause, another reason why these young monks … live the holy life completely?” - “Great king, the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, has said: ‘Come, monks, contemplate this body from the soles of the feet upward, from the top of the head downward, enclosed by skin and full of various impurities. In this body there are: head hairs, body hairs, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, intestinal mesentery, stomach, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, skin oil, saliva, snot, synovial fluid, urine.’ This, great king, is the cause, this is the reason why these young monks live the perfectly pure holy life for their whole life, completing it fully.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.127", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.127/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Wonderful, Venerable Bharadvāja! Marvelous, Venerable Bharadvāja! This is well spoken by the Blessed One, the Knower, the Seer, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One. This very cause, this very reason, Venerable Bharadvāja, is why these young monks, youthful, with black hair, endowed with the blessing of youth, in the prime of life, do not indulge in sensual pleasures and live the perfectly pure holy life for their whole life, completing it fully. I too, Venerable Bharadvāja, when I enter the inner apartments with body unguarded, speech unguarded, mind unguarded, mindfulness unestablished, sense faculties unrestrained — then lust overcomes me. But, Venerable Bharadvāja, when I enter the inner apartments with body guarded, speech guarded, mind guarded, mindfulness established, sense faculties restrained — then lust does not overcome me.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.127", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.127/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk delights in those forms, praises them, and dwells with lust for them, depending on them, consciousness arises with clinging to them. Householder, a monk who has clinging does not attain complete Nibbāna … Households, there are tastes cognizable by the tongue … Householder, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable … enticing. If a monk delights in those phenomena, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — because he delights, praises, and dwells with lust, depending on them, consciousness arises with clinging to them. Having clinging, householder, that monk does not attain Nibbāna. This, householder, is the cause, this is the reason why some beings here and now do not attain complete Nibbāna.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.124", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.124/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them, not depending on them, consciousness arises without clinging to them. Householder, a monk without clinging attains complete Nibbāna … Householder, there are tastes … Householder, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable … enticing. If a monk does not delight in those phenomena, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them — because he does not delight, does not praise, and dwells without lust, not depending on them, consciousness arises without clinging to them. Without clinging, householder, that monk attains Nibbāna. This, householder, is the cause, this is the reason why some beings here and now attain complete Nibbāna.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.124", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.124/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, a jackal saw a tortoise from afar and approached it. Having approached, it stood to one side and thought: ‘When this tortoise stretches out any of its limbs or its neck, I will seize it right there, break it, and eat it.’ But, monks, because the tortoise did not stretch out any limb or its neck, the jackal became disenchanted with the tortoise and left, not having gained an opportunity. So too, monks, Māra constantly and relentlessly stands in ambush for you, thinking: ‘Perhaps I can gain an opportunity through the eye … through the tongue … through the mind.’ Therefore, monks, guard the sense faculties. When you see a form with the eye, do not grasp the general feature, do not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — restrain that cause, guard the eye, practice restraint of the eye. When you hear a sound … smell an odor … taste a flavor … feel a touch … cognize a phenomenon with the mind, do not grasp the general feature, do not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the mind faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — restrain that cause, guard the mind, practice restraint of the mind. Monks, when you live guarding the sense faculties, Māra will become disenchanted with you and leave, not gaining an opportunity, just like the jackal with the tortoise.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.240", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.240/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Venerable Kaccāna, ‘guarding the sense faculties, guarding the sense faculties’ is said. To what extent, Venerable Kaccāna, is there guarding of the sense faculties?” - “Here, brahmin, when a person sees a form with the eye, his mind inclines toward agreeable forms and recoils from disagreeable forms. He dwells with mindfulness unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not know as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not abandoned without remainder. When he hears a sound … smells an odor … tastes a flavor … feels a touch … cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, his mind inclines toward agreeable phenomena and recoils from disagreeable phenomena. He dwells with mindfulness unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not know as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not abandoned without remainder. Thus, brahmin, there is non-guarding of the sense faculties.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.132", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.132/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Wonderful, Venerable Kaccāna! Marvelous, Venerable Kaccāna! The way Venerable Kaccāna has defined non-guarding of the sense faculties is excellent. Venerable Kaccāna has spoken of ‘guarding of the sense faculties, guarding of the sense faculties.’ To what extent, Venerable Kaccāna, is there guarding of the sense faculties?” - “Here, brahmin, a monk, when seeing a form with the eye, his mind does not incline toward agreeable forms nor recoil from disagreeable forms. He dwells with mindfulness established, with an immeasurable mind. He knows as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are abandoned without remainder. When he hears a sound … smells an odor … tastes a flavor … feels a touch … cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, his mind does not incline toward agreeable phenomena nor recoil from disagreeable phenomena. He dwells with mindfulness established, with an immeasurable mind. He knows as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Therefore, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are abandoned without remainder. Thus, brahmin, is the guarding of the sense faculties.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.132", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.132/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are agreeable and disagreeable. Though they touch the mind again and again, they do not overpower the mind and remain. Because the mind is not overpowered, energy and exertion arise, not laziness; mindfulness is established, not lost; the body becomes tranquil, not feverish; the mind becomes concentrated and one-pointed. Seeing this fruit of heedfulness, monks, regarding these monks, I declare that one should strive heedfully with regard to the six sense bases. Monks, there are sounds … odors … tastes … touches … Monks, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are agreeable and disagreeable. Though they touch the mind again and again, they do not overpower the mind and remain. Because the mind is not overpowered, energy and exertion arise, not laziness; mindfulness is established, not lost; the body becomes tranquil, not feverish; the mind becomes concentrated and one-pointed. Seeing this fruit of heedfulness, monks, regarding these monks, I declare that one should strive heedfully with regard to the six sense bases.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.134", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.134/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, devas and humans delight in form, are excited by form. When form changes, fades, and ceases, monks, devas and humans dwell in suffering. They delight in sound … in odor … in taste … in touch … Monks, devas and humans delight in phenomena, are excited by phenomena. When phenomena change, fade, and cease, monks, devas and humans dwell in suffering. Monks, the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One, having directly known as they actually are the origination, the cessation, the gratification, the peril, and the escape in regard to form, does not delight in form, does not cherish form, is not excited by form. When form changes, fades, and ceases, monks, the Tathāgata dwells at ease. He does not delight in sound … in odor … in taste … in touch … Having directly known as they actually are the origination, the cessation, the gratification, the peril, and the escape in regard to phenomena, the Tathāgata does not delight in phenomena, does not cherish them, is not excited by them. When phenomena change, fade, and cease, the Tathāgata dwells at ease.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.136/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Forms, sounds, tastes, odors, touches,<br>And all phenomena —<br>Desirable, delightful, agreeable —<br>Thus they are called.<br><br>Devas and humans in the world,<br>Regarding them as delightful —<br>Where they cease and fade away,<br>Devas and humans see suffering.<br><br>The noble one sees as ease<br>When identity view is destroyed —<br>The noble one sees as opposite<br>All the views of the world.<br><br>What others call pleasure,<br>The noble call suffering.<br>What others call suffering,<br>The noble know as pleasure.<br><br>See the Dhamma, hard to comprehend,<br>Where the ignorant are bewildered —<br>Darkness for the blind,<br>Obscurity for those who cannot see.<br><br>For the good person with open eyes,<br>Light is clearly seen —<br>Living close, they know clearly,<br>Skilled in the great Dhamma.<br><br>Overcome by the thirst of birth,<br>Swept away by the current of existence,<br>Subject to Māra’s control —<br>They do not awaken to this Dhamma.<br><br>Apart from the noble ones, no one<br>Awakens to this path —<br>The path leading to Nibbāna,<br>With perfect wisdom, free from defilements.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.136/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. This, monks, is not called the ocean in the noble one’s discipline. Here, this world with its devas, Māras, and Brahmās, with its ascetics and brahmins, with its gods and humans, for the most part is submerged in them, tangled like a ball of thread, covered like a tangled skein, become like a tangled grass rope, unable to pass beyond the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, saṃsāra. Monks, there are sounds … odors … tastes … touches … Monks, there are phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. This, monks, is not called the ocean in the noble one’s discipline. Here, this world … for the most part is submerged in them … unable to pass beyond the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, saṃsāra.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.229", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.229/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, good sirs, is one defiled by sensual lust? Here, good sirs, when a monk sees a form with the eye, he is attached to agreeable forms and repelled by disagreeable forms. He dwells with bodily mindfulness unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not know as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Here, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not abandoned without remainder. When he tastes a flavor with the tongue … When he cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, he is attached to agreeable phenomena and repelled by disagreeable phenomena. He dwells with bodily mindfulness unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not know as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Here, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not abandoned without remainder. This, good sirs, is called a monk who is defiled by sensual lust regarding forms cognizable by the eye … regarding tastes … regarding phenomena cognizable by the mind. A monk living thus, good sirs, if Māra approaches him through the eye, Māra gains an opportunity, Māra gains an object. If Māra approaches him through the tongue … through the mind, Māra gains an opportunity, Māra gains an object.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.243", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.243/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, good sirs, is one not defiled by sensual lust? Here, good sirs, when a monk sees a form with the eye, he is not attached to agreeable forms nor repelled by disagreeable forms. He dwells with bodily mindfulness established, with an immeasurable mind. He knows as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Here, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are abandoned without remainder. When he tastes a flavor with the tongue … When he cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, he is not attached to agreeable phenomena nor repelled by disagreeable phenomena. He dwells with bodily mindfulness established, with an immeasurable mind. He knows as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Here, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are abandoned without remainder. This, good sirs, is called a monk who is not defiled by sensual lust regarding forms … regarding tastes … regarding phenomena. A monk living thus, good sirs, if Māra approaches him through the eye, Māra does not gain an opportunity, Māra does not gain an object. If Māra approaches him through the tongue … through the mind, Māra does not gain an opportunity, Māra does not gain an object.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.243", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.243/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is a monk one who sees sensual pleasures? When sensual pleasures are seen, then desire, lust for sensual pleasure, infatuation with sensual pleasure, and fever of sensual pleasure have no underlying tendency regarding sensual pleasures. Suppose, monks, there is a pit of glowing embers deeper than a man’s height, filled with glowing embers that are neither flaming nor smoking. Then a man comes who desires to live, not to die, who desires happiness and loathes suffering. Two strong men grab him by both arms and drag him toward that pit. He twists his body this way and that. Why? Because he knows: ‘I will fall into this pit of embers. Because of this, I will meet death or deadly suffering.’ So too, monks, a monk sees sensual pleasures as a pit of embers. And one who sees sensual pleasures thus has no desire, lust, infatuation, or fever for sensual pleasures as an underlying tendency.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.244", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.244/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is there non-restraint? Here, monks, when a monk sees a form with the eye, he is attached to agreeable forms and repelled by disagreeable forms. He dwells with bodily mindfulness unestablished, with a limited mind. He does not know as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Here, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are not abandoned without remainder. Thus, monks, is non-restraint.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.244", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.244/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is there restraint? Here, monks, when a monk sees a form with the eye, he is not attached to agreeable forms nor repelled by disagreeable forms. He dwells with bodily mindfulness established, with an immeasurable mind. He knows as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Here, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are abandoned without remainder. When he tastes a flavor … When he cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, he is not attached to agreeable phenomena nor repelled by disagreeable phenomena. He dwells with bodily mindfulness established, with an immeasurable mind. He knows as it actually is the liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom. Here, evil, unwholesome states that have arisen are abandoned without remainder. Thus, monks, is restraint.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.244", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.244/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these three feelings. What three? Pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. Pleasant feeling, monks, should be seen as suffering. Painful feeling should be seen as a dart. Neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling should be seen as impermanent. When, monks, a monk sees pleasant feeling as suffering, sees painful feeling as a dart, sees neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling as impermanent — then, monks, he is called a monk who has right view, who has cut off craving, who has destroyed the fetters. By thoroughly breaking through conceit, he has made an end of suffering.<br><br>One who sees pleasure as suffering,<br>And sees pain as a dart,<br>Sees the neutral feeling<br>As impermanent —<br>That monk sees rightly,<br>Fully understanding feelings.<br><br>Having fully understood feelings,<br>He is defilement-free in this very life.<br>At the breaking of the body, that Dhamma-abider,<br>The great sage, is beyond measure.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, suppose a man is struck by an arrow, and then they strike him with a second arrow. Thus, monks, that man experiences the feeling of both arrows. So too, monks, an untaught ordinary person, when touched by a painful feeling, sorrows, grieves, laments, beats his breast, and becomes distraught. He experiences two feelings — a bodily feeling and a mental feeling. Touched by that painful feeling, he feels aversion. Because he feels aversion toward that painful feeling, the underlying tendency to aversion toward painful feeling persists. Touched by that painful feeling, he delights in sensual pleasures. Why? Because, monks, the untaught ordinary person knows no escape from painful feeling other than sensual pleasure. Delighting in sensual pleasure, the underlying tendency to greed for pleasant feeling persists. He does not know as it actually is the origination, the cessation, the gratification, the peril, and the escape regarding these feelings. Not knowing as it actually is the origination … and escape regarding these feelings, the underlying tendency to ignorance regarding neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling persists. If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is bound. If he feels a painful feeling, he feels it as one who is bound. If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is bound. This, monks, is called an untaught ordinary person who is bound by birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is bound by suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Suppose, monks, a man is struck by a single arrow. They do not strike him with a second arrow. Thus, monks, that man experiences the feeling of one arrow. So too, monks, a well-taught noble disciple, when touched by a painful feeling, does not sorrow, grieve, lament, beat his breast, or become distraught. He experiences one feeling — a bodily feeling, not a mental feeling. Touched by that painful feeling, he does not feel aversion. Because he does not feel aversion toward that painful feeling, the underlying tendency to aversion toward painful feeling does not persist. Touched by that painful feeling, he does not delight in sensual pleasures. Why? Because, monks, the well-taught noble disciple knows an escape from painful feeling other than sensual pleasure. Not delighting in sensual pleasure, the underlying tendency to greed for pleasant feeling does not persist. He knows as it actually is the origination, the cessation, the gratification, the peril, and the escape regarding these feelings. Because he knows … the underlying tendency to ignorance regarding neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling does not persist. If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is not bound. If he feels a painful feeling, he feels it as one who is not bound. If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is not bound. This, monks, is called a well-taught noble disciple who is not bound by birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is not bound by suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“If he feels a pleasant feeling, he understands: ‘It is impermanent.’ He understands: ‘I am not attached to it.’ He understands: ‘I do not delight in it.’ If he feels a painful feeling … If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he understands: ‘It is impermanent.’ He understands: ‘I am not attached to it.’ He understands: ‘I do not delight in it.’ If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is not bound. If he feels a painful feeling, he feels it as one who is not bound. If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is not bound. When he feels a feeling ending with the body, he understands: ‘I feel a feeling ending with the body.’ When he feels a feeling ending with life, he understands: ‘I feel a feeling ending with life.’ He understands: ‘With the breakup of the body, after death, everything that is felt, in which he no longer delights, will become cool right here.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“There are these two extremes that one who has gone forth should not pursue: devotion to sensual pleasure in sensual objects — low, vulgar, worldly, ignoble, unbeneficial; and devotion to self-mortification — painful, ignoble, unbeneficial. Avoiding these two extremes, the Middle Way has been realized by the Tathāgata, giving rise to vision, giving rise to knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna.<br><br>And what, headman, is that Middle Way realized by the Tathāgata, giving rise to vision, giving rise to knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration. This, headman, is the Middle Way realized by the Tathāgata, giving rise to vision, giving rise to knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 42.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn42.12/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable Gotama, I have a perplexity and doubt: ‘How should one understand the Dhamma of the ascetic Gotama?’” - “Vaccha, your perplexity is enough, your doubt is enough. It is on this point that perplexity and doubt have arisen. I declare the rebirth of one who has clinging, Vaccha, not of one who has no clinging. Just as, Vaccha, a fire burns when there is fuel, not when there is no fuel. So too, Vaccha, I declare rebirth for one who has clinging, not for one who has no clinging.” - “Venerable Gotama, when the wind blows a fire far away, what does Venerable Gotama declare as the fuel for that fire?” - “Vaccha, when the wind blows a fire far away, I say that the wind is its fuel. At that time, Vaccha, the wind is the fuel (upādāna).” - “Venerable Gotama, when a being gives up this body and is reborn in another body, what does Venerable Gotama declare as the fuel for that being?” - “Vaccha, when a being gives up this body and is reborn in another body, I declare that at that time craving (taṇhā) is the fuel (upādāna).”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 44.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn44.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“When ignorance leads the way, monks, for the attainment of unwholesome states, then lack of conscience and lack of fear of wrongdoing follow. For one overwhelmed by ignorance and without wisdom, monks, wrong view arises. For one with wrong view, wrong intention arises. For one with wrong intention, wrong speech arises. For one with wrong speech, wrong action arises. For one with wrong action, wrong livelihood arises. For one with wrong livelihood, wrong effort arises. For one with wrong effort, wrong mindfulness arises. For one with wrong mindfulness, wrong concentration arises.<br><br>When true knowledge leads the way, monks, for the attainment of wholesome states, then conscience and fear of wrongdoing follow. For one with true knowledge and wisdom, monks, right view arises. For one with right view, right intention arises. For one with right intention, right speech arises. For one with right speech, right action arises. For one with right action, right livelihood arises. For one with right livelihood, right effort arises. For one with right effort, right mindfulness arises. For one with right mindfulness, right concentration arises.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is right effort? Here, monks, a monk awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the non-arising of unarisen evil, unwholesome states. He awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the abandoning of arisen evil, unwholesome states. He awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the arising of unarisen wholesome states. He awakens desire, makes effort, arouses energy, applies his mind, and strives for the continuance, non-disappearance, strengthening, increase, development, and fulfillment of arisen wholesome states. This, monks, is called right effort.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.8/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monk, I say that there are these three feelings: pleasant feeling, painful feeling, neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling. These three feelings have been spoken of by me. But, monk, I also say: ‘Whatever is felt is included in suffering.’ It is in relation to the impermanence of formations that this is said: ‘Whatever is felt is included in suffering.’ It is in relation to the nature of destruction, the nature of vanishing, the nature of fading away, the nature of cessation, the nature of change of formations that this is said: ‘Whatever is felt is included in suffering.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 36.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn36.11/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“So too, venerable sirs, the eye is not the bondage of forms, nor are forms the bondage of the eye. Whatever desire and lust arises in dependence on both — that is the bondage there. The ear is not the bondage of sounds … The nose is not the bondage of odors … The tongue is not the bondage of tastes … The body is not the bondage of touches … The mind is not the bondage of phenomena, nor are phenomena the bondage of the mind. Whatever desire and lust arises in dependence on both — that is the bondage there.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 41.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn41.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Just as, monks, this body subsists in dependence on food, with food as condition it stands; without food it does not stand. So too, monks, the five hindrances subsist in dependence on food, with food as condition they stand; without food they do not stand. And what, monks, is the food for the arising of unarisen sensual desire, and for the growth and increase of arisen sensual desire? There is, monks, the sign of the beautiful. Frequent unwise attention to it — this is the food for the arising of unarisen sensual desire, and for the growth and increase of arisen sensual desire.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the defilements of gold — because of which gold becomes defiled, not malleable, not wieldy, not radiant, brittle, and not properly workable — likewise, monks, there are these five defilements of the mind because of which the mind becomes defiled, not malleable, not wieldy, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the defilements. What five? Sensual desire, monks, is a defilement of the mind. Because of this defilement, the mind becomes defiled, not malleable, not wieldy, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the defilements. Ill-will … sloth and torpor … restlessness and remorse … doubt are defilements of the mind. These, monks, are the five defilements of the mind. Because of these defilements, the mind becomes not malleable, not wieldy, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the defilements.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.33", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.33/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, here a clansman, abandoning sensual pleasures, goes forth from the household life into homelessness. But because of those sensual pleasures, or other sensual pleasures worse than those, he is destroyed, ruined, falls, lies prostrate. These five hindrances, monks, are obscurations, hindrances, coverings of the mind, debilitating to wisdom. What five? Sensual desire, monks, is an obscuration, a hindrance, a covering of the mind, debilitating to wisdom. Ill-will … sloth and torpor … restlessness and remorse … doubt, monks, is an obscuration, a hindrance, a covering of the mind, debilitating to wisdom. These five hindrances, monks, are obscurations, hindrances, coverings of the mind, debilitating to wisdom. The seven factors of enlightenment, monks, are not obscurations, not hindrances, not coverings of the mind; when developed and cultivated, they lead to the realization of the fruit of true knowledge and liberation. What seven? The mindfulness factor of enlightenment … The equanimity factor of enlightenment — these are not obscurations, not hindrances, not coverings of the mind; when developed and cultivated, they lead to the realization of the fruit of true knowledge and liberation.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 46.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn46.39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if anyone speaks of ‘a heap of the unwholesome,’ he would speak rightly of the five hindrances. The entire heap of the unwholesome, monks, is just the five hindrances. What five? The hindrance of sensual desire, the hindrance of ill-will, the hindrance of sloth and torpor, the hindrance of restlessness and remorse, the hindrance of doubt. If anyone speaks of ‘a heap of the unwholesome,’ he would speak rightly of the five hindrances. The entire heap of the unwholesome is just the five hindrances. If anyone speaks of ‘a heap of the wholesome,’ monks, he would speak rightly of the four foundations of mindfulness. The entire heap of the wholesome, monks, is just the four foundations of mindfulness. What four? Here, monks, a monk dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and sorrow in the world; dwells contemplating feelings as feelings … mind as mind … phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and sorrow in the world. If anyone speaks of ‘a heap of the wholesome,’ he would speak rightly of the four foundations of mindfulness. The entire heap of the wholesome is just the four foundations of mindfulness.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Once, monks, a hawk suddenly swooped down and seized a quail. Then, monks, the quail, while being carried off by the hawk, lamented: ‘This is my misfortune! This is my lack of merit! For I wandered outside my own proper range, into the domain of others. If I had kept to my own proper range, my ancestral territory, this hawk would not have been a match for me in battle.’ - ‘What, quail, is your own proper range, your ancestral territory?’ - ‘A field plowed with a plow.’ Then, monks, the hawk, not boasting of its own strength, not pressing its own strength, released the quail and said: ‘Go, quail. Even after going there, I will not let you go.’ Then, monks, the quail went to a field plowed with a plow, climbed onto a large clod of earth, stood on it, and said to the hawk: ‘Come at me, hawk! Come at me, hawk!’ Then the hawk, boasting of its own strength, pressing its own strength, folding both wings, suddenly swooped down on the quail. When the quail knew: ‘This hawk is swooping down hard on me,’ it hid behind that clod of earth. Then, monks, the hawk shattered its own breast. So too, monks, for one who wanders outside his own proper range, into the domain of others. Therefore, monks, do not wander outside your own proper range, into the domain of others. For one who wanders outside his proper range, into the domain of others, Māra gains an opportunity, Māra gains an object.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“So too, monks, for one who wanders outside his own proper range, into the domain of others, Māra gains an opportunity, Māra gains an object. And what, monks, is not a monk’s proper range, but the domain of others? It is the five strands of sensual pleasure. What five? Forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. Sounds … odors … tastes … touches cognizable by the body … desirable … enticing. This, monks, is not a monk’s proper range, but the domain of others. Monks, wander in your own proper range, your ancestral territory. When you wander in your own proper range, your ancestral territory, Māra does not gain an opportunity, does not gain an object. And what, monks, is a monk’s proper range, his ancestral territory? It is the four foundations of mindfulness. What four? Here, monks, a monk dwells contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and sorrow in the world; dwells contemplating feelings as feelings … mind as mind … phenomena as phenomena, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and sorrow in the world. This, monks, is a monk’s own proper range, his ancestral territory.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, on King Snowy Mountain there are rough, uneven stretches where neither monkeys nor humans go. On King Snowy Mountain there are rough, uneven stretches where monkeys go but humans do not. On King Snowy Mountain there are even, pleasant stretches where both monkeys and humans go. There, monks, hunters set a trap of sticky resin on the paths where monkeys go, to catch monkeys. Here, monks, those monkeys that are not foolish and not greedy avoid the trap of resin when they see it. But a foolish, greedy monkey, seeing the resin, reaches out with its hand and gets stuck. Wanting to free its hand, it reaches out with the other hand and gets stuck. Wanting to free both hands, it reaches out with one foot and gets stuck. Wanting to free its hands and foot, it reaches out with the other foot and gets stuck. Wanting to free its hands and feet, it puts its mouth to it and gets stuck. Thus, monks, the monkey, caught in five places, lies down screeching, having fallen into misfortune, into calamity, subject to the hunter’s will. The hunter then kills it, roasts it over a charcoal fire, and goes away as he wishes. So too, monks, for one who wanders outside his own proper range, into the domain of others. For one who wanders outside his proper range, into the domain of others, Māra gains an opportunity, Māra gains an object.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn47.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, does a monk dwell ‘as below, so above; as above, so below’? Here, monks, a monk contemplates this body from the soles of the feet upward, from the top of the head downward, enclosed by skin and full of various impurities: ‘There are in this body: head hairs, body hairs, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, intestinal mesentery, stomach, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, skin oil, saliva, snot, synovial fluid, urine.’ Thus, monks, a monk dwells ‘as below, so above; as above, so below.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 51.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn51.20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, it is because of not realizing, not penetrating the Four Noble Truths that you and I have wandered and wandered through this long course. What four? Because of not realizing, not penetrating the noble truth of suffering, monks, you and I have wandered and wandered through this long course … the noble truth of the origin of suffering … the noble truth of the cessation of suffering … Because of not realizing, not penetrating the noble truth of the path leading to the cessation of suffering, monks, you and I have wandered and wandered through this long course. But now, monks, the noble truth of suffering has been realized and penetrated. The noble truth of the origin of suffering has been realized and penetrated. The noble truth of the cessation of suffering has been realized and penetrated. The noble truth of the path leading to the cessation of suffering has been realized and penetrated. Cut off is craving for existence; destroyed is what leads to renewed existence. Now there is no further becoming.” The Blessed One said this … the Teacher further said:<br><br>From not seeing the four noble truths<br>As they really are,<br>One wanders for a long time<br>Through many births.<br>But when these are seen,<br>The root of rebirth is pulled out,<br>The root of suffering is cut off —<br>Now there is no further becoming.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.21", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.21/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What leads the world along?<br>What torments itself?<br>And what is the one thing<br>Upon which everything depends?”<br><br>“Craving leads the world along,<br>Craving torments itself,<br>Craving is the one thing<br>Upon which everything depends.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 1.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn1.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, what one intends, what one plans, and what one has a tendency towards — that becomes a basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is a basis, consciousness becomes established. When consciousness is established and grows, there is a leaning (nati). When there is a leaning, there is a going to a state of rebirth. When there is a going to a state of rebirth, there is future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. Such is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Monks, if one does not intend, does not plan, and has no tendency towards anything, there is no basis for the establishment of consciousness. When there is no basis, consciousness does not become established. When consciousness is not established and does not grow, there is no leaning. When there is no leaning, there is no going to a state of rebirth. When there is no going to a state of rebirth, there is no future birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. Such is the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.40/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as an oil lamp burns in dependence on oil and a wick, and someone occasionally pours in oil and adjusts the wick — that oil lamp, being nourished and sustained in such a way, would burn for a long time. So too, monks, one who dwells seeing gratification in things that are fetters — craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging arises … Thus the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Monks, just as an oil lamp burns in dependence on oil and a wick, and no one occasionally pours in oil or adjusts the wick — that oil lamp, being without its own fuel, with no further fuel added, not being nourished, would be extinguished. So too, monks, one who dwells seeing peril in things that are fetters — craving ceases. With the cessation of craving, clinging ceases … Thus the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, just as a great tree, having its roots that extend downward and laterally, all those roots convey the sap upwards — that great tree, being nourished and sustained in such a way, would stand for a long time. So too, monks, one who dwells seeing gratification in things that are clung to — craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging arises … Thus the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Monks, just as a great tree, and a man comes with a shovel and a basket. He cuts the tree’s roots … He digs a trench … he pulls out the rootlets … or he burns the tree and scatters the ashes in a strong stream of water. That great tree, with its roots cut, made like a palm stump, cannot be reborn, cannot arise again in the future. So too, monks, one who dwells seeing peril in things that are clung to — craving ceases. With the cessation of craving, clinging ceases … Thus the cessation of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.56/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Deep, Ānanda, is this dependent origination, and deep indeed is its definition. It is because of not understanding, not penetrating this Dhamma, Ānanda, that beings are tangled like a ball of thread, covered with blight, like muñja grass, like bulrushes, unable to escape from the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, saṃsāra. Ānanda, one who dwells seeing gratification in things that are clung to — craving increases. With craving as condition, existence comes to be. With existence as condition, birth comes to be. With birth as condition, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise. Such is the origination of this whole mass of suffering. Just as, Ānanda, a great tree, having its roots that extend downward and laterally, all those roots convey the sap upwards — that great tree, being nourished and sustained in such a way, would stand for a long time. So too, Ānanda, one who dwells seeing gratification in things that are clung to — craving increases. With craving as condition, clinging comes to be … Such is the origination of this whole mass of suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 12.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn12.60/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Form, monks, is impermanent. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of form — that too is impermanent. Form that has arisen from the impermanent, monks, how could it be permanent? Feeling, monks, is impermanent … Perception … Formations … Consciousness is impermanent. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of consciousness — that too is impermanent. Consciousness that has arisen from the impermanent, monks, how could it be permanent? Seeing thus, monks, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form … disenchanted with feeling … disenchanted with perception … disenchanted with formations … disenchanted with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate … He knows: ‘… there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.18/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Form, monks, is suffering. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of form — that too is suffering. Form that has arisen from suffering, monks, how could it be happiness? Feeling … Perception … Formations … Consciousness is suffering. Whatever cause and condition for the arising of consciousness — that too is suffering. Consciousness that has arisen from suffering, monks, how could it be happiness? Seeing thus, monks, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form … disenchanted with feeling … disenchanted with perception … disenchanted with formations … disenchanted with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate … He knows: ‘… there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Venerable sirs, for one who has abandoned lust for form, abandoned desire, abandoned love, abandoned thirst, abandoned passion, abandoned craving — when that form changes and alters, no sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, or despair arise. For feeling … perception … formations … For one who has abandoned lust for consciousness, abandoned desire, abandoned love, abandoned thirst, abandoned passion, abandoned craving — when that consciousness changes and alters, no sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, or despair arise. Seeing this benefit, venerable sirs, our Teacher speaks of the subduing of desire and lust for form … for feeling … for perception … for formations; our Teacher speaks of the subduing of desire and lust for consciousness. And because one attains and dwells in wholesome states, living at ease in this very life, without obstruction, without distress, without fever, and at the breakup of the body, after death, one will be reborn in a good destination. Therefore, this is the accomplishment of wholesome states praised by the Blessed One.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I have searched for the gratification of form. Whatever gratification there is in form — I have found it. To what extent there is gratification in form — that I have seen well with wisdom. Monks, I have searched for the peril of form. Whatever peril there is in form — I have found it. To what extent there is peril in form — that I have seen well with wisdom. Monks, I have searched for the escape from form. Whatever escape there is from form — I have found it. To what extent there is escape from form — that I have seen well with wisdom. Monks, I have searched for the gratification of feeling … of perception … of formations … of consciousness. Whatever gratification there is in consciousness — I have found it. To what extent there is gratification in consciousness — that I have seen well with wisdom. Monks, I have searched for the peril of consciousness … the escape from consciousness … That I have seen well with wisdom. Monks, as long as I did not directly know as it actually is the gratification as gratification, the peril as peril, the escape as escape in regard to these five aggregates of clinging, I did not declare that … ascetics, brahmins, devas, and humans. But when I directly knew them, then the knowledge and vision arose in me: ‘My mind is liberated, imperturbable. This is my last life, now there is no further becoming.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.27", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.27/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, one who delights in form delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. Monks, one who delights in feeling … perception … formations … consciousness delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. And, monks, one who does not delight in form does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering. One who does not delight in feeling … perception … formations … consciousness does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.29", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.29/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, through lust, one is not freed. Through lust for form, monks, consciousness becomes established with a foothold. With form as its object, with form as its support, seeking delight, it grows, increases, and expands. Through lust for feeling … for perception … for formations, monks, consciousness becomes established with a foothold. With formations as its object, with formations as its support, seeking delight, it grows, increases, and expands. Monks, if anyone says: ‘Apart from form, apart from feeling, apart from perception, apart from formations, I will show the coming and going, the passing away and arising, the growth, increase, and expansion of consciousness’ — such a thing is not possible. Monks, if a monk has abandoned lust for the form element — with the abandonment of lust, the basis is cut off, the support of consciousness does not exist. If a monk has abandoned lust for the feeling element … for the perception element … for the formation element … Monks, if a monk has abandoned lust for the consciousness element — with the abandonment of lust, the basis is cut off, the support of consciousness does not exist. Without that support, consciousness does not expand, does not generate activity, and is liberated. Being liberated, it is steady; being steady, it is content; being content, it is not agitated; being not agitated, he personally attains Nibbāna. He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.53/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Through lust for form, monks, consciousness becomes established with a foothold. With form as its object, with form as its support, seeking delight, it grows, increases, and expands. Through lust for feeling … for perception … for formations, monks, consciousness becomes established with a foothold. With formations as its object, with formations as its support, seeking delight, it grows, increases, and expands. Monks, if anyone says: ‘Apart from form, apart from feeling, apart from perception, apart from formations, I will show the coming and going, the passing away and arising, the growth, increase, and expansion of consciousness’ — such a thing is not possible. Monks, if a monk has abandoned lust for the form element — with the abandonment of lust, the basis is cut off, the support of consciousness does not exist. Monks, if he has abandoned lust for the feeling element … for the perception element … for the formation element … for the consciousness element — with the abandonment of lust, the basis is cut off, the support of consciousness does not exist. Without that support, consciousness does not expand, does not generate activity, and is liberated; being liberated, it is steady; being steady, it is content; being content, it is not agitated; being not agitated, he personally attains Nibbāna. He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Mahāli, there is a cause, a condition for the defilement of beings. Mahāli, there is a cause, a condition for the purification of beings.” “But, venerable sir, what is the cause, what is the condition for the defilement of beings?” “Mahāli, if form were exclusively suffering, immersed in suffering, accompanied by suffering, not accompanied by happiness, beings would not become lustful for form. But because form is happiness, Mahāli, immersed in happiness, accompanied by happiness, not accompanied by suffering, beings become lustful for form. Through lust, they are bound; through being bound, they are defiled. This, Mahāli, is the cause, this is the condition for the defilement of beings. Such being the cause, such being the condition, beings are defiled.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.60/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What, venerable sir, is the cause, what is the condition for the purification of beings?” “Mahāli, if form were exclusively happiness, immersed in happiness, accompanied by happiness, not accompanied by suffering, beings would not become disenchanted with form. But because form is suffering, Mahāli, immersed in suffering, accompanied by suffering, not accompanied by happiness, beings become disenchanted with form. Through disenchantment, they become dispassionate; through dispassion, they are liberated. This, Mahāli, is the cause, this is the condition for the purification of beings. Such being the cause, such being the condition, beings are purified. If feeling … perception … formations … if consciousness were exclusively happiness … beings would not become disenchanted with consciousness. But because consciousness is suffering … beings become disenchanted with consciousness … and are liberated. This, Mahāli, is the cause, this is the condition for the purification of beings.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.60/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who clings, monk, is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One.” - “I understand, Blessed One! I understand, Well-gone One!” - “How, monk, do you understand in detail the meaning of my brief statement?” - “One who clings to form, venerable sir, is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One. One who clings to feeling … to perception … to formations … to consciousness is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One. Venerable sir, I understand in detail the meaning of the Blessed One’s brief statement thus.” - “Good, good, monk! Good, monk! Thus you understand in detail the meaning of my brief statement. One who clings to form, monk, is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One. One who clings to feeling … to perception … to formations … to consciousness is bound by Māra. One who does not cling is freed from the Evil One.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, an untaught ordinary person does not know as it actually is the origination, the cessation, the gratification, the peril, and the escape in regard to form, feeling, perception, formations, and consciousness. Monks, a well-taught noble disciple knows as it actually is the origination, the cessation, the gratification, the peril, and the escape in regard to form, feeling, perception, formations, and consciousness.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.74", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.74/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, form is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it actually is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Feeling … perception … formations … consciousness is impermanent. What is impermanent is suffering. What is suffering is not-self. What is not-self should be seen as it actually is with correct wisdom: ‘This is not mine, this I am not, this is not my self.’ Seeing thus, monks, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form … with feeling … with perception … with formations … with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate. Through dispassion, he is liberated. In liberation, knowledge arises: ‘Liberated.’ He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’<br><br>Happy indeed are the arahants,<br>In them no craving is found,<br>Conceit has been cut off,<br>The net of delusion is torn apart.<br><br>They have attained the imperturbable,<br>Their minds are far from defilement,<br>They are not stained in the world —<br>The holy ones, free from defilements.<br><br>Fully understanding the five aggregates,<br>Practicing the seven good qualities,<br>Praised by true persons,<br>Disciples of the Buddha.<br><br>Possessing seven treasures,<br>Completed in the three trainings,<br>The great heroes wander forth,<br>Having abandoned all fear.<br><br>Endowed with ten powers,<br>The great elephant is concentrated,<br>They are supreme in the world,<br>Craving has been destroyed.<br><br>Achieved the knowledge of the adept,<br>This body is their last,<br>The end of the holy life,<br>Achieved independently.<br><br>Not shaken by perceptions,<br>Liberated from renewed existence,<br>Having reached the tamed state,<br>They are conquerors in the world.<br><br>Above, below, and across,<br>They have no delight,<br>They roar the lion’s roar —<br>The supreme Buddhas in the world!`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.76", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.76/en/sujato" },

{ text: `When feeling a pleasant feeling, he understands: ‘It is impermanent’; he understands: ‘It is not to be clung to’; he understands: ‘It is not to be delighted in.’ When feeling a painful feeling, he understands: ‘It is impermanent’; he understands: ‘It is not to be clung to’; he understands: ‘It is not to be delighted in.’ When feeling a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he understands: ‘It is impermanent’; he understands: ‘It is not to be clung to’; he understands: ‘It is not to be delighted in.’ If he feels a pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is not bound. If he feels a painful feeling … If he feels a neither-painful-nor-pleasant feeling, he feels it as one who is not bound. When he feels a feeling ending with the body, he understands: ‘I feel a feeling ending with the body.’ When he feels a feeling ending with life, he understands: ‘I feel a feeling ending with life.’ He understands: ‘With the breakup of the body, after death, everything that is felt, in which he no longer delights, will become cool right here.’ Just as, Assaji, an oil lamp burns in dependence on oil and a wick. When the oil and wick of that lamp are exhausted, with no further fuel, the lamp is extinguished. So too, Assaji, a monk, when feeling a feeling ending with the body, understands … when feeling a feeling ending with life, understands … after death, everything that is felt, in which he no longer delights, becomes cool.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 22.88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn22.88/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘Māra, Māra,’ venerable sir, is said. What, venerable sir, is Māra?” - “Form, Rādha, is Māra. Feeling is Māra. Perception is Māra. Formations are Māra. Consciousness is Māra. Seeing thus, Rādha, a well-taught noble disciple becomes disenchanted with form … with feeling … with perception … with formations … with consciousness. Being disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate. Through dispassion, he is liberated. In liberation, knowledge arises: ‘Liberated.’ He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 23.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn23.11/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, whatever is not yours, abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being. And what, monks, is not yours? The eye, monks, is not yours — abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being. Forms are not yours — abandon them. Eye-consciousness is not yours — abandon it. Eye-contact is not yours — abandon it. Suppose, monks, a person were to carry away, burn, or do whatever they want with all the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves in this Jeta’s Grove. Would you think: ‘This person carries us away, burns us, or does whatever they want with us’?” - “No, venerable sir.” - “Why not?” - “Because that is not our self nor belonging to our self.” - “So too, monks, the eye is not yours — abandon it … Forms … Eye-consciousness … Eye-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on mind-contact — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is not yours. Abandon it. Abandoning it will lead to your happiness and well-being.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.101", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.101/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk delights in those forms, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — then, monks, this is called a monk who has gone into Māra’s domain, who has come under Māra’s control. Māra’s net has surrounded him. Bound by Māra, he is subject to the Evil One’s will. Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye … If a monk does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them — then, monks, this is called a monk who has not gone into Māra’s domain, not come under Māra’s control. Māra’s net has not surrounded him. Freed from Māra’s bondage, he is not subject to the Evil One’s will.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.114", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.114/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, devas and humans delight in form, are excited by form. When form changes, fades, and ceases, devas and humans dwell in suffering. Devas and humans delight in sound … in odor … in taste … in touch … in phenomena, are excited by phenomena. When phenomena change, fade, and cease, devas and humans dwell in suffering.<br><br>Forms, sounds, tastes, odors, touches,<br>And all phenomena —<br>Desirable, delightful, agreeable —<br>Thus they are called.<br><br>Devas and humans in the world,<br>Regarding them as delightful —<br>Where they cease and fade away,<br>Devas and humans see suffering.<br><br>The noble one sees as ease<br>When identity view is destroyed —<br>The noble one sees as opposite<br>All the views of the world.<br><br>What others call pleasure,<br>The noble call suffering.<br>What others call suffering,<br>The noble know as pleasure.<br><br>See the Dhamma, hard to comprehend,<br>Where the ignorant are bewildered —<br>Darkness for the blind,<br>Obscurity for those who cannot see.<br><br>The wise are open-eyed,<br>Like light clearly shining,<br>The foolish, even though near,<br>Do not understand the Dhamma.<br><br>Overcome by the thirst of birth,<br>Swept away by the current of existence,<br>Subject to Māra’s control —<br>They do not awaken to this Dhamma.<br><br>Apart from the noble ones, no one<br>Awakens to this path —<br>The path leading to Nibbāna,<br>With perfect wisdom, free from defilements.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.136", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.136/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Good, venerable sir, if the Blessed One would teach me the Dhamma in brief. Having heard the Dhamma from the Blessed One, I will dwell alone, secluded, heedful, ardent, and resolute.” - “Koṭṭhita, whatever is suffering — there you should abandon your desire. And what, Koṭṭhita, is suffering? The eye is suffering — there you should abandon your desire. Forms are suffering — there you should abandon your desire. Eye-consciousness is suffering — there you should abandon your desire. Eye-contact is suffering — there you should abandon your desire. Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact — pleasant, painful, or neither-painful-nor-pleasant — that feeling is suffering. There you should abandon your desire.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.163", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.163/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“If there were no gratification in form, monks, beings would not become lustful for form. But because there is gratification in form, beings become lustful for form. If there were no peril in form, beings would not become disenchanted with form. But because there is peril in form, beings become disenchanted with form. If there were no escape from form, beings would not escape from form. But because there is escape from form, beings escape from form. Monks, as long as beings do not directly know as it actually is the gratification as gratification, the peril as peril, the escape as escape in regard to these six internal sense bases, they have not, monks, along with this world of devas, Māras, Brahmās, with its ascetics and brahmins, with its devas and humans, dwelt with minds free from clinging, detached, liberated, unbounded. But because beings have directly known them as they actually are, therefore they have dwelt with minds free from clinging, detached, liberated, unbounded.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.18/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, one who delights in the eye delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. One who delights in the ear … the nose … the tongue … the body … the mind delights in suffering. One who delights in suffering, I say, is not freed from suffering. And, monks, one who does not delight in the eye does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering. One who does not delight in the ear … the nose … the tongue … the body … the mind does not delight in suffering. One who does not delight in suffering, I say, is freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.19", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.19/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘The ocean, the ocean,’ monks, an untaught ordinary person says. That, monks, is not the ocean in the noble one’s discipline. That is just a great mass of water, a great flood. Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. This, monks, is called the ocean in the noble one’s discipline. Here, this world with its devas, Māras, Brahmās, with its ascetics and brahmins, with its devas and humans, for the most part is submerged in it, tangled like a ball of thread, covered like a tangled skein, become like a tangled grass rope, unable to pass beyond the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, saṃsāra.<br><br>Having destroyed ignorance, greed, and hatred,<br>This ocean with its many dangers —<br>With its sharks, crocodiles,<br>Whirlpools, and terrifying waves —<br>Is very hard to cross.<br><br>Having crossed the bond, escaped death,<br>Free from attachments,<br>Having made an end of suffering,<br>There is no further becoming.<br>He has destroyed birth and death,<br>The incomparable one —<br>I say that such a one<br>Has blinded Death.`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.229", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.229/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Suppose, monks, a fisherman throws a baited hook into a deep lake. A fish, seeing the bait, swallows the hook. Thus, monks, that fish, having swallowed the fisherman’s hook, has fallen into misfortune, into calamity, subject to the fisherman’s will. So too, monks, there are these six hooks in the world, leading to the misfortune of beings, to the calamity of living beings. What six? Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk delights in those forms, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — then that monk is called one who has swallowed Māra’s hook, has fallen into misfortune, into calamity, subject to the Evil One’s will. There are sounds … odors … tastes … touches … phenomena cognizable by the mind that are desirable … enticing. If a monk delights in those phenomena, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — then that monk is called one who has swallowed Māra’s hook, has fallen into misfortune, into calamity, subject to the Evil One’s will.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.230", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.230/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. If a monk does not delight in those forms, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them — then that monk is called one who has not swallowed Māra’s hook, who has broken the hook, destroyed the hook, who has not fallen into misfortune, into calamity, not subject to the Evil One’s will. There are sounds … odors … tastes … touches … phenomena cognizable by the mind … If a monk does not delight in those phenomena, does not praise them, and dwells without lust for them — then that monk is called one who has not swallowed Māra’s hook, who has broken the hook, destroyed the hook, who has not fallen into misfortune, into calamity, not subject to the Evil One’s will.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.230", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.230/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, defilement is a disease; defilement is a boil; defilement is a dart. Therefore, monks, the Tathāgata dwells without defilement, free from the dart. Therefore, monks, if any monk has a wish, let him wish to dwell without defilement, free from the dart. Do not conceive about the eye, do not conceive in the eye, do not conceive from the eye, do not conceive ‘the eye is mine.’ Do not conceive about forms … Do not conceive about eye-consciousness … Do not conceive about eye-contact … Whatever feeling arises dependent on eye-contact … do not conceive about that feeling, do not conceive in it, do not conceive from it, do not conceive ‘that feeling is mine.’ Not conceiving thus, he does not cling to anything in the world. Not clinging, he is not agitated. Not agitated, he personally attains Nibbāna. He knows: ‘Birth is destroyed, the holy life has been lived, what had to be done has been done, there is no more of this state of being.’”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.90/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is non-restraint? Monks, there are forms cognizable by the eye that are desirable … enticing. If a monk delights in those forms, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — then that monk, monks, should understand: ‘I have fallen away from wholesome states.’ The Tathāgata calls this ‘falling away.’ And, monks, there are sounds … odors … tastes … phenomena cognizable by the mind … If a monk delights in those phenomena, praises them, and dwells with lust for them — then that monk should understand: ‘I have fallen away from wholesome states.’ The Tathāgata calls this ‘falling away.’ Thus, monks, is non-restraint.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 35.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn35.98/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if wanderers of other sects ask you: ‘For what purpose, friends, is the holy life lived under the ascetic Gotama?’ — being asked thus, monks, you should answer them: ‘For the purpose of the destruction of greed, friends, the holy life is lived under the Blessed One.’ Then, monks, if they ask: ‘Is there, friends, a path, a way for the destruction of greed?’ — being asked thus, you should answer: ‘There is a path, a way for the destruction of greed.’ And what, monks, is that path, that way? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view … right concentration. This, monks, is the path, the way for the destruction of greed. Being asked thus, monks, you should answer them in that way.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 45.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn45.41/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“There are these two extremes, monks, that one who has gone forth should not pursue: devotion to sensual pleasure in sensual objects — low, vulgar, worldly, ignoble, unbeneficial; and devotion to self-mortification — painful, ignoble, unbeneficial. Avoiding these two extremes, monks, the Middle Way has been realized by the Tathāgata, giving rise to vision, giving rise to knowledge, leading to peace, direct knowledge, enlightenment, Nibbāna. And what, monks, is that Middle Way …? It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration. This, monks, is the Middle Way … leading to Nibbāna. This, monks, is the noble truth of suffering. Birth is suffering, aging is suffering, sickness is suffering, death is suffering, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair are suffering, association with the disliked is suffering, separation from the liked is suffering, not getting what one wants is suffering. In short, the five aggregates of clinging are suffering. This, monks, is the noble truth of the origin of suffering. It is this craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and lust, delighting here and there — that is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence. This, monks, is the noble truth of the cessation of suffering. It is the remainderless fading away and cessation of that same craving, the abandoning and relinquishing of it, freedom from it, non-reliance. This, monks, is the noble truth of the path leading to the cessation of suffering. It is the Noble Eightfold Path, namely: right view … right concentration.”`, ref: "Saṃyutta Nikāya 56.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/sn56.11/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other form, monks, that so obsesses and occupies the mind of a man as the form of a woman. The form of a woman, monks, obsesses and occupies the mind of a man.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other form, monks, that so obsesses and occupies the mind of a woman as the form of a man. The form of a man, monks, obsesses and occupies the mind of a woman.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other sound, monks, that so obsesses and occupies the mind of a man as the sound of a woman. The sound of a woman, monks, obsesses and occupies the mind of a man.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, that so gives rise to unarisen sensual desire, or to the increase and expansion of arisen sensual desire, as the sign of the beautiful. The sign of the beautiful, monks, when unwisely attended to, gives rise to unarisen sensual desire and increases and expands arisen sensual desire.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.11/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, that so prevents unarisen sensual desire from arising, or abandons arisen sensual desire, as the sign of the foul. The sign of the foul, monks, when wisely attended to, prevents unarisen sensual desire from arising and abandons arisen sensual desire.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Whatever things, monks, are unwholesome, partaking of the unwholesome, belonging to the unwholesome side — all of them have the mind as their forerunner. The mind arises first for those things, and the unwholesome states follow after.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.56/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as heedlessness. For one who is heedless, monks, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.58/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, through which unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline, as fewness of wishes. For one with few wishes, monks, unarisen wholesome states arise and arisen unwholesome states decline.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as great desire. For one with great desire, monks, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.62/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, evil, unwholesome states arise with a sign, not without a sign. By abandoning that sign, those evil, unwholesome states are not present. Monks, evil, unwholesome states arise with a cause, not without a cause. By abandoning that cause, those evil, unwholesome states are not present. Monks, evil, unwholesome states arise with a form, not without a form … arise with a feeling … with a perception … with consciousness, not without consciousness. By abandoning that cause, those evil, unwholesome states are not present.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.77/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Truly, brahmins, this world is led by aging, illness, and death. Since the world is led by aging, illness, and death, brahmins, restraint of body, speech, and mind in this life is a refuge, a cave, an island (or a lamp), a shelter, and a destination for one who has gone to death.<br><br>When a house is on fire,<br>The goods that are removed<br>Are useful to the owners,<br>Not those burned inside.<br>So too, the world is burning<br>With aging and death on fire —<br>Save yourself by giving,<br>For what is given is well-saved.<br>Here, restraint of body,<br>Restraint of speech and mind —<br>One who does this, even while dying,<br>Experiences happiness,<br>Because while still alive,<br>He has made merit.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.52/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“To what extent, Venerable Gotama, is the Dhamma visible here and now, immediate, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be directly experienced by the wise?” - “Brahmin, being infatuated by craving, overwhelmed, with mind obsessed, one plans for one’s own harm, plans for others’ harm, plans for the harm of both, and experiences mental suffering and mental distress. When craving is abandoned, one does not plan for one’s own harm, nor for others’ harm, nor for the harm of both, and does not experience mental suffering or mental distress. Being infatuated by craving, brahmin, overwhelmed, with mind obsessed, one engages in misconduct of body, misconduct of speech, misconduct of mind. When craving is abandoned, one does not engage in misconduct of body, speech, or mind. Being infatuated by craving, brahmin, overwhelmed, with mind obsessed, one does not know as it actually is one’s own benefit, nor the benefit of others, nor the benefit of both. When craving is abandoned, one knows as it actually is one’s own benefit, the benefit of others, and the benefit of both. Thus, brahmin, the Dhamma is visible here and now, immediate, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be directly experienced by the wise.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.54", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.54/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What is the cause, good sirs, what is the condition for the arising of unarisen greed, and for the growth and increase of arisen greed?” - “The sign of the beautiful.” For one who attends unwisely to the sign of the beautiful, unarisen greed arises and arisen greed increases and grows. This, good sirs, is the cause, this is the condition for the arising of unarisen greed and for the growth and increase of arisen greed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.68/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What is the cause, good sirs, what is the condition for the non-arising of unarisen greed, or for the abandonment of arisen greed?” - “The sign of the foul.” For one who attends wisely to the sign of the foul, unarisen greed does not arise and arisen greed is abandoned. This, good sirs, is the cause, this is the condition for the non-arising of unarisen greed and for the abandonment of arisen greed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.68/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then the Venerable Ānanda went to that nun, sat down on the prepared seat, and said to her: “Sister, this body is produced by food, depends on food. Food should be abandoned. Sister, this body is produced by craving, depends on craving. Craving should be abandoned. Sister, this body is produced by conceit, depends on conceit. Conceit should be abandoned. Sister, this body is produced by sexual intercourse, depends on sexual intercourse. Sexual intercourse — the breaking of the bridge — has been spoken of by the Blessed One. ‘Sister, this body is produced by food, depends on food. Food should be abandoned.’ Thus it has been said. For what reason was this said?”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.159", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.159/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, one who dwells seeing gratification in things that are fetters — greed is not abandoned, hatred is not abandoned, delusion is not abandoned. Because greed, hatred, and delusion are not abandoned, he is not freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is not freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, one who dwells seeing danger in things that are fetters — greed is abandoned, hatred is abandoned, delusion is abandoned. Because greed, hatred, and delusion are abandoned, he is freed from birth, aging, death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair. I say that he is freed from suffering.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Brahmin, if an elder is eighty, ninety, or a hundred years old, and he enjoys sensual pleasures, dwells amidst sensual pleasures, is burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, consumed by sensual thoughts, and strives for sensual pleasures — such a person is called a fool, not an elder. But if a young person, brahmin, a youth with black hair, endowed with the blessing of youth, in the prime of life, does not enjoy sensual pleasures, does not dwell amidst sensual pleasures, is not burned by the fever of sensual pleasures, not consumed by sensual thoughts, and does not strive for sensual pleasures — such a person is called a wise one, an elder.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.38/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these two kinds of pleasure. What two? Sensual pleasure and the pleasure of renunciation. These, monks, are the two pleasures. The best of these two pleasures, monks, is the pleasure of renunciation.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 2.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an2.65/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“What do you think, prince? For that householder or householder’s son, do bodily or mental fevers arise due to craving? Burned by those fevers born of craving, does he experience suffering?” - “Yes, venerable sir.” - “That householder or householder’s son, prince, burned by fevers born of craving, experiences suffering. That craving has been abandoned by the Tathāgata, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future. Therefore I feel at ease.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.35", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.35/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Truly, brahmins, this world is led by aging, illness, and death. Since the world is led by aging, illness, and death, brahmins, restraint of body, speech, and mind in this life is a refuge, a cave, an island, a shelter, and a destination for one who has gone to death.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Life is swept along,<br>The lifespan is short —<br>Led to old age,<br>There is no shelter.<br>Seeing this danger in death,<br>Always do meritorious deeds<br>That bring true happiness.<br>Here, restraint of body,<br>Restraint of speech and mind —<br>One who does this, even while dying,<br>Experiences happiness,<br>Because while still alive,<br>He has made merit.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Being infatuated by craving, brahmin, overwhelmed, with mind obsessed, one plans for one’s own harm, plans for others’ harm, plans for the harm of both, and experiences mental suffering and mental distress. When craving is abandoned, one does not plan for one’s own harm, nor for others’ harm, nor for the harm of both, and does not experience mental suffering or mental distress. Thus, brahmin, the Dhamma is visible here and now, immediate, inviting inspection, leading onward, to be directly experienced by the wise.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.53", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.53/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“He understands thus: ‘Previously I had greed — that was unwholesome. Now I have none. Thus it is wholesome. Previously I had hatred — that was unwholesome. Now I have none. Thus it is wholesome. Previously I had delusion — that was unwholesome. Now I have none. Thus it is wholesome.’ Thus, in this very life, he is freed from longing, calm, cooled, experiencing ease, abiding in the Brahma-state himself.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, whatever is greed — that is unwholesome. Whatever a person does bodily, verbally, or mentally with greed — that is unwholesome. When a person with greed, overcome by greed, with mind uncontrolled, makes another suffer — by killing, binding, confiscation, abuse, or expulsion — thinking ‘I am strong, I have power’ — that is unwholesome. Thus, many evil, unwholesome states arise in him born of greed, originating from greed, produced by greed.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.69/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if there were no gratification in the world, beings would not become lustful for the world. But because there is gratification in the world, beings become lustful for the world. If there were no peril in the world, beings would not become disenchanted with the world. But because there is peril in the world, beings become disenchanted with the world. If there were no escape from the world, beings would not escape from the world. But because there is escape from the world, beings escape from the world.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.105", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.105/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, just as a house with a badly thatched roof — the ridgepole is not protected, the rafters are not protected, the walls are not protected; the ridgepole becomes soaked and leaks, the rafters become soaked and leak, the walls become soaked and leak; the ridgepole rots, the rafters rot, the walls rot. So too, householder, when the mind is not guarded, bodily actions are not guarded, verbal actions … mental actions … then bodily actions become soaked with greed and leak, verbal actions become soaked with greed and leak, mental actions become soaked with greed and leak. For one whose bodily actions are soaked and leak with greed, whose verbal and mental actions are soaked and leak with greed, bodily actions rot, verbal actions rot, mental actions rot. For one whose bodily, verbal, and mental actions rot, death is not good, the end is not good.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.109/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The eye is unguarded,<br>The faculties are unrestrained —<br>Flies will swarm<br>Thoughts of craving.<br>The monk becomes rotten,<br>Filled with foul smells —<br>Far, far away is Nibbāna!<br>He meets with misfortune.<br>In village or forest,<br>If one’s self is not peaceful,<br>The fool, without wisdom,<br>Walking or standing, is full of flies.<br>But one endowed with virtue,<br>Delighting in tranquil wisdom,<br>Lives peacefully and happily —<br>All flies are destroyed.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.128", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an3.128/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Those who live in the world<br>Without restraining sensual desires,<br>Not abandoning passion,<br>Enjoying sensual pleasures —<br>They go to birth and aging,<br>Again and again,<br>Bound by craving,<br>They go with the stream.<br>Therefore the wise,<br>Mindful in the world,<br>Do not enjoy sensual pleasures,<br>Do not do evil deeds.<br>Even if they suffer,<br>Abandoning sensual pleasures,<br>They are called those<br>Who go against the stream.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `One with craving as companion<br>Wanders for a long time —<br>Now here, now there —<br>He cannot stop<br>The wandering of rebirth.<br>Having understood this danger —<br>That craving is the origin of suffering —<br>The monk, abandoning craving,<br>Not grasping, not clinging,<br>Mindfully dwells,<br>Living the homeless life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, monks, a person truly understands the origination, the cessation, the gratification, the peril, and the escape in regard to sensual pleasures. By truly understanding them, sensual desire, sensual delight, sensual attachment, sensual infatuation, sensual thirst, sensual fever, sensual clinging, sensual craving regarding sensual pleasures do not invade and remain. This, monks, is called freedom from the yoke of sensual desire.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.10/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Householder, having known that sensual desire is a defilement of the mind, that noble disciple abandons sensual desire, the defilement of the mind; having known that ill-will is a defilement of the mind, he abandons ill-will; having known that sloth and torpor are defilements of the mind, he abandons sloth and torpor; having known that restlessness and remorse are defilements of the mind, he abandons restlessness and remorse; having known that doubt is a defilement of the mind, he abandons doubt. This, householder, is called a noble disciple of great wisdom, of broad wisdom, who has entered the sphere of clear vision, endowed with wisdom. This is called being endowed with wisdom.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.61/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Craving for beautiful things,<br>Delighting in agreeable forms,<br>Bound by ignorance,<br>Lowly beings<br>Increase their bondage.<br>Even the wise who do unwholesome deeds<br>Born from greed, hatred, delusion —<br>Causing distress, discomfort,<br>Giving rise to suffering —<br>Are surrounded by ignorance,<br>Blind, without eyes.<br>Such is their nature —<br>They cannot think:<br>I can be thus.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“When, monks, a monk is not lustful regarding objects that can provoke lust, and his self is free from lust; is not hateful regarding objects that can provoke hatred, and his self is free from hatred; is not deluded regarding objects that can provoke delusion, and his self is free from delusion; is not infatuated regarding objects that can provoke infatuation, and his self is free from infatuation — then he has no fear, no trembling, no terror, does not fall into fear, and does not go by whatever ascetics may say.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.117/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the practice of restraint? Here, monks, when a monk sees a form with the eye, he does not grasp the general feature, does not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the eye faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — he restrains that cause, guards the eye faculty, practices restraint of the eye. When he hears a sound … smells an odor … tastes a flavor … feels a touch … cognizes a phenomenon with the mind, he does not grasp the general feature, does not grasp the particular feature. Those causes whereby, if the mind faculty were not restrained, covetousness, sorrow, evil, unwholesome states would arise — he restrains that cause, guards the mind faculty, practices restraint of the mind. This, monks, is called the practice of restraint.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.164", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.164/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the practice of calming? Here, monks, a monk does not consent to arisen sensual thought; he abandons, dispels, calms, ends, and makes it non-existent. He does not consent to arisen ill-will thought … harmful thought … to arisen evil, unwholesome thoughts; he abandons, dispels, calms, ends, and makes them non-existent. This, monks, is called the practice of calming.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.164", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.164/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, brahmin, a person is not free from lust for sensual pleasures, not free from desire, not free from affection, not free from thirst, not free from fever, not free from craving. Then a severe illness arises for him. Affected by that severe illness, he thinks: ‘Truly, agreeable sensual pleasures will leave me,’ or ‘I will leave agreeable sensual pleasures.’ He sorrows, grieves, laments, beats his breast, and becomes distraught. This, brahmin, is a person who is subject to death, fearful, and falls into terror at the thought of death.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.184", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.184/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, wanderers, a brahmin says: ‘All sensual pleasures are impermanent, suffering, subject to change.’ That brahmin speaks truth, not falsehood. And by directly knowing the truth contained therein, he practices disenchantment, dispassion, and cessation regarding sensual pleasures.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.185", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.185/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Craving, monks, is a net that widens the wandering, it sticks; because of this craving, this world is destroyed, bound, tangled like a ball of thread, like a tangled skein, like muñja grass and babaja reeds, unable to pass beyond the plane of misery, the bad destination, the lower realm, saṃsāra.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.199", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.199/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these four ignoble searches. What four? Here, monks, a person being himself subject to aging seeks what is subject to aging; being himself subject to sickness seeks what is subject to sickness; being himself subject to death seeks what is subject to death; being himself subject to defilement seeks what is subject to defilement. These, monks, are the four ignoble searches.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.255", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.255/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these four noble searches. What four? Here, monks, a person being himself subject to aging, having known the peril in what is subject to aging, seeks the unaging, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna; being himself subject to sickness, having known the peril in sickness, seeks the unailing, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna; being himself subject to death, having known the peril in death, seeks the deathless, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna; being himself subject to defilement, having known the peril in defilement, seeks the undefiled, supreme security from bondage, Nibbāna. These, monks, are the four noble searches.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 4.255", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an4.255/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“For the most part, monks, beings find pleasure in sensual pleasures. But a clansman who has set aside the sickle and the carrying-pole, gone forth from the household life into homelessness, is justifiably called ‘a clansman who has gone forth out of faith.’ Why is that? Sensual pleasures are found with youth, these sensual pleasures or others. And, monks, low sensual pleasures, middling sensual pleasures, and supreme sensual pleasures — all are classed as sensual pleasures.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these five defilements of the mind because of which the mind becomes defiled, not malleable, not wieldy, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the defilements. What five? Sensual desire, ill-will, sloth and torpor, restlessness and remorse, doubt. These five defilements of the mind, monks, because of which the mind becomes defiled, not malleable, not wieldy, not radiant, brittle, and not properly concentrated for the destruction of the defilements.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.23/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And when, monks, the mind is freed from these five defilements — sensual desire, ill-will, sloth and torpor, restlessness and remorse, doubt — then it becomes malleable, wieldy, radiant, not brittle, properly concentrated for the destruction of the defilements. Regarding whatever state is to be directly known, the mind inclines to direct knowledge, and in each case he attains the ability and capacity to realize that state.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.23/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Nāgita, for those who are heavily inclined toward delight, when there is change, alteration, sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief, and despair arise — that is the natural result. For those who fix their minds on the sign of the foul, Nāgita, disenchantment with the sign of the beautiful becomes established — that is the natural result. For one who dwells contemplating impermanence in the six sense bases, Nāgita, disenchantment with contact becomes established — that is the natural result. For one who dwells contemplating arising and passing away in the five aggregates of clinging, Nāgita, disenchantment with clinging becomes established — that is the natural result.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.30", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.30/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Sensual desire, monks, is an obscuration, a hindrance, a covering of the mind, debilitating to wisdom. Ill-will, monks … sloth and torpor … restlessness and remorse … doubt is an obscuration, a hindrance, a covering of the mind, debilitating to wisdom. These, monks, are the five obscurations, hindrances, coverings of the mind, debilitating to wisdom.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“If anyone speaks of ‘a heap of the unwholesome,’ monks, he would speak rightly of the five hindrances. Indeed, the entire heap of the unwholesome, monks, is just the five hindrances. What five? The hindrance of sensual desire, the hindrance of ill-will, the hindrance of sloth and torpor, the hindrance of restlessness and remorse, the hindrance of doubt. If anyone speaks of ‘a heap of the unwholesome,’ he would speak rightly of the five hindrances. Indeed, the entire heap of the unwholesome is just the five hindrances.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.52/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if anyone says: ‘Māra’s complete snare’ — he would speak rightly of women. Indeed, women are ‘Māra’s complete snare.’”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.55/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Speak with a person<br>Who holds a sword in hand,<br>Speak with a demon,<br>Or sit closely with them.<br>A poisonous snake —<br>If bitten, one dies —<br>But do not alone<br>Speak with a woman.<br>Mindless, they bind one<br>With glances, with smiles,<br>With revealing clothes,<br>With sweet words —<br>Still not satisfied,<br>One becomes unconscious and dies.<br>These five strands of sensual pleasure<br>Are seen in female form —<br>Form, sound, smell, taste, touch —<br>Enticing and agreeable.<br>Overwhelmed by the waterfall of sensuality,<br>Flooded and swept away,<br>The foolish and ignorant,<br>Not understanding sensual pleasures.<br>Humans, at death,<br>Go to states of existence and non-existence —<br>They are led on<br>Through many births.<br>Those who understand sensual pleasures,<br>Without fear in their conduct,<br>Reach the far shore,<br>Attaining the destruction of the defilements.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.55/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monk, when a person dwells with sense faculties unguarded, without moderation in eating, not committed to wakefulness, not watching over wholesome states, not devoted to developing the factors of enlightenment at the beginning and end of the night — then his body feels intoxicated, his eye does not see directions clearly, the Dhamma is not remembered by him. Sloth and torpor overcome his mind and remain. Without gladness, he lives the holy life. He has doubts about the true Dhamma. Therefore, monk, you should train thus: ‘I will guard the sense faculties, have moderation in eating, be committed to wakefulness, watch over wholesome states, and be devoted to developing the factors of enlightenment at the beginning and end of the night.’”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.56/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monk, when a person dwells with sense faculties guarded, with moderation in eating, committed to wakefulness, watching over wholesome states, devoted to developing the factors of enlightenment at the beginning and end of the night — then his body does not feel intoxicated, his eye sees directions clearly, the Dhamma is remembered by him. Sloth and torpor do not overcome his mind. With gladness, he lives the holy life. He has no doubts about wholesome states. Therefore, monks, you should train thus: ‘I will guard the sense faculties … be devoted to developing the factors of enlightenment at the beginning and end of the night.’”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.56/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Suffering from disease and aging,<br>And also subject to death —<br>Such is the nature of conditioned things,<br>Such is the nature of beings.<br>If ordinary people become disenchanted,<br>That would not be fitting for me —<br>If I too were disenchanted<br>With beings who share the same fate.<br>While I live,<br>Not different from them,<br>I dwell thus,<br>Knowing the Dhamma without attachment.<br>Conceit in health,<br>In youth, in life —<br>All these I have subdued,<br>Springing from security.<br>I see the path of seclusion,<br>I arouse strong energy,<br>Seeing the state of Nibbāna.<br>Now I cannot<br>Enjoy sensual pleasures —<br>I will not fall back,<br>Achieving the final goal of the holy life.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.57/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these five perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, ending in the deathless. What five? The perception of foulness, the perception of death, the perception of peril, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world. These five perceptions, monks, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, ending in the deathless.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.61/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these five perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, ending in the deathless. What five? The perception of impermanence, the perception of not-self, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world. These five perceptions, monks, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, ending in the deathless.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.62", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.62/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these five things, when developed and cultivated, lead to the destruction of the defilements. What five? Here, monks, a monk dwells contemplating foulness in the body, with the perception of disgust for food, with the perception of non-delight in the entire world, contemplating impermanence in all formations, and the perception of death is well established within him. These five things, monks, when developed and cultivated, lead to the destruction of the defilements.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.70", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.70/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And for what benefit, monks, should a monk dwell with the perception of disgust toward the non-disgusting? ‘May greed not arise in me toward agreeable states.’ For this benefit, monks, a monk should dwell with the perception of disgust toward the non-disgusting. And for what benefit, monks, should a monk dwell with the perception of non-disgust toward the disgusting? ‘May hatred not arise in me toward states that provoke hatred.’ For this benefit, a monk should dwell with the perception of non-disgust toward the disgusting. And for what benefit should a monk, abandoning both the non-disgusting and the disgusting, dwell equanimously, mindful and clearly comprehending? ‘May greed not arise in me toward agreeable states, wherever, however; may hatred not arise in me toward states that provoke hatred, wherever, however; may delusion not arise in me toward states that provoke delusion, wherever, however.’ For this benefit, monks, a monk, abandoning both the non-disgusting and the disgusting, dwells equanimously, mindful and clearly comprehending.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.144", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.144/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other contact, monks, that so obsesses and occupies the mind of a man as the contact of a woman. The contact of a woman, monks, obsesses and occupies the mind of a man.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as unwise attention. For one who attends unwisely, monks, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.66", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.66/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as lack of clear comprehension. For one lacking clear comprehension, monks, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.68/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, through which unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline, as intimacy with unwholesome states and non-intimacy with wholesome states. Through intimacy with unwholesome states and non-intimacy with wholesome states, monks, unarisen unwholesome states arise and arisen wholesome states decline.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.72/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, through which unarisen factors of enlightenment arise and arisen factors of enlightenment come to completion, as wise attention. Through wise attention, monks, unarisen factors of enlightenment arise and arisen factors of enlightenment come to full development.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.75", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.75/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, that leads to such great harm as heedlessness. Heedlessness, monks, leads to great harm.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.82", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.82/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“I do not see any other thing, monks, that leads to such great benefit as heedfulness. Heedfulness, monks, leads to great benefit.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 1.83", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an1.83/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And how, monks, is a monk one who has completely cut off all searches? Here, monks, a monk has abandoned the search for sensual pleasures, abandoned the search for existence, and the search for the holy life has been calmed. Thus, monks, is a monk who has completely cut off all searches. And how, monks, is a monk one whose thoughts are unblemished? Here, monks, a monk has abandoned sensual thought, abandoned ill-will thought, abandoned harmful thought. Thus, monks, is a monk whose thoughts are unblemished. And how, monks, is a monk one whose mental activities are calmed? Here, monks, a monk, with the abandoning of pleasure and pain, with the previous passing away of joy and grief, enters and dwells in the fourth jhāna, neither painful nor pleasant, with equanimity and mindfulness purified. Thus, monks, is a monk whose mental activities are calmed. And how, monks, is a monk one whose mind is well liberated? Here, monks, a monk’s mind is liberated from greed, liberated from hatred, liberated from delusion. Thus, monks, is a monk whose mind is well liberated. And how, monks, is a monk one whose wisdom is well liberated? Here, monks, a monk knows: ‘Greed has been abandoned in me, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future’; knows: ‘Hatred has been abandoned in me …’; knows: ‘Delusion has been abandoned in me, cut off at the root, made like a palm stump, made non-existent, unable to arise in the future.’ Thus, monks, is a monk whose wisdom is well liberated. Monks, all those noble ones in the past who lived the noble dwelling — they lived these ten noble dwellings. All those noble ones in the future who will live the noble dwelling — they will live these ten noble dwellings. All those noble ones in the present who live the noble dwelling — they live these ten noble dwellings. These, monks, are the ten noble dwellings that the noble ones have lived, are living, and will live.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, for direct knowledge of craving, ten things should be developed. What ten? The perception of foulness, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of not-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation. For direct knowledge of craving, monks, these ten things should be developed.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.237", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.237/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Good sirs, if a monk, reflecting, knows: ‘I dwell much with a greedy mind; I dwell much with a hateful mind; I dwell much with a mind overcome by sloth and torpor; I dwell much with restlessness; I dwell much with doubt; I dwell much with anger; I dwell much with a defiled mind; I dwell much with bodily fever; I dwell much with laziness; I dwell much with an unconcentrated mind’ — then that monk should make a strong wish, arouse effort, be energetic, strive, be strong-minded, not fall away, be mindful and clearly comprehending for the abandonment of those evil, unwholesome states. Just as, good sirs, if a turban or head were on fire, one would make a strong wish, arouse effort, be energetic, strive, be strong-minded, not fall away, be mindful and clearly comprehending to extinguish that turban or head — so too, that monk should make a strong wish … for the abandonment of those evil, unwholesome states. If a monk, reflecting, knows: ‘I dwell much with a mind free from greed; I dwell much with a mind free from hatred; I dwell much with a mind free from sloth and torpor; I dwell much with a mind free from restlessness; I dwell much with a mind that has overcome doubt; I dwell much with a mind free from anger; I dwell much with an undefiled mind; I dwell much with a body free from fever; I dwell much with an energetic, striving mind; I dwell much with a concentrated mind’ — then that monk, established in those wholesome states, should further devote himself to the destruction of the defilements.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.52", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.52/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Sāriputta, while a noble disciple attains and dwells in the rapture born of seclusion, during that time five things do not occur for him: pain and grief connected with sensuality do not occur; pleasure and joy connected with sensuality do not occur; pain and grief connected with the unwholesome do not occur; pleasure and joy connected with the unwholesome do not occur; pain and grief connected with the wholesome do not occur. Sāriputta, while a noble disciple attains and dwells in the rapture born of seclusion, during that time these five things do not occur for him.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.176", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.176/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these five dangers for one who is mindless, not clearly comprehending, and falls asleep. What five? He sleeps badly; he wakes up badly; he has bad dreams; devas do not protect him; impure things flow out, nocturnal emission. These, monks, are the five dangers for one who is mindless, not clearly comprehending, and falls asleep. Monks, there are these five benefits for one who is mindful, clearly comprehending, and falls asleep. What five? He sleeps well; he wakes up well; he has no bad dreams; devas protect him; impure things do not flow out. These, monks, are the five benefits for one who is mindful, clearly comprehending, and falls asleep.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.210", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.210/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these five mental shackles. What five? Here, monks, a monk is not free from lust, desire, affection, thirst, fever, craving for sensual pleasures. Monks, for a monk who is not free from lust … craving for sensual pleasures, his mind does not incline to exertion, commitment, persistence, striving. If one’s mind does not incline to exertion, commitment, persistence, striving, that is the first mental shackle.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 5.206", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an5.206/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these three things. What three? Sensual thought, ill-will thought, harmful thought. Monks, these are the three things. To abandon these three things, three things should be developed. What three? To abandon sensual thought, the thought of renunciation should be developed. To abandon ill-will thought, the thought of non-ill-will should be developed. To abandon harmful thought, the thought of harmlessness should be developed. To abandon those three things, monks, these three things should be developed.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.109/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Fear, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. Suffering, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. Disease, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. A boil, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. Clinging, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. A bog, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. And why, monks, is fear a synonym for sensual pleasures? Monks, infatuated by sensual desire, bound by sensual desire, one is not free from fear in this very life, nor free from fear in the future. Therefore, fear is a synonym for sensual pleasures.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.23/en/sujato" },


{ text: `“Monks, with unguarded faculties, with deficiency in guarding the faculties, virtue is destroyed. With no virtue, with deficiency in virtue, right concentration is destroyed. With no right concentration, with deficiency in right concentration, true knowledge and vision are destroyed. With no true knowledge and vision, with deficiency in true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are destroyed. With no disenchantment and dispassion, with deficiency in disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation are destroyed. Just as, monks, a tree with deficient branches and foliage — its shoots do not reach perfection, its bark does not reach perfection, its sapwood does not reach perfection, its heartwood does not reach perfection. So too, monks, with unguarded faculties, with deficiency in guarding the faculties … the knowledge and vision of liberation are destroyed.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.50", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.50/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, with guarded faculties, with completeness in guarding the faculties, virtue is complete. With virtue present, with completeness in virtue, right concentration is complete. With right concentration present, with completeness in right concentration, true knowledge and vision are complete. With true knowledge and vision present, with completeness in true knowledge and vision, disenchantment and dispassion are complete. With disenchantment and dispassion present, with completeness in disenchantment and dispassion, the knowledge and vision of liberation are complete. Just as, monks, a tree with complete branches and foliage — its shoots reach perfection, its bark reaches perfection, its sapwood reaches perfection, its heartwood reaches perfection. So too, monks, with guarded faculties, with completeness in guarding the faculties … the knowledge and vision of liberation are complete.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.50", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.50/en/sujato" },

{ text: `One whose mind inclines to renunciation,<br>His heart tends toward seclusion;<br>One whose mind inclines to non-ill-will,<br>His heart tends toward the cessation of clinging;<br>One whose mind inclines to the cessation of craving,<br>His heart tends toward the absence of delusion;<br>Seeing the place of arising,<br>His mind is rightly liberated.<br>For one rightly liberated,<br>The monk with a pure mind,<br>There is nothing further to do,<br>Nothing remains to be done.<br>Like a solid mass of rock,<br>Unmoved by the wind,<br>So too, all forms,<br>Tastes, sounds, smells, contacts,<br>And all phenomena —<br>Agreeable or disagreeable —<br>Cannot disturb one such as this,<br>Whose mind is steady, liberated,<br>Seeing the nature of their cessation.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.55", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.55/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Contact, monks, is one extreme. The origination of contact is the second extreme. The cessation of contact is the middle. Craving is the weaver; for craving weaves one to be reborn in this or that state of existence. Thus, monks, a monk directly knows what should be directly known, fully understands what should be fully understood. By directly knowing what should be directly known and fully understanding what should be fully understood, he makes an end of suffering here and now.<br>Knowing both extremes,<br>Not stained in the middle,<br>I call that great person,<br>He has surpassed the weaver.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.61", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.61/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure: forms cognizable by the eye — desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing; sounds cognizable by the ear … odors … tastes … touches cognizable by the body — desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing. Although they are not sensual pleasures, monks, in the noble one’s discipline they are called the strands of sensual pleasure.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Thoughts of lust<br>Are the sensual pleasures of humans,<br>The beautiful things in the world<br>Are not themselves sensual pleasures.<br>Thoughts of lust<br>Are the sensual pleasures of humans.<br>The beautiful things remain<br>As they are in the world,<br>But the wise here<br>Subdue their lust.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘For life, the arahants have abandoned unchastity, live the holy life, live secluded, abstaining from sexual intercourse, the low practice. Today, this night and day, I too abandon unchastity, live the holy life, live secluded, abstaining from sexual intercourse, the low practice. In this factor, I follow the arahants and will observe the uposatha day.’”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.41", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.41/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, for direct knowledge of greed, six things should be developed. What six? The perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of not-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation. For direct knowledge of greed, monks, these six things should be developed.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 6.142", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an6.142/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the perception of foulness, when developed and cultivated, is of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, having the deathless as its end. For what reason is this said? When a monk dwells much with the perception of foulness, his mind retreats, turns back, and draws away from sexual intercourse, and thus his mind is not strained, becomes peaceful, and disenchantment arises. Just as, monks, a cock’s feather or a sinew thrown into fire retreats, turns back, draws away, and is not strained — so too, when a monk dwells much with the perception of foulness, his mind retreats, turns back, draws away from sexual intercourse, and thus his mind is not strained, becomes peaceful, and disenchantment arises. If a monk dwells much with the perception of foulness, yet his mind still runs after, gets stuck in sexual intercourse, and disenchantment does not arise, then he should understand: ‘The perception of foulness is not developed in me; there is no distinction before and after in me; I have not attained the fruit of development.’ There he is clearly aware. If a monk dwells much with the perception of foulness, his mind retreats, turns back, draws away from sexual intercourse, his mind is not strained, becomes peaceful, and disenchantment arises, then he should understand: ‘The perception of foulness is developed in me; there is a distinction before and after in me; I have attained the fruit of development.’ There he is clearly aware. That the perception of foulness, when developed and cultivated, is of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, having the deathless as its end — for this reason it is said.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.49", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.49/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, a woman, attending to her own female faculties, female deportment, female attire, female nature, female desires, female voice, female adornment — becomes lustful and delights in them. Through being lustful and delighting in them, she attends to external male faculties, male deportment, male attire, male nature, male desires, male voice, male adornment, and becomes lustful and delights in them. Through being lustful and delighting in them, she desires external bonding. With that bonding as condition, pleasure and joy arise, and she desires that pleasure and joy. Monks, through delighting in their own femininity, beings become bonded to men. Thus, monks, a woman does not escape her own femininity.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, a man, attending to his own male faculties, male deportment, male attire, male nature, male desires, male voice, male adornment — becomes lustful and delights in them. Through being lustful and delighting in them, he attends to external female faculties, female deportment, female attire, female nature, female desires, female voice, female adornment, and becomes lustful and delights in them. Through being lustful and delighting in them, he desires external bonding. With that bonding as condition, pleasure and joy arise, and he desires that pleasure and joy. Monks, through delighting in their own masculinity, beings become bonded to women. Thus, monks, a man does not escape his own masculinity.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 7.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an7.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, misconduct in sensual pleasures, when performed, developed, and cultivated, leads to hell, to the animal realm, to the realm of hungry ghosts. The very least result of misconduct in sensual pleasures is being born human with enmity from adversaries.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.40", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.40/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Fear, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. Suffering, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. Disease, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. A boil, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. A dart, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. Bondage, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. Mud, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures. A womb, monks, is a synonym for sensual pleasures.<br>How, monks, is fear a synonym for sensual pleasures? Because those who are infected by sensual desire, bound by sensual lust, are not freed from fear in the present life, not freed from fear in the future — therefore fear is a synonym for sensual pleasures.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.56/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Fear, suffering, and disease,<br>A boil, and a dart,<br>Bondage and mud,<br>And also a womb —<br>These are called sensual pleasures,<br>Where worldlings become attached,<br>Sinking into the beautiful,<br>They enter a womb again.<br>When a monk is ardent,<br>Not lax, mindful,<br>He crosses this dangerous path,<br>This path so hard to cross.<br>He sees beings living in fear,<br>Because of birth and aging,<br>Oppressed and conquered.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.56/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘My mind will be internally established, well fixed. Evil, unwholesome states that arise will not invade my mind and will not stand.’ Thus, monk, you should train.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘I will dwell contemplating the body as a body, ardent, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and sorrow in the world.’ Thus, monk, you should train. Monk, when this concentration of yours is developed and cultivated in this way, then, monk, you should develop this concentration with initial and sustained thought; you should develop it without initial thought but with sustained thought; you should develop it without initial and sustained thought; you should develop it with rapture; you should develop it without rapture; you should develop it accompanied by pleasure; you should develop it accompanied by equanimity. Monk, when this concentration of yours is developed and cultivated in this way, then, monk, wherever you go, you will go at ease; wherever you stand, you will stand at ease; wherever you sit, you will sit at ease; wherever you lie down, you will lie down at ease.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 8.63", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an8.63/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And, monks, when that monk dwells in these five things, four more things should be developed. The perception of foulness should be developed to abandon greed; loving-kindness should be developed to abandon ill-will; mindfulness of breathing should be developed to cut off thoughts; the perception of impermanence should be developed to uproot the conceit ‘I am.’ For a monk with the perception of impermanence, monks, the perception of not-self becomes established. For one with the perception of not-self, the conceit ‘I am’ is uprooted, and Nibbāna is attained in this very life.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“A boil, monks, is a synonym for this body composed of the four great elements, born of mother and father, nourished with boiled rice and porridge, impermanent, subject to rubbing, pressing, breaking, dissolution, and destruction. It has nine wound openings, nine natural orifices. From these, whatever flows out is inevitably impure, foul-smelling, and disgusting; whatever issues out is inevitably impure, foul-smelling, and disgusting. Therefore, monks, be disenchanted with this body.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.15/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these nine perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, having the deathless as their end. What nine? The perception of foulness, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of not-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion. These nine perceptions, monks, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, having the deathless as their end.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“‘For life, the arahants have abandoned unchastity, live the holy life, live secluded, abstaining from sexual intercourse, the low practice. Today, this night and day, I too abandon unchastity, live the holy life, live secluded, abstaining from sexual intercourse, the low practice. In this factor, I follow the arahants and will observe the uposatha day.’ This is the third factor attained.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.18/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I will teach you nine things rooted in craving. Listen and pay close attention. And what, monks, are the nine things rooted in craving? Dependent on craving, seeking arises; dependent on seeking, gain arises; dependent on gain, decision arises; dependent on decision, desire and lust arise; dependent on desire and lust, attachment arises; dependent on attachment, possessiveness arises; dependent on possessiveness, guarding arises; dependent on guarding, the taking up of sticks and swords, quarrels, disputes, arguments, slander, false speech, and many evil, unwholesome states arise. These, monks, are the nine things rooted in craving.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.23", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.23/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these five strands of sensual pleasure. What five? Forms cognizable by the eye — desirable, agreeable, pleasant, charming, connected with sensuality, enticing; sounds cognizable by the ear … odors … tastes … touches cognizable by the body — desirable … enticing. These, monks, are the five strands of sensual pleasure. To abandon these five strands of sensual pleasure, monks, the four foundations of mindfulness should be developed.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 9.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an9.65/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“So too, monks, a monk reflecting thus gains great benefit in wholesome states. ‘Do I dwell much with greed? Do I dwell much without greed? Do I dwell much with a mind of ill-will? Do I dwell much with a mind without ill-will? Do I dwell much overcome by sloth and torpor, or do I dwell much with sloth and torpor abandoned? Do I dwell much with restlessness, or do I dwell much without restlessness? Do I dwell much with doubt, or do I dwell much with doubt overcome? Do I dwell much with anger, or do I dwell much without anger? Do I dwell much with a defiled mind, or do I dwell much with an undefiled mind? Do I dwell much with bodily fever, or do I dwell much without bodily fever? Do I dwell much with laziness, or do I dwell much with energy and striving? Do I dwell much unconcentrated, or do I dwell much concentrated?’”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, if a monk, reflecting thus, knows: ‘I dwell much with a greedy mind; I dwell much with a hateful mind; I dwell much with a mind overcome by sloth and torpor; I dwell much with restlessness; I dwell much with doubt; I dwell much with anger; I dwell much with a defiled mind; I dwell much with bodily fever; I dwell much with laziness; I dwell much unconcentrated’ — then that monk should make a strong wish, arouse effort, be energetic, strive, be strong-minded, not fall away, be mindful and clearly comprehending for the abandonment of those evil, unwholesome states. Just as, monks, if a turban or head were on fire, one would make a strong wish, arouse effort, be energetic, strive, be strong-minded, not fall away, be mindful and clearly comprehending to extinguish that turban or head — so too, that monk should make a strong wish … for the abandonment of those evil, unwholesome states.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.51", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.51/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, having the deathless as their end. What ten? The perception of impermanence, the perception of not-self, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of a skeleton, the perception of a worm-infested corpse, the perception of a livid corpse, the perception of a fissured corpse, the perception of a bloated corpse. These ten perceptions, monks, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, having the deathless as their end.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.57", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.57/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these ten perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, having the deathless as their end. What ten? The perception of foulness, the perception of death, the perception of disgust with food, the perception of non-delight in the entire world, the perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of not-self in suffering, the perception of abandoning, the perception of dispassion, the perception of cessation. These ten perceptions, monks, when developed and cultivated, are of great fruit, great benefit, merging with the deathless, having the deathless as their end.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.56", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.56/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, you should train thus: ‘Our minds will be trained and accumulated as when we went forth; unarisen unwholesome states will not overcome our minds and persist; our minds will be trained and accumulated with the perception of impermanence; our minds will be trained and accumulated with the perception of not-self; our minds will be trained and accumulated with the perception of foulness; our minds will be trained and accumulated with the perception of peril; having known the world’s even and uneven, our minds will be trained and accumulated with that perception; having known the world’s arising and passing away, our minds will be trained and accumulated with that perception; having known the world’s origination and cessation, our minds will be trained and accumulated with that perception; our minds will be trained and accumulated with the perception of abandoning; our minds will be trained and accumulated with the perception of dispassion; our minds will be trained and accumulated with the perception of cessation.’ Thus, monks, you should train.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.59/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, Ānanda, is the perception of peril? Here, Ānanda, a monk, going to the forest, to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, reflects: ‘This body is of much suffering, of much peril. Various diseases arise in this body, such as: eye disease, ear disease, nose disease, tongue disease, body disease, head disease, ear-edge disease, mouth disease, tooth disease, cough, asthma, catarrh, fever, aging, abdominal pain, fainting, dysentery, colic, cholera, leprosy, boils, eczema, tuberculosis, epilepsy, skin disease, itch, scab, ringworm, scabies, blood-bile disorder, diabetes, hemorrhoids, cancer, sores, ulcerations; diseases born of bile, born of phlegm, born of wind, born of the combination of humors; diseases born of change of season, born of improper behavior, born of sudden assault, born of the result of kamma; cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation, urination.’ Thus he dwells contemplating peril in this body.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.60", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.60/en/sujato" },

{ text: `- “Venerable Sāriputta, what is happiness? What is suffering?”<br>- “Friend, rebirth is suffering; non-rebirth is happiness. When there is rebirth, friend, this suffering is to be expected: cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation, urination, contact with fire, contact with a stick, contact with a sword. Even relatives and friends, when they meet and gather together, cause distress. Friend, rebirth is suffering; when there is rebirth, this suffering is to be expected. When there is no rebirth, friend, this happiness is to be expected: no cold, no heat, no hunger, no thirst, no defecation, no urination, no contact with fire, no contact with a stick, no contact with a sword. Even relatives and friends, when they meet and gather together, do not cause distress. Friend, when there is no rebirth, this happiness is to be expected.”`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.65", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.65/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Few among humans<br>Reach the further shore,<br>While the rest of humankind<br>Run up and down on this shore.<br>Those who practice the Dhamma<br>In accordance with the well-taught Dhamma,<br>Will reach the further shore,<br>Beyond the realm of death, so hard to escape.<br>The wise, having left the dark state,<br>Should develop the bright,<br>Leaving home for the homeless life,<br>Living in seclusion, where pleasure is hard to find.<br>Seeking delight in Nibbāna,<br>Having abandoned sensual pleasures, without possessions,<br>The wise should cleanse themselves<br>Of defilements of the mind.<br>Those who have well developed the factors of enlightenment<br>With a mind rightly directed,<br>Who, without clinging, delight in the abandoning of grasping —<br>They, the defilement-free, the radiant,<br>Attain final Nibbāna in the world.`, ref: "Aṅguttara Nikāya 10.117", url: "https://suttacentral.net/an10.117/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Mind precedes all mental states,<br>Mind is their chief; they are all mind-made.<br>If with an impure mind one speaks or acts,<br>Suffering follows like the wheel that follows the ox’s foot.”<br><br>“Mind precedes all mental states,<br>Mind is their chief; they are all mind-made.<br>If with a pure mind one speaks or acts,<br>Happiness follows like a shadow that never leaves.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“He who dwells attending to the beautiful,<br>Unrestrained in the senses,<br>Immoderate in food,<br>Lazy, inactive —<br>Māra overthrows him<br>As wind a weak tree.”<br><br>“He who dwells contemplating the foul,<br>Well-restrained in the senses,<br>Moderate in food,<br>Faithful, energetic —<br>Māra does not overthrow him,<br>As wind a rocky mountain.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“As rain seeps into a house with a faulty roof,<br>So lust seeps into an undeveloped mind.”<br><br>“As rain does not seep into a house with a good roof,<br>So lust does not seep into a well-developed mind.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 1-20", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp1-20/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“The mind is fickle and restless,<br>Hard to guard, hard to restrain.<br>The wise make it straight,<br>Like a fletcher straightens an arrow.”<br><br>“Like a fish thrown on dry ground,<br>Wrenched from its watery home,<br>This mind struggles and thrashes<br>To escape Māra’s grip.”<br><br>“Hard to hold, fickle,<br>It jumps where it wishes.<br>Good is it to tame the mind —<br>A tamed mind brings happiness.”<br><br>“The mind is hard to see, subtle,<br>It jumps where it wishes.<br>The wise guard the mind —<br>A guarded mind brings happiness.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 33-43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp33-43/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Knowing this body to be like a clay pot,<br>Fortifying this mind like a city,<br>Fight Māra with the sword of wisdom,<br>Guard your conquest, and be free of attachment.”<br><br>“Before long, alas, this body<br>Will lie on the ground,<br>Cast aside, devoid of consciousness,<br>Like a useless log.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 33-43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp33-43/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Knowing this body to be like foam,<br>Realizing its mirage-like nature,<br>Breaking Māra’s flower-tipped arrows,<br>One goes beyond the sight of the King of Death.”<br><br>“He who gathers flowers of sensual pleasures,<br>With mind attached, infatuated,<br>Death carries him away<br>As a flood sweeps away a sleeping village.”<br><br>“He who gathers flowers of sensual pleasures,<br>With mind attached, infatuated,<br>Before he has had his fill of sensual pleasures,<br>Is overpowered by death.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 44-59", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp44-59/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Fletchers make arrows,<br>Potters make pots,<br>Carpenters shape wood,<br>The wise tame themselves.”<br><br>“Like a solid rock<br>Unmoved by the wind,<br>So the wise are unmoved<br>Amid praise and blame.”<br><br>“Like a deep lake,<br>Clear, unruffled,<br>So the wise become serene,<br>Hearing the Dhamma.”<br><br>“The good renounce everything,<br>The virtuous do not prattle about sensual desires.<br>Whether touched by pleasure or pain,<br>The wise show neither elation nor depression.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 76-89", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp76-89/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Why laughter, why joy,<br>When the world is always burning?<br>Shrouded in darkness,<br>Why do you not seek a light?”<br><br>“Behold this painted image,<br>This heap of wounds,<br>Diseased, full of many thoughts,<br>Of nothing stable or lasting.”<br><br>“This form is worn out,<br>A nest of diseases, fragile;<br>This putrid mass breaks apart —<br>Death is the end of life.”<br><br>“Like a gourd in autumn,<br>Abandoned and cast away,<br>Seeing these bleached bones,<br>What pleasure can there be?”`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“This city is built of bones,<br>Plastered with flesh and blood;<br>Within dwells aging and death,<br>Conceit and hypocrisy.”<br><br>“Even the king’s splendid chariot wears out,<br>So too this body eventually ages.<br>But the Dhamma of the good does not age —<br>So the good indeed speak to the good.”<br><br>“A person of little learning,<br>Like an ox, grows old;<br>His flesh increases,<br>But not his wisdom.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Through many a birth in samsara I have wandered,<br>Seeking but not finding the builder of this house.<br>Suffering is birth again and again.”<br><br>“O house-builder, you are seen!<br>You shall not build a house again.<br>All your rafters are broken,<br>Your ridge-pole is shattered.<br>My mind has attained the unconditioned,<br>And the extinction of craving has been reached.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 146-156", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp146-156/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who once was heedless and later is not,<br>Illumines the world like the moon freed from clouds.”<br><br>“He who deeds of merit makes,<br>And thereby his evil deeds dispels,<br>Illumines the world like the moon freed from clouds.”<br><br>“Blinded is this world,<br>Few are those who see clearly.<br>Like birds escaped from a net,<br>Few go to heaven.”<br><br>“Like a swan flying through the sky,<br>With psychic power soaring through space,<br>Having conquered Māra and his host,<br>The wise one leaves this world behind.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 167-178", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp167-178/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Though one should rain down golden coins,<br>One’s desires are not satisfied.<br>Little sweetness, much bitterness —<br>Knowing this, the wise one understands.”<br><br>“The disciple of the Perfectly Enlightened One<br>Does not seek sensual pleasures,<br>Even heavenly ones —<br>He delights only in the destruction of craving.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 179-196", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp179-196/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“From attachment arises grief,<br>From attachment arises fear.<br>For one freed from attachment,<br>there’s no grief–so how fear?”<br><br>“From delight arises grief,<br>From delight arises fear.<br>For one freed from delight,<br>there’s no grief–so how fear?”<br><br>“From sensual desire arises grief,<br>From sensual desire arises fear.<br>For one freed from sensual desire,<br>there’s no grief–so how fear?”<br><br>“From craving arises grief,<br>From craving arises fear.<br>For one freed from craving,<br>there’s no grief–so how fear?”`, ref: "Dhammapada 209-220", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp209-220/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“All conditioned things are impermanent” —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering —<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>“All conditioned things are suffering” —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering —<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>“All phenomena are not-self” —<br>When one sees this with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering —<br>This is the path to purity.`, ref: "Dhammapada 273-289", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp273-289/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Cut down the forest, not just a tree —<br>From the forest, fear is born.<br>Having cut down both forest and undergrowth,<br>Be forest-free, O monks.”<br><br>“As long as even the smallest desire<br>Of a man for women is not cut off,<br>His mind is bound like a suckling calf to its mother.”<br><br>“Cut off your affection,<br>Like plucking an autumn lotus with the hand.<br>Develop the path to peace, Nibbāna,<br>Taught by the Well-gone One.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 273-289", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp273-289/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“For a person who lives heedlessly,<br>Craving grows like a creeping vine.<br>He leaps from life to life,<br>Like a monkey seeking fruit in the forest.”<br><br>“Whoever in this world is overcome by this wretched clinging,<br>His sorrows increase like well-watered birana grass.”<br><br>“Whoever in this world overcomes this wretched clinging,<br>Sorrows fall away from him like water drops from a lotus.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“This good teaching I give to you —<br>You who have gathered here.<br>Dig up the root of craving<br>Like digging up birana grass.<br>Do not let Māra destroy you,<br>Like a flood destroying reeds.”<br><br>“Even though a tree is cut down,<br>If its root remains uncut,<br>The tree grows back —<br>So too, if the latent tendency to craving is not uprooted,<br>Suffering arises again and again.”<br><br>“The thirty-six streams of craving<br>Sweep away a person who is bent on pleasing thoughts —<br>Thoughts of lust,<br>Sweeping him away with wrong view.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“The stream of craving flows everywhere,<br>The creeper of craving sprouts and stands.<br>Seeing that creeper that has arisen,<br>Cut its root with wisdom.”<br><br>“People, immersed in sensual pleasures,<br>Delight in various pleasures.<br>Though they seek happiness,<br>They undergo birth and aging.”<br><br>“People bound by craving,<br>Thrashing about, terrified,<br>Like hares caught in a snare —<br>Bound by craving,<br>They undergo suffering for a long time.”<br><br>“People bound by craving,<br>Thrashing about, terrified,<br>Like hares caught in a snare —<br>Therefore, a monk who desires his own dispassion<br>Should abandon craving.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“A person intoxicated by craving<br>Throws himself into the stream<br>Like a spider into its own web.<br>But the wise cut it off,<br>Having abandoned all suffering, they wander on without desire.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who restrains evil intent,<br>Seeing the beautiful with sharp desire —<br>That person’s craving increases;<br>He makes the fetter strong.”<br><br>“One who delights in calming the mind,<br>Always contemplating foulness, mindful —<br>That person will destroy craving;<br>He cuts off Māra’s fetter.”<br><br>“One who has reached the goal, without fear,<br>Free from craving, without defilement,<br>Having pulled out the dart of existence —<br>This body is his last.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 334-359", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp334-359/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Good is restraint over the eye,<br>Good is restraint over the ear,<br>Good is restraint over the nose,<br>Good is restraint over the tongue.”<br><br>“Good is restraint over the body,<br>Good is restraint over speech,<br>Good is restraint over the mind,<br>Good is restraint everywhere.<br>A monk restrained everywhere<br>Is freed from all suffering.”<br><br>“One who controls his hands and feet,<br>Controls his speech and his head,<br>Delights in inner seclusion,<br>Is content, lives alone —<br>Him they call a monk.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monk, cultivate seclusion,<br>Do not be heedless,<br>Do not let your mind whirl in sensual pleasures.<br>If you are heedless, you will swallow a hot iron ball,<br>And when burned, do not cry out in pain!”<br><br>“Without wisdom, there is no jhāna;<br>Without jhāna, there is no wisdom.<br>One who has both jhāna and wisdom<br>Is indeed close to Nibbāna.”<br><br>“Entering an empty house,<br>A monk with a peaceful mind<br>Experiences a superhuman delight<br>In the clear vision of the Dhamma.”<br><br>“When he clearly comprehends<br>The arising and passing away of the aggregates,<br>He gains joy and rapture —<br>That is the deathless for those who know.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 360-382", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp360-382/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“O brahmin, strive to cut the stream,<br>Abandon sensual pleasures.<br>Knowing the destruction of formations,<br>You will be the one who knows the Unmade.”<br><br>“By always dwelling in two Dhammas,<br>One reaches the further shore.<br>That brahmin, wise,<br>Cuts off all fetters.”<br><br>“One who has no near shore, no far shore,<br>No both shores,<br>Free from suffering, unbound —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”<br><br>“Meditating, free from dust,<br>Duty done, without defilements,<br>Having attained the highest goal —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One without craving, wise,<br>Without doubt,<br>Having merged into the deathless —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”<br><br>“One who in this world<br>Is not stained by good and evil,<br>Griefless, stainless, pure —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”<br><br>“Like the moon, stainless,<br>Clear, pure, calm,<br>With craving for existence destroyed —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”<br><br>“Who has crossed this dangerous path,<br>Saṃsāra and delusion,<br>Gone to the further shore,<br>Meditative, without sensual desire, without doubt,<br>Not clinging, at peace —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who in this world has abandoned sensuality,<br>Left home, gone forth,<br>With sensual desire and existence destroyed —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”<br><br>“One who in this world has abandoned craving,<br>Left home, gone forth,<br>With craving and existence destroyed —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”<br><br>“Having abandoned the human yoke,<br>Transcended the heavenly yoke,<br>Free from all bondage —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”<br><br>“Having abandoned liking and disliking,<br>Cool, free from attachments,<br>A hero who conquers all worlds,<br>Who subdues all —<br>Him I call a brahmin.”`, ref: "Dhammapada 383-423", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dhp383-423/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Seclusion is happiness<br>For one who knows contentment,<br>For one who has heard the Dhamma,<br>For one who sees rightly.<br><br>Non-ill-will is happiness<br>For those in the world<br>Who practice self-restraint<br>Toward living beings.<br><br>Dispassion is happiness<br>For those who transcend sensual pleasures,<br>Who subdue the conceit ‘I am’ —<br>This is the highest happiness.`, ref: "Udana 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud2.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Who has crossed this mud,<br>Crushed the thorn of sensuality,<br>Attained the destruction of delusion —<br>Such a monk,<br>Does not feel pleasure or pain!`, ref: "Udana 3.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Who has conquered the thorn of sensuality,<br>Insult, injury, bondage,<br>That one stands firm,<br>Like a mountain unshaken —<br>Such a monk,<br>Pleasure and pain do not disturb.`, ref: "Udana 3.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Dependent on attachment, this suffering arises. By the complete destruction of all attachments, suffering does not come to be.<br><br>See the world with its multitude,<br>Overcome by ignorance,<br>Beings given to birth,<br>Delighting in becoming,<br>Not freed from existence.<br><br>For one who burns up existence,<br>At all times and places,<br>All this existence —<br>Impermanent, suffering, subject to change —<br><br>Seeing this as it really is<br>With perfect wisdom,<br>Craving for existence is abandoned,<br>As is the delight in non-existence.<br><br>With the complete destruction of craving,<br>Dispassion, cessation, complete,<br>That is Nibbāna.<br>That monk, cooled,<br>Without clinging to renewed existence,<br>Has conquered Māra,<br>Won the battle,<br>Crossed over all forms of existence.”`, ref: "Udana 3.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud3.10/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, Meghiya, for a monk well established in these five things, four more things are to be developed: foulness should be developed to abandon greed; loving-kindness should be developed to abandon ill-will; mindfulness of breathing should be developed to cut off thoughts; the perception of impermanence should be developed to uproot the conceit ‘I am.’ For one with the perception of impermanence, Meghiya, the perception of not-self becomes established. For one with the perception of not-self, the uprooting of the conceit ‘I am’ is attained, Nibbāna in this very life.”`, ref: "Udana 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `One whose mind is like a rock,<br>Firm, not shaken,<br>Without greed for the agreeable,<br>Without hatred for the disagreeable —<br>One whose mind is thus developed —<br>From where can suffering come?`, ref: "Udana 4.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud4.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Here, venerable sir, many people in Sāvatthi are mostly intoxicated with sensual pleasures, living as if drunk, attached, lustful, infatuated, bound, and bewitched by sensual pleasures.” The Blessed One, understanding the meaning, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Beings are attached<br>To various sensual pleasures,<br>They see no fault<br>In the defilements that fetter.<br><br>Indeed, beings bound by fetters,<br>Do not cross over<br>This great, broad flood.`, ref: "Udana 7.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Then the Blessed One saw those people in Sāvatthi, mostly intoxicated with sensual pleasures, living as if drunk, attached, lustful, infatuated, bound, and bewitched by sensual pleasures. Then the Blessed One, understanding the meaning, on that occasion uttered this inspired utterance:<br><br>Blinded by sensual pleasures,<br>Covered by a net,<br>Veiled by craving,<br>Bound by the fetter of heedlessness —<br>Like fish caught in a net,<br>They go to aging and death,<br>Like a suckling calf to its mother.`, ref: "Udana 7.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/ud7.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, abandon one thing. I guarantee you no further rebirth. What one thing? Greed, monks, is that one thing. Abandon it! I guarantee you no further rebirth.” The Blessed One spoke this meaning. Here it is said:<br><br>With greed, beings,<br>Infatuated, go to a bad destination.<br>But the meditator, with right knowledge,<br>Abandons that greed.<br>Having abandoned it, he never<br>Returns to this world again.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, one who does not directly know and fully understand everything, not having his mind dispassionate toward it, abandoning it, cannot make an end of suffering. One who directly knows and fully understands everything, having his mind dispassionate toward it, abandoning it, can make an end of suffering.” The Blessed One spoke this meaning. Here it is said:<br><br>One who knows and understands<br>Everything as everything,<br>And does not lust for anything anywhere —<br>Such a one, indeed,<br>Has fully understood everything<br>And can pass beyond<br>All suffering.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I do not see any other hindrance by which beings, hindered, wander and transmigrate for a long time as this hindrance of ignorance. Monks, hindered by the hindrance of ignorance, beings wander and transmigrate for a long time.<br><br>No other thing so hinders beings,<br>That they run on by day and night,<br>As that of delusion’s snare.<br><br>But one who has abandoned delusion,<br>Pierced through the mass of darkness,<br>No longer wanders on —<br>In them the cause is no more.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, I do not see any other fetter by which beings, fettered, wander and transmigrate for a long time as this fetter of craving. Monks, fettered by the fetter of craving, beings wander and transmigrate for a long time.<br><br>One with craving as companion<br>Wanders on for a long time.<br>Neither here nor there beyond such becoming<br>Can they cross the wandering.<br><br>Knowing this peril — that craving<br>Is the origin of suffering —<br>Free from craving, without clinging,<br>Mindful, the monk lives the homeless life.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti15/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the bones of a single person, if collected and preserved without being destroyed, would form a heap of bones, a pile of bones, a mass of bones as great as this Mount Vepulla.<br><br>The bones of a single person<br>Accumulated in one lifetime<br>Would be a heap like a mountain —<br>So said the Great Sage.<br><br>This great mountain of bones<br>Is called Vepulla,<br>North of Vulture’s Peak<br>In the Magadhan hills.<br><br>But one who sees the Four Noble Truths<br>With perfect wisdom —<br>Suffering and its origin,<br>The transcending of suffering,<br>The Noble Eightfold Path<br>Leading to suffering’s stilling —<br><br>That person, wandering at most<br>Seven more times,<br>Makes an end of suffering,<br>Destroying all fetters.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 24", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti24/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“There is, monks, an unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned. If there were not that unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned, no escape would be discerned from the born, become, made, conditioned. But because there is an unborn, unbecome, unmade, unconditioned, therefore escape is discerned from the born, become, made, conditioned.”<br><br>That which is born, become, arisen,<br>Made, conditioned, impermanent,<br>Composed of aging and death,<br>A nest of disease, perishable,<br>Born from nutriment and craving —<br>That is not fit to delight in.<br><br>But the escape from that —<br>Peace, beyond reasoning,<br>Unborn, unbecome,<br>The sorrowless state, the path without defilement,<br>The cessation of painful states,<br>The stilling of conditioned things —<br>That is happiness.`, ref: "Itivuttaka 43", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti43/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these three kinds of craving. What three? Craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for non-existence. These, monks, are the three kinds of craving.<br><br>Bound by the bondage of craving,<br>Their minds attached to becoming and non-becoming,<br>Bound by Māra’s bondage,<br>Those beings are not secure from bondage.<br>They go on in the wandering,<br>Gone to birth and death.<br><br>But those who have abandoned craving,<br>Free from craving for becoming and non-becoming,<br>Having reached the far shore,<br>In this very world, they have attained<br>The destruction of the defilements.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 58", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti58/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, for one whose greed is not abandoned, whose hatred is not abandoned, whose delusion is not abandoned — he is called one who is bound by Māra, trapped in Māra’s snare, subject to the Evil One’s will.<br><br>But, monks, for one whose greed is abandoned, whose hatred is abandoned, whose delusion is abandoned — he is called one not bound by Māra, freed from Māra’s snare, not subject to the Evil One’s will.<br><br>One who has abandoned greed, hatred, and delusion,<br>Him they call one with a developed mind,<br>One who has become Brahmā, the Tathāgata, the Buddha,<br>The one who has overcome enmity and fear,<br>The one who has abandoned all — such a one is called thus.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 68", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti68/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, for any monk or nun whose greed is not abandoned, whose hatred is not abandoned, whose delusion is not abandoned — that one is called one who has not crossed the ocean with its waves, its whirlpools, its sharks, its demons.<br><br>But, monks, for any monk or nun whose greed is abandoned, whose hatred is abandoned, whose delusion is abandoned — that one is called one who has crossed the ocean with its waves, its whirlpools, its sharks, its demons, who has crossed to the far shore, a brahmin standing on dry land.<br><br>One who has abandoned greed, hatred, and delusion<br>Has crossed this ocean with its sharks, demons,<br>Its terrifying waves — so very hard to cross —<br>He has passed beyond all bonds.<br><br>He has abandoned death,<br>Without attachments,<br>He has abandoned suffering,<br>With no further becoming.<br>Having reached the goal, he is immeasurable —<br>I say such a one<br>Has blinded the King of Death.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 69", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti69/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these three elements of escape. What three? The escape from sensual pleasures — that is renunciation. The escape from form — that is the formless. And as to whatever has come to be, is conditioned, dependently arisen, its escape is its cessation. These, monks, are the three elements of escape.<br><br>Knowing the escape from sensual pleasures,<br>And transcending all forms,<br>Always ardent, calming all conditioned things —<br>That monk sees rightly.<br><br>From that, being thus liberated,<br>He perfects direct knowledge,<br>Dwells at peace, in that very life,<br>That sage has crossed beyond all yokes.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 72", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti72/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, this body is subject to destruction, consciousness is subject to vanishing, all attachments are impermanent, suffering, subject to change.<br><br>Knowing the body’s destruction,<br>And that consciousness must vanish,<br>Seeing the peril in attachments,<br>Understanding birth and death —<br><br>Having attained the supreme peace,<br>The mind is well-developed,<br>He simply bides his time.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti77/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, dwell contemplating foulness in the body. Establish well mindfulness of breathing, setting mindfulness before you, inwardly directed. Dwell contemplating impermanence in all conditioned things. For one dwelling contemplating foulness in the body, the underlying tendency to lust for the beautiful is abandoned. For one who has well-established mindfulness of breathing, setting mindfulness before you, inwardly directed, there are no externally directed, harmful thoughts. For one dwelling contemplating impermanence in all conditioned things, ignorance is abandoned and true knowledge arises.<br><br>Contemplating foulness in the body,<br>Mindful of in-breath and out-breath,<br>Calming all conditioned things,<br>Ever ardent, right in view —<br><br>That monk who sees rightly,<br>From that, being thus liberated,<br>Perfects direct knowledge,<br>Is at peace, truly stilled —<br>That sage has certainly crossed beyond all yokes.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti85/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, sensual thought is blind, causes blindness, causes lack of knowledge, leads to the destruction of wisdom, partakes of distress, does not lead to Nibbāna. Monks, ill-will thought is blind … harmful thought is blind, causes blindness, causes lack of knowledge, leads to the destruction of wisdom, partakes of distress, does not lead to Nibbāna.<br><br>Three thoughts of wholesome kind<br>One should frequently reflect upon —<br>Three unwholesome thoughts should be abandoned, turned away from.<br>That one surely restrains<br>The conduct of thoughts.<br><br>As rain settles the dust,<br>So by calming thoughts with the mind,<br>One here and now attains<br>The peaceful path of peace.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 87", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti87/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Greed gives rise to misfortune,<br>Greed stirs up the mind.<br>Greed is the inner fear<br>Born within people.<br>People do not recognize<br>That special kind of greed.<br><br>The greedy person knows not what is good,<br>The greedy person sees not the Dhamma.<br>Blindness and darkness occur<br>Where greed dwells together.<br><br>One who has abandoned greed,<br>Not greedy for what is to be craved,<br>For him greed falls away<br>Like a drop of water from a lotus leaf.<br><br>Hatred gives rise to misfortune,<br>Hatred stirs up the mind.<br>Hatred is the inner fear<br>Born within people.<br>People do not recognize<br>That special kind of hatred.<br><br>The hateful person knows not what is good,<br>The hateful person sees not the Dhamma.<br>Blindness and darkness occur<br>Where hatred dwells together.<br><br>One who has abandoned hatred,<br>Not hating what is hateful,<br>For him hatred falls away<br>Like a palm fruit cut from its stalk.<br><br>Delusion gives rise to misfortune,<br>Delusion stirs up the mind.<br>Delusion is the inner fear<br>Born within people.<br>People do not recognize<br>That special kind of delusion.<br><br>The deluded person knows not what is good,<br>The deluded person sees not the Dhamma.<br>Blindness and darkness occur<br>Where delusion dwells together.<br><br>One who has abandoned delusion,<br>Not deluded about what is delusive,<br>That one dispels all darkness<br>Like the rising sun.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti88/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, these three are inner stains, inner enemies, inner foes, inner murderers, inner adversaries. What three? Greed, monks, is an inner stain, inner enemy, inner foe, inner murderer, inner adversary. Hatred, monks, is an inner stain … Delusion, monks, is an inner stain, inner enemy, inner foe, inner murderer, inner adversary. These, monks, are the three inner stains, inner enemies, inner foes, inner murderers, inner adversaries.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 88", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti88/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these three fires. What three? The fire of greed, the fire of hatred, the fire of delusion. These, monks, are the three fires.<br><br>The fire of greed burns up people<br>Who are intoxicated by sensual pleasures.<br>The fire of hatred burns up<br>Those who are hateful,<br>Who kill living beings.<br><br>The fire of delusion burns up<br>Those who are confused,<br>Not trained in the noble Dhamma.<br>Not understanding these fires,<br>People delight in personal existence.<br><br>They increase hell,<br>The realm of animals,<br>The domain of hungry ghosts,<br>And also the asuras —<br>They are not freed<br>From Māra’s bondage.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti93/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Those who day and night<br>Devote themselves to the teaching<br>Of the Perfectly Enlightened One —<br>They calm the fire of greed<br>By always perceiving the foul.<br><br>With the mind of loving-kindness, the supreme,<br>They calm the fire of hatred.<br>With the fire of delusion,<br>By wisdom they extinguish it —<br>Wisdom that leads to penetration.<br><br>Ardent, mindful,<br>Day and night they calm<br>These fires without remainder —<br>They make them cease without remainder.<br><br>Those noble ones who have seen,<br>The wise with knowledge,<br>Having rightly known the destruction of birth,<br>Do not go to renewed existence.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti93/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, there are these three ways that sensual desire arises. What three? Sensual desire for present objects, delight in one’s own creations, and acceptance of what is created by others. These, monks, are the three ways that sensual desire arises.<br><br>The gods who enjoy sense pleasures,<br>The gods of great power,<br>The gods who delight in creation,<br>And the gods who wield power over others —<br>Enjoying sense pleasures,<br>Here and there in various existences,<br>They do not go beyond the wandering.<br><br>Knowing this peril,<br>The wise should abandon all sensual desires,<br>Whether divine or human,<br>Here and in future states.<br><br>Those who have cut the stream<br>So hard to cross,<br>Who have broken the bond<br>To what is dear and beautiful,<br>Having made an end of suffering,<br>Without remainder,<br>Those noble ones who have seen,<br>The wise with knowledge,<br>Having rightly known the destruction of birth,<br>Do not go to renewed existence.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 95", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti95/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, suppose a person is being swept away by a river that is lovely and pleasant. A man with good eyesight, standing on the bank, seeing him, says: ‘Good man, though you are being swept away by this lovely, pleasant river, further down there is a lake with waves and whirlpools, with crocodiles and demons. If you reach that place, you will die or suffer deadly pain.’ Then that person, hearing his words, struggles upstream with his hands and feet. Monks, I have given this simile to make the meaning clear. The meaning here is this: ‘The river,’ monks, is a synonym for craving. ‘Lovely and pleasant’ is a synonym for the six internal sense bases. ‘The lake further down’ is a synonym for the five lower fetters. ‘Waves’ is a synonym for anger and distress. ‘Whirlpools’ is a synonym for the five strands of sensual pleasure. ‘Crocodiles and demons’ is a synonym for women. ‘Struggling upstream’ is a synonym for renunciation. ‘Struggling with hands and feet’ is a synonym for arousing energy. ‘The man with good eyesight standing on the bank’ is a synonym for the Tathāgata, the Arahant, the Perfectly Enlightened One.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti109/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Along with this suffering, abandon sensual desires,<br>Seeking future security from bondage.<br>Rightly understanding, with mind well liberated,<br>There, right there, one is liberated from contact.<br>That one attains knowledge,<br>Accomplishes the holy life,<br>Reaches the end of the world,<br>Gets to the far shore —<br>That one is so called.”`, ref: "Itivuttaka 109", url: "https://suttacentral.net/iti109/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who has cut off craving,<br>Without remainder,<br>Dried up the swift stream —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”<br><br>“One who has destroyed conceit,<br>Without remainder,<br>As a great flood destroys a fragile reed —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who finds no core among becomings,<br>Like one picking flowers from a fig tree —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”<br><br>“One in whom there is no anger inside,<br>Who has gone beyond existence and non-existence —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”<br><br>“One whose thoughts have been dispersed,<br>Internally well-ordered, without remainder —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who does not go too far,<br>Nor lag behind,<br>Having overcome all this unreality —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”<br><br>“One who does not go too far,<br>Nor lag behind,<br>Knowing that all this is unreality —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”<br><br>“One who does not go too far,<br>Nor lag behind,<br>Free from greed, free from hatred,<br>Free from delusion —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One in whom there are no underlying tendencies,<br>Roots of unwholesome states well pulled out —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”<br><br>“One in whom there is nothing born of anguish,<br>That might lead back to this shore —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”<br><br>“One in whom there is nothing born of craving,<br>That might lead to continued existence —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”<br><br>“One who has abandoned the five hindrances,<br>Free from anguish, free from uncertainty,<br>Gone beyond the dart —<br>That monk abandons the near and far shore,<br>Like a serpent sheds its worn-out skin.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Pleasant and delightful are sensual pleasures,<br>In various forms both coarse and refined —<br>Seeing the danger in these strands of pleasure,<br>Wander alone like a rhinoceros horn.”<br><br>“This is a boil, this is a calamity,<br>This is a disease, this is a dart —<br>Seeing the danger in these strands of pleasure,<br>Wander alone like a rhinoceros horn.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Hemavata:<br>“Is he without desire for sensual pleasures?<br>Is his mind undisturbed?<br>Has he overcome all delusion?<br>Does he truly have eyes for all things?”<br><br>Sātāgira:<br>“He has no desire for sensual pleasures,<br>His mind is undisturbed,<br>He has overcome all delusion —<br>The Buddha truly has eyes for all things.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Hemavata:<br>“Who here has crossed the flood?<br>Who here has crossed the ocean?<br>Without footing, without clinging —<br>Who does not sink into the deep?”<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>“One always virtuous, wise,<br>Well-concentrated, inwardly directed,<br>Mindful — crosses the flood so hard to cross.<br><br>One who has abandoned sense-desire perceptions,<br>Who has overcome all fetters,<br>Who has destroyed delight in existence —<br>Does not sink into the deep.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Bound with sinews and bones,<br>Plastered with flesh and skin,<br>This body is covered by skin —<br>Truth is not seen as it is.<br><br>Within, it is full of liver, bladder,<br>Heart, lungs,<br>Kidneys and spleen,<br>Nasal mucus, saliva, sweat, fat,<br>Blood, synovial fluid, bile, and lymph.<br><br>From these nine streams,<br>Impurity constantly flows —<br>From the eyes, discharge flows,<br>From the ears, discharge flows.<br><br>From the nostrils, mucus flows,<br>From the mouth, sometimes vomit —<br>Bile and phlegm flow —<br>From the body, sweat and dirt.<br><br>In the hollow of the head,<br>The brain is full.<br>The fool, led by ignorance,<br>Thinks it is beautiful.<br><br>When it lies dead, swollen,<br>Livid, discarded in a charnel ground,<br>Relatives no longer care.<br><br>Dogs, jackals, wolves, worms,<br>Crows, vultures, and other creatures eat it.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.11/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Hearing the Buddha’s words,<br>The wise monk fully understands the body,<br>Sees it as it really is.<br><br>As it is below, so above,<br>As above, so below —<br>Abandoning desire for the body inside and out,<br><br>The wise monk abandons desire and lust.<br>He attains the deathless, peace,<br>The constant state of Nibbāna.<br><br>This two-footed, impure, foul-smelling body<br>Filled with various rotting corpses, oozing —<br>Yet it is preserved and honored.<br><br>Who would think to exalt this body,<br>Or despise another —<br>Except one who is blind?”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 1.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp1.11/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Like a pit of filth<br>Accumulated for many years —<br>So too, a defiled person<br>Is very hard to cleanse.<br><br>Monks, know such a person —<br>Attached to households,<br>With evil desires, evil intentions,<br>Evil conduct, evil practices.<br><br>All of you, being of one mind,<br>Should shun such a person.<br>Blow him away like dust,<br>Throw him out like rubbish.<br><br>Expel the verbose one,<br>The fake ascetic.<br>Having expelled evil desires,<br>Evil conduct, evil practices —<br><br>Keep yourselves pure,<br>Live with the pure,<br>Mindful, dwelling together,<br>Wise, and make an end of suffering.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 2.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp2.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Seeing the destruction of birth,<br>The end of fetters,<br>Destroying the path of sensual desire,<br>Without remainder —<br>That one is pure, faultless,<br>Stainless, undefiled —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of offerings.”<br><br>“One who does not see a self within the self,<br>Concentrated, upright, steady,<br>Without desire, without rigidity, without doubt —<br>The Tathāgata is worthy of offerings.”<br><br>“One in whom there is no root of delusion,<br>Who knows, who sees all things,<br>Who bears this last body —<br>Attaining perfect enlightenment,<br>The unsurpassed state of peace —<br>Thus is the Tathāgata, worthy of offerings.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Abandon desire, abandon greed —<br>These are the bonds of worldlings.<br>The one with eyes walks the path,<br>Crosses hell and human birth.<br><br>Eating little, moderate in food,<br>With few wishes, not greedy —<br>He is without desire, without craving,<br>Truly at peace.<br><br>Having gone on alms-round,<br>The sage enters the forest,<br>Goes to the root of a tree,<br>Prepares his sitting place.<br><br>The wise one, meditating,<br>Delights in the forest,<br>Meditating at the root of a tree,<br>Content, he practices his own pleasure.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.11/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Dependent on attachment, suffering arises.<br>All the various sufferings in the world<br>Come into being through attachment.<br>The fool, by making attachments,<br>Again and again encounters suffering.<br>Therefore, the wise one, knowing,<br>Does not create attachments,<br>Contemplating the nature of birth and suffering.<br><br>Those who fall into the stream<br>Of repeated birth and death,<br>Going from one existence to another,<br>Are deluded by ignorance.<br><br>This great delusion, ignorance,<br>Leads to long wandering —<br>But beings who have attained true knowledge<br>Do not go to renewed existence.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Form, sound, taste, smell, touch —<br>All these things<br>Are desirable, delightful, agreeable<br>As long as they exist.<br><br>The world with its devas<br>Regards them as delightful,<br>But when they cease,<br>Then they are seen as suffering.<br><br>The noble ones see as happiness<br>The destruction of identity.<br>This is completely opposite<br>To what the whole world sees.<br><br>What others call happiness,<br>The noble call suffering.<br>What others call suffering,<br>The noble know as happiness.<br><br>The good have open eyes, they see, they have light —<br>Apart from the noble ones,<br>Who is worthy of perfect enlightenment?<br>By that right knowledge of the path,<br>They attain Nibbāna, free from defilements.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp3.12/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who avoids sensual desires<br>As one’s foot avoids a snake’s head —<br>That mindful one transcends<br>This attachment in the world.<br><br>Whoever is greedy for sensual pleasures —<br>Land, gold, cows, horses,<br>Servants, attendants, women, relatives —<br><br>Weak, overcome by sensual pleasures,<br>Calamity crushes him,<br>Suffering follows him<br>As water rushes into a broken boat.<br><br>Therefore, always mindful,<br>One should abandon sensual pleasures.<br>Having abandoned them, one crosses the flood,<br>Having bailed out the boat, one reaches the far shore.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Short is this life —<br>Within a hundred years one dies,<br>And even if one lives longer,<br>One dies of old age.<br><br>People grieve for what they hold as ‘mine’ —<br>All possessions are impermanent.<br>Seeing this, one should live homeless.<br><br>What people think of as ‘mine’<br>Is destroyed by death.<br>Knowing this, the wise one<br>Would not incline toward ‘mine.’<br><br>As when a person wakes up,<br>He no longer sees what appeared in a dream,<br>So too, a beloved person who dies<br>Is no longer seen.<br><br>Those who are seen and heard<br>Are called by such and such a name —<br>Only the name remains<br>For one who has passed away.<br><br>People who are greedy for ‘mine’<br>Do not abandon sorrow, lamentation,<br>And stinginess.<br>Therefore, sages, leaving behind attachments,<br>Live seeing safety.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.6", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.6/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who indulges in sexual intercourse,<br>Forgetting the teaching,<br>Falls into wrong conduct —<br>That life is not noble.<br><br>One who formerly lived alone,<br>Now falls into sexual intercourse —<br>Like a swerving chariot,<br>He is called a worldling, a low person.<br><br>The good reputation he once had<br>He now loses.<br>Seeing this, one should train<br>To abandon sexual intercourse.<br><br>Overcome by thoughts,<br>He broods like a poor man —<br>Hearing others’ reproach,<br>He becomes dejected.<br><br>Then he makes weapons,<br>Attacked by others’ words —<br>He becomes greatly greedy,<br>Grasping at false speech.<br><br>Called wise, living alone,<br>If he falls into sexual intercourse,<br>He sorrows like a fool.<br><br>Seeing this danger,<br>The sage, steadfast before and after,<br>Lives solitary,<br>Not practicing sexual intercourse.<br><br>Train in seclusion —<br>This is the supreme noble practice.<br>Do not think yourself best,<br>Though you are close to Nibbāna.<br><br>The sage’s way is empty,<br>Not wishing for sensuality.<br>The one who has crossed the flood,<br>Envied and desired by people<br>Bound by sensual pleasures.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The Blessed One:<br>“Seeing craving, aversion, and lust,<br>There is no desire for sexual intercourse.<br>What is this, so full of urine and feces?<br>I would not wish even to touch it with my foot.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“One who here has overcome sensual desires,<br>Craving so hard to overcome in the world,<br>Sorrowless, without longing,<br>Has cut the stream, unbound.<br><br>Dry up what is before,<br>Let there be nothing after —<br>If you grasp nothing in between,<br>You will live at peace.<br><br>For one who has no ‘mine’<br>In name-and-form at all,<br>Who grieves not for what is not,<br>Suffers no loss in the world.<br><br>For whom there is no ‘this is mine,’<br>Nor ‘this belongs to another,’<br>Finding nothing that is self,<br>He does not grieve at ‘I have nothing.’<br><br>Not harsh, not greedy,<br>Without desire, always the same —<br>When asked, I speak about<br>The benefit of the unshaken.<br><br>The one who has known without lust,<br>He has no inclinations —<br>Freed, not striving,<br>He sees security everywhere.<br><br>The sage does not speak<br>Of being equal, worse, or better —<br>Peaceful, without stinginess,<br>He neither takes nor rejects.” So spoke the Blessed One.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.15", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.15/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Again, the five kinds of kings<br>Are present in the world —<br>Learn to subdue them,<br>Always keeping mindfulness.<br>Toward forms and sounds,<br>Toward tastes and smells,<br>And toward contacts —<br>Subdue desire and lust.<br><br>Subdue desire<br>For these things.<br>The mindful monk,<br>With mind well liberated,<br>Then, at the right time,<br>Rightly reflecting on the Dhamma,<br>With unified mind,<br>He should destroy darkness.” So spoke the Blessed One.`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 4.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp4.16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Venerable Ajita:<br>“By what is the world shrouded?<br>Why does it not shine forth?<br>What do you call its defilement?<br>What is its great fear?”<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>“The world is shrouded by ignorance.<br>Through stinginess and heedlessness it does not shine forth.<br>I say longing is its defilement —<br>Suffering is its great fear.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The Blessed One replied to Upasīva:<br>“Mindful, not longing for anything,<br>You will cross the flood.<br>Abandoning sensual desires, free from doubt,<br>Day and night see clearly —<br>The destruction of craving is Nibbāna.”<br><br>“One who is completely dispassionate<br>Toward all sensual pleasures,<br>Depending on nothing, giving up all else —<br>Freed completely, that is the supreme liberation.<br>There, that one abides,<br>And does not go on.”<br><br>“Just as a flame blown by strong wind<br>Goes to its end and cannot be measured,<br>So too the sage, freed from name and body,<br>Goes to his end and cannot be measured.”<br><br>“For one who has reached the end,<br>There is no measure by which one could speak of him.<br>When all phenomena are uprooted,<br>All paths of speech are uprooted as well.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Venerable Todeyya:<br>“One in whom desires do not dwell,<br>One in whom craving is not found,<br>One who has crossed beyond doubt —<br>What is the liberation of such a one?”<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Todeyya:<br>“One in whom desires do not dwell,<br>One in whom craving is not found,<br>One who has crossed beyond doubt —<br>There is no other kind of liberation.”<br><br>Venerable Todeyya:<br>“Does such a one have longing,<br>Or is he free from longing?<br>Does he have wisdom,<br>Or is he still acquiring wisdom?<br>O all-seeing sage, explain this to me,<br>So that I may know what a sage is, O Sakyan.”<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>“He is free from longing,<br>Without any longing —<br>He is wise, not acquiring wisdom.<br>Thus, Todeyya, know the sage:<br>Possessing nothing,<br>Not attached to sensual existence.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.10/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Venerable Kappa:<br>“For those standing in the middle of the flood,<br>In the terrifying current of existence,<br>Overcome by old age and death —<br>Tell me, sir, an island,<br>That there may be no further suffering.”<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Kappa:<br>“For those standing in the middle of the flood,<br>In the terrifying current of existence,<br>Overcome by old age and death —<br>I will tell you, Kappa, an island.<br><br>This island is unique —<br>Possessing nothing, not clinging —<br>I call it Nibbāna,<br>The destruction of old age and death.<br><br>Knowing this, mindful,<br>Attaining Nibbāna in this very life,<br>They do not come into Māra’s power,<br>Do not become servants of Māra.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.11", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.11/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Venerable Jatukaṇṇī:<br>“Having heard of the hero, free from desire for sensual pleasures,<br>I have come to ask the desireless one,<br>Who has crossed the flood,<br>The one born with the eye —<br>Speak the path of peace,<br>Let the Blessed One tell it to me as it is.<br><br>Having conquered sensual desires,<br>The Blessed One lives in the world<br>Like the sun illuminating the earth with its radiance.<br>O great wise one, teach me the Dhamma —<br>I am of little wisdom —<br>That by knowing it, I might overcome birth and old age.”<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Jatukaṇṇī:<br>“Subdue greed for sensual pleasures,<br>See renunciation as peace.<br>Do not hold on to or reject anything in the world.<br><br>Dry up what has gone before,<br>Let there be nothing after —<br>If you grasp nothing in the middle,<br>You will live at peace.<br><br>For one who has no ‘mine’ at all<br>In name-and-form, O brahmin,<br>There are no defilements by which<br>One would be in death’s power.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.12/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The Blessed One replied to Bhadrāvudha:<br>“Having expelled all desire for household things,<br>Above, below, across, and in between —<br>Whatever one clings to in the world,<br>By that very thing, Māra follows one.<br><br>Therefore, the wise one, knowing this,<br>Does not cling to anything in the world.<br>The mindful monk, seeing that beings<br>Are attached to what they cling to,<br>In Māra’s realm,<br>Should not long for any possession.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.13", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Venerable Udaya:<br>“I have come with a question —<br>To the meditator, sitting dustless,<br>Duty done, without defilements,<br>Who has reached the far shore —<br>Speak the knowledge of liberation,<br>The breaking of ignorance.”<br><br>The Blessed One replied to Udaya:<br>“Abandon desire for sensual pleasures,<br>Both sorrow and grief;<br>Abandon sloth and torpor,<br>And prevent remorse.<br><br>Knowledge of liberation, I say,<br>Is the breaking of ignorance —<br>Purified by equanimity and mindfulness,<br>With reflection leading the way.”<br><br>Venerable Udaya:<br>“What binds the world?<br>What is its range?<br>By abandoning what is Nibbāna called?”<br><br>The Blessed One:<br>“The world is bound by delight;<br>Directed thought is its range.<br>By abandoning craving,<br>Nibbāna is called.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `The Blessed One replied to Piṅgiya:<br>“Seeing the danger in all forms,<br>Beings living heedlessly,<br>Afflicted by forms —<br>Therefore, Piṅgiya, do not be heedless.<br>Abandon forms so as not to come to birth again.<br><br>Seeing beings, human folk,<br>Falling into craving,<br>Burned by old age,<br>Overcome by old age —<br>Therefore, Piṅgiya, do not be heedless.<br>Abandon craving so as not to come to birth again.”`, ref: "Sutta Nipāta 5.17", url: "https://suttacentral.net/snp5.17/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Bhalliya:<br>“Who drives away the army of Death,<br>As a great flood sweeps away a frail bridge of reeds —<br>Victorious, fearless,<br>Having subdued, he dwells at peace.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Siṅgālapitar:<br>“Look at the forest of Bhesakaḷā!<br>A monk lives there,<br>Heir to the Buddha’s teaching,<br>Pervading this great earth<br>With the perception of a skeleton.<br>I think that monk will quickly<br>Abandon sensual lust.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.18", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.18/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Tissa:<br>“As if struck by a sword,<br>As if his head were on fire,<br>Mindful, a monk should go forth,<br>Abandoning sensual lust.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.39", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.39/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Māṇava:<br>“I saw an old person,<br>I saw a sick person in pain,<br>I saw a dead person,<br>With life exhausted —<br>Therefore I went forth,<br>Leaving the home life,<br>Abandoning sensual pleasures<br>That are enticing and agreeable.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.73", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.73/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Hatthārohaputta:<br>“This mind formerly wandered<br>Wherever it wished, as it liked, as it pleased.<br>Now I will restrain it thoroughly<br>With wise reflection,<br>As a driver with a hook<br>Restrains a rutting elephant.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.77", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.77/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Sunāga:<br>“Skilled in the mind’s signs,<br>Knowing the taste of seclusion,<br>Meditating, mindful, careful,<br>He attains the non-worldly happiness.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.85", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.85/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Samiddhatta:<br>“The five aggregates are fully understood,<br>Their root is cut off.<br>The wandering of birth is ended,<br>Now there is no further becoming.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.90", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.90/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Eraka:<br>“O Eraka, painful are sensual pleasures!<br>O Eraka, not happiness are sensual pleasures!<br>One who desires sensual pleasures, desires suffering.<br>One who does not desire sensual pleasures, does not desire suffering.<br>O Eraka, know this as it is.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.93", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.93/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Abhaya (2):<br>“Seeing a form, mindfulness is lost —<br>Attending to a pleasing sign,<br>The mind feels infatuation,<br>Clinging to the perception remains.<br>The defilements increase,<br>Leading to the root of existence.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.98", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.98/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Uttiya:<br>“Hearing a sound, mindfulness is lost —<br>Attending to a pleasing sign,<br>The mind feels infatuation,<br>Clinging to the perception remains.<br>The defilements increase,<br>Leading to defilement in saṃsāra.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.99", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.99/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Parāpariya:<br>“Having abandoned the six sense-bases,<br>With sense-doors well restrained,<br>Having pulled out the root of evil,<br>I have attained the destruction of defilements.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.116", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.116/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Isidatta:<br>“The five aggregates are fully understood,<br>Standing with their root cut off.<br>The destruction of suffering is attained,<br>I have realized the destruction of defilements.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 1.120", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag1.120/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Uttara:<br>“Nothing exists here that is permanent,<br>No conditioned thing is everlasting.<br>The aggregates arise and cease,<br>They pass away in another existence.<br><br>Knowing this danger,<br>I do not desire existence.<br>Having abandoned all sensual desires,<br>I have realized the destruction of defilements.”`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Rādha:<br><br>As rain seeps into a house with a faulty roof,<br>So lust seeps into an undeveloped mind.<br><br>As rain does not seep into a house with a good roof,<br>So lust does not seep into a well-developed mind.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Mahākāla:<br><br>One who does not know thus,<br>Yet still creates attachments —<br>The fool goes on,<br>Experiencing suffering again and again.<br>Therefore, one who knows<br>Does not create attachments.<br>I will not lie down<br>With my head broken.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.16", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.16/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Puṇṇamāsa:<br><br>Having abandoned the five hindrances,<br>Attaining security from bondage,<br>Holding the mirror of the Dhamma,<br>Knowing and seeing the self.<br><br>I contemplate this body,<br>From within and without —<br>The body is seen as empty,<br>Both inside and out.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.26", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.26/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Sivaka:<br><br>Impermanent are these houses,<br>Built again and again.<br>Seeking the house-builder,<br>Birth is suffering.<br><br>O house-builder, you are seen!<br>From now on, you cannot<br>Build a house again.<br>All your rafters are broken,<br>The ridge-pole is shattered.<br>The mind has been pushed from the stream,<br>Here, it is destroyed.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.32", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.32/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nitaka:<br><br>The mind is like a rock,<br>Standing firm, unmoved.<br>Toward agreeable things,<br>The mind has no desire.<br>Toward things that disturb,<br>The mind is not disturbed.<br>One whose mind is thus developed —<br>From where can suffering come?<br><br>My mind is like a rock,<br>Standing firm, unmoved.<br>Toward agreeable things,<br>My mind has no desire.<br>Toward things that disturb,<br>My mind is not disturbed.<br>My mind is thus developed —<br>From where can suffering come to me?`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.36", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.36/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nisabha:<br><br>Having abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure,<br>Those things so agreeable,<br>Which delight the mind —<br>With faith, I went forth,<br>Putting an end to suffering.<br><br>I do not delight in death,<br>I do not delight in life.<br>I await the time,<br>Mindful and clearly comprehending.`, ref: "Theragāthā 2.38", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag2.38/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Uttarapāla:<br><br>I am truly virtuous,<br>Reflecting on good purpose.<br>I have abandoned the five strands of sensual pleasure,<br>Which are the world’s confusion.<br><br>Born in Māra’s realm,<br>Struck by strong darts,<br>Yet I have escaped<br>Māra’s snare.<br><br>All sensual desires are destroyed,<br>All forms of existence are demolished.<br>The path of birth and death is ended —<br>Now there is no further becoming.`, ref: "Theragāthā 3.12", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag3.12/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nāgasamāla:<br><br>Adorned, dressed in fine clothes,<br>They set the bait for Death.<br><br>Then I attended to it,<br>Reflecting wisely —<br>The danger became clear,<br>I dwelt in disenchantment.<br><br>And my mind was liberated.<br>Seeing the Dhamma as it is,<br>I attained the three true knowledges,<br>Accomplishing the Buddha’s teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nandaka:<br><br>Foul is the thing!<br>Full of foul smell and stench,<br>Possessed by Māra,<br>Oozing many streams —<br>This body has nine streams,<br>Always flowing.<br><br>Do not despise the ancients!<br>Do not insult the Tathāgata!<br>They do not long for the heavenly realm,<br>Let alone the human world.<br><br>The fool, without wisdom,<br>With evil intent, enveloped by delusion —<br>That one, full of lust,<br>Is caught in Māra’s snare.<br><br>Those who have escaped<br>Greed, hatred, and delusion —<br>They are not lustful,<br>The snare is cut, they are unbound.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Rāhula:<br><br>Blinded by sensual desires,<br>Covered by the net of wrong views,<br>Craving acts as a veil,<br>Covering, hiding completely.<br>Bound by heedlessness,<br>Like a fish caught in a net.<br><br>I have overcome those sensual desires,<br>Cut Māra’s bondage.<br>Having pulled out the root of craving,<br>I am cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 4.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag4.8/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Rājadatta:<br><br>A monk came to a charnel ground,<br>Saw a woman’s body<br>Abandoned there,<br>Discarded in the cemetery,<br>Food for worms.<br><br>Some become disenchanted<br>Seeing such a miserable corpse.<br>In me, sensual desire arose —<br>Blind, I was bound.<br><br>Faster than boiling rice,<br>I left that place.<br>Mindful, clearly comprehending,<br>I came, sat to one side.<br><br>Then I attended to it,<br>Reflecting wisely —<br>The danger became clear,<br>I dwelt in disenchantment.<br><br>And my mind was liberated.<br>Seeing the Dhamma as it is,<br>I attained the three true knowledges,<br>Accomplishing the Buddha’s teaching.`, ref: "Theragāthā 5.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag5.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Kulla:<br><br>Kulla went to the charnel ground,<br>Saw a woman abandoned,<br>Thrown away in the cemetery,<br>Food for worms.<br><br>“Kulla, look at this body —<br>Diseased, foul, stinking,<br>Oozing, seeping,<br>Delighting fools.”<br><br>Having taken up the mirror of Dhamma,<br>I attained right view.<br>I contemplated this body —<br>Empty inside and out.<br><br>As it is below, so above,<br>As above, so below,<br>As below, so above,<br>As above, so below.<br><br>As by day, so by night,<br>As by night, so by day,<br>As before, so after,<br>As after, so before.<br><br>Such a one does not delight<br>In the five kinds of music.<br>When one-pointed,<br>Rightly meditating on the Dhamma.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Māluṅkyaputta:<br><br>One who lives heedlessly,<br>Craving grows like a creeper.<br>He drifts and wanders,<br>Life after life,<br>Like a monkey in the forest,<br>Longing for fruit.<br><br>This wretched craving<br>Poisons the whole world.<br>When it conquers anyone,<br>Sorrow increases —<br>Like birana grass<br>Spreading and growing.<br><br>One who subdues craving,<br>Wretched, hard to conquer —<br>Sorrow falls from that person<br>Like a water drop from a lotus.<br><br>You have come here —<br>I teach this good thing.<br>Dig up the root of craving<br>Like seeking the sweet root<br>Of the usīra grass.<br>Do not let Māra, the flood,<br>Destroy you like a reed,<br>Again and again, forever.<br><br>Practice the Buddha’s instruction.<br>Do not let the moment pass.<br>If the moment passes, sorrow,<br>You will suffer in hell.<br><br>Heedlessness is dust,<br>Filthy dust born of heedlessness.<br>Heedful, with clear wisdom,<br>Pull out the dart from yourself.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Sabbhakāma:<br><br>This two-footed creature,<br>Impure and foul-smelling,<br>Full of various corpses —<br>From it, fluid oozes.<br><br>With deer, use a trap; with fish, a hook;<br>With monkeys, a pit;<br>Thus worldlings are caught.<br><br>Forms, sounds, tastes, smells, touches —<br>Agreeable and pleasing —<br>These five strands of sensual pleasure<br>Are known in female form.<br><br>Worldlings, with mind infatuated,<br>Run after enjoying female form.<br>The terrifying cemetery increases,<br>Storing up renewed existence.<br><br>One who avoids female form<br>As a foot avoids a snake’s head —<br>That mindful one overcomes<br>The world’s poisoner.<br><br>Seeing the danger in sensual pleasures,<br>Security in renunciation,<br>Having escaped all sensual pleasures,<br>I have attained the destruction of defilements.`, ref: "Theragāthā 6.14", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag6.14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Lakuṇṭaka-Bhaddiya:<br><br>“Outside the parks,<br>At the Ambāṭaka woodland,<br>In the forest with its groves,<br>Having abandoned craving, the root of craving,<br>Bhaddiya sits in meditation —<br>Blissful, happy.”<br><br>Some people delight<br>In drums, flutes, and cymbals.<br>But I, at the root of a tree,<br>Delight in the Buddha’s teaching.<br><br>If the Buddha grants a gift,<br>I receive that gift.<br>I bear mindfulness of the body,<br>Constantly in all realms.<br><br>Those who mock me for my body,<br>Or follow me for my voice —<br>They do not know me,<br>Driven by sensual desire.<br><br>Not knowing the inside,<br>Not seeing the outside —<br>Blocked on all sides, the fool<br>Is carried away by words.<br><br>Not knowing the inside,<br>But seeing the outside —<br>Seeing only the external fruit,<br>He too is carried away by words.<br><br>Knowing the inside with wisdom,<br>Seeing the outside as well —<br>Seeing without obstruction,<br>He is not carried away by words.`, ref: "Theragāthā 7.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag7.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Kappa:<br><br>Full of various impurities,<br>Where there is no purity —<br>Like a long-stagnant puddle,<br>A great boil, a wound.<br><br>Full of blood and pus,<br>Sunk in a pit of filth —<br>This body oozes fluid,<br>Constantly oozing impurity.<br><br>Bound by sixty sinews,<br>Plastered with flesh as mortar,<br>Clad in skin as armor —<br>This foul body is useless.<br><br>Connected by a chain of bones,<br>Tied together with sinews —<br>By their combined power,<br>They create various postures.<br><br>Always heading toward death,<br>Approaching the end of life —<br>There, abandoned,<br>People go according to their desire.<br><br>The body, shrouded by ignorance,<br>Bound by four bonds,<br>Sinks in the flood,<br>Caught in the net of underlying tendencies —<br><br>Fettered by five hindrances,<br>Obsessed by thought,<br>Following the root of craving,<br>Covered by the veil of delusion.<br><br>Thus this body wanders,<br>Led by the chariot of kamma —<br>Sometimes success, sometimes failure —<br>Enduring many births of craving.<br><br>One who thinks ‘this body is mine’<br>Is a foolish worldling,<br>Increasing the fearful cemetery,<br>Clinging tightly to renewed existence.<br><br>One who avoids this body<br>As one avoids a snake smeared with feces —<br>That one abandons the root of existence<br>And attains Nibbāna, free from defilements.`, ref: "Theragāthā 10.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag10.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Añña-Koṇḍañña:<br><br>I am exceedingly joyful,<br>Having heard the supreme Dhamma,<br>The Dhamma taught for dispassion,<br>Completely without clinging.<br><br>In this world of a round earth,<br>With many colors and forms,<br>Bewildering the mind —<br>Thus I thought:<br>The sign of beauty is very enticing,<br>Connected with lust.<br><br>As wind blows away dust,<br>As rain settles it down,<br>Thoughts become stilled<br>When seen with wisdom.<br><br>All conditioned things are impermanent —<br>When seen with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering —<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>All conditioned things are suffering —<br>When seen with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering —<br>This is the path to purity.<br><br>All phenomena are not-self —<br>When seen with wisdom,<br>One becomes disenchanted with suffering —<br>This is the path to purity.`, ref: "Theragāthā 15.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag15.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Parāpariya:<br><br>The eye goes to forms —<br>Without restraint, without checking,<br>Not seeing the danger,<br>That person does not escape suffering.<br><br>The ear goes to sounds —<br>Without restraint, without checking,<br>Not seeing the danger,<br>That person does not escape suffering.<br><br>Not seeing the escape,<br>Enjoying odors,<br>That person does not escape suffering,<br>Because of lust for smells.<br><br>Remembering sweet and sour as supreme,<br>Remembering bitter as supreme,<br>Enslaved by the taste of craving,<br>The mind cannot awaken.<br><br>Remembering contacts —<br>Beautiful and pleasurable —<br>Infatuated, conditioned by lust,<br>One meets many sufferings.<br><br>The mind toward all these things —<br>All five —<br>If unable to guard them,<br>Suffering follows that person.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Parāpariya:<br><br>Most bodies,<br>Full of pus and blood,<br>Are made by skilled people<br>Into beautifully painted boxes.<br><br>Bitter as sweetness,<br>Suffering bound by the agreeable —<br>Like a sharp sword smeared with honey —<br>The greedy person does not know.<br><br>One who lusts after female form,<br>Female taste, female touch,<br>One who is infatuated by female smell,<br>Meets many sufferings.<br><br>All the streams from women —<br>Five kinds flow in five places —<br>A person with energy and strength<br>Can block them.<br><br>One who has a goal, abiding in Dhamma,<br>Skilled, clear-seeing,<br>Rejoices in doing the duty<br>Connected with Dhamma and meaning.<br><br>Sunk in temporary benefits,<br>Abandon what is unbeneficial.<br>If one thinks of such a thing,<br>Not the thing to be done —<br>That one, not heedless,<br>Sees clearly.<br><br>If it is a good deed to do,<br>Rejoice in practicing the Dhamma.<br>Seize the doing immediately —<br>That is truly the highest happiness.<br><br>With high and low means,<br>Deceiving others,<br>Killing, causing sorrow,<br>Violent, overpowering others —<br><br>As a strong man carves wood,<br>Driving out a peg with a peg,<br>So the good person,<br>Drives out a sense-faculty with a sense-faculty.<br><br>Developing faith, energy, concentration,<br>Training mindfulness and wisdom,<br>Using five to conquer five,<br>Stainless, one goes forward.<br><br>That brahmin, having a goal,<br>Abiding in Dhamma,<br>Following the Buddha’s instruction,<br>Complete, with full strength —<br>That person enjoys peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.2", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Telakāni:<br><br>I sank deep in a lake,<br>Full of mud, unable to escape —<br>Full of deceit, envy,<br>Tension and darkness.<br><br>Thunder of restlessness resounded,<br>Clouds of fetters covered,<br>Waterfall of wrong thoughts,<br>Connected with sensual desire —<br>They swept me away<br>Into the ocean of wrong views.<br><br>Everywhere, streams flow,<br>Creepers stand and sprout.<br>Who can block those streams?<br>Who can cut down the creepers?<br><br>Venerable sir, make a dam,<br>Block those streams.<br>Do not let the water<br>Born of mind sweep you away,<br>As a rapid current sweeps away a tree.<br><br>So I, afraid,<br>Seeking the far shore from this shore,<br>Then the Teacher,<br>Attended by the noble Saṅgha,<br>With the weapon of wisdom,<br>Waits as a support for people.<br><br>He brought me, while sinking,<br>A well-made ladder —<br>The Buddha, pure, firm,<br>Made of the heartwood of Dhamma —<br>Then he said to me:<br>“Do not be afraid!”<br><br>Climbing the tower of mindfulness,<br>From there I contemplate<br>People who delight in identity view —<br>Formerly, I was proud.<br><br>When I saw the path,<br>The boat I needed to board,<br>I did not abide in a self,<br>Seeing the supreme destination.<br><br>The dart that arises from self,<br>Born from the cause of existence —<br>He taught the supreme path,<br>The cessation of those things.<br><br>The knot that for a long time,<br>Hidden, lay within the skin —<br>The Buddha untied and threw it away,<br>Removing all that is harmful.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Raṭṭhapāla:<br><br>Behold this decorated image —<br>A heap of wounds, a collection of sores,<br>Diseased, full of lustful thoughts,<br>Nothing stable or permanent here.<br><br>Behold this adorned appearance,<br>With jewels and earrings —<br>A skeleton covered by skin,<br>Made beautiful by clothes.<br><br>The feet are painted with lac and dye,<br>The face is smeared with powder and paste —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>Not one who seeks enlightenment.<br><br>The hair is curled in eight rings,<br>The eyes are rubbed with collyrium and rouge —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>Not one who seeks enlightenment.<br><br>Like a newly painted medicine box,<br>This foul body is adorned —<br>Enough to fool a fool,<br>Not one who seeks enlightenment.<br><br>The hunter set his trap and snare —<br>The wise deer does not touch the snare.<br>Having eaten the bait, we go away,<br>Leaving the trapper to mourn.<br><br>The hunter’s trap is cut —<br>The wise deer does not touch the snare.<br>Having eaten the bait, we go away,<br>Leaving the trapper to grieve.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Māluṅkyaputta:<br><br>Seeing a form, mindfulness is lost —<br>If one attends to a pleasing perception,<br>The mind feels infatuation,<br>Gets stuck and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Manyfold, born from form —<br>Greed and harmful thoughts grow strong,<br>They afflict his mind.<br>Suffering accumulates thus —<br>Far, far away is Nibbāna.<br><br>Hearing a sound, mindfulness is lost —<br>If one attends to a pleasing perception,<br>The mind feels infatuation,<br>Gets stuck and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Manyfold, born from sound —<br>Greed and harmful thoughts grow strong,<br>They afflict his mind.<br>Suffering accumulates thus —<br>Far, far away is Nibbāna.<br><br>Smelling an odor, mindfulness is lost —<br>If one attends to a pleasing perception,<br>The mind feels infatuation,<br>Gets stuck and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Manyfold, born from odor —<br>Greed and harmful thoughts grow strong,<br>They afflict his mind.<br>Suffering accumulates thus —<br>Far, far away is Nibbāna.<br><br>Tasting a flavor, mindfulness is lost —<br>If one attends to a pleasing perception,<br>The mind feels infatuation,<br>Gets stuck and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Manyfold, born from taste —<br>Greed and harmful thoughts grow strong,<br>They afflict his mind.<br>Suffering accumulates thus —<br>Far, far away is Nibbāna.<br><br>Feeling a touch, mindfulness is lost —<br>If one attends to a pleasing perception,<br>The mind feels infatuation,<br>Gets stuck and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Manyfold, born from touch —<br>Greed and harmful thoughts grow strong,<br>They afflict his mind.<br>Suffering accumulates thus —<br>Far, far away is Nibbāna.<br><br>Cognizing a phenomenon, mindfulness is lost —<br>If one attends to a pleasing perception,<br>The mind feels infatuation,<br>Gets stuck and remains.<br><br>His feelings increase,<br>Manyfold, born from mind —<br>Greed and harmful thoughts grow strong,<br>They afflict his mind.<br>Suffering accumulates thus —<br>Far, far away is Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Māluṅkyaputta:<br><br>Not lusting after forms,<br>Seeing a form, mindful,<br>The mind not clinging to the feeling,<br>Not getting stuck, not remaining —<br><br>As one sees a form,<br>Thus one feels the feeling —<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, practicing thus —<br><br>Thus, not storing up suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not lusting after sounds,<br>Hearing a sound, mindful,<br>The mind not clinging to the feeling,<br>Not getting stuck, not remaining —<br><br>As one hears a sound,<br>Thus one feels the feeling —<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, practicing thus —<br>Thus, not storing up suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not lusting after odors,<br>Smelling an odor, mindful,<br>The mind not clinging to the feeling,<br>Not getting stuck, not remaining —<br><br>As one smells an odor,<br>Thus one feels the feeling —<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, practicing thus —<br>Thus, not storing up suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not lusting after tastes,<br>Tasting a flavor, mindful,<br>The mind not clinging to the feeling,<br>Not getting stuck, not remaining —<br><br>As one tastes a flavor,<br>Thus one feels the feeling —<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, practicing thus —<br>Thus, not storing up suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not lusting after touches,<br>Feeling a touch, mindful,<br>The mind not clinging to the feeling,<br>Not getting stuck, not remaining —<br><br>As one feels a touch,<br>Thus one feels the feeling —<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, practicing thus —<br>Thus, not storing up suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.<br><br>Not lusting after phenomena,<br>Cognizing a phenomenon, mindful,<br>The mind not clinging to the feeling,<br>Not getting stuck, not remaining —<br><br>As one cognizes a phenomenon,<br>Thus one feels the feeling —<br>Abandoning, not accumulating,<br>Mindful, practicing thus —<br>Thus, not storing up suffering,<br>He is said to be close to Nibbāna.`, ref: "Theragāthā 16.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag16.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Talapuṭa:<br><br>O mind, everywhere,<br>I have acted as you wished,<br>For many lives —<br>You were not angry with me,<br>And this inner-born body<br>Is your gratitude!<br>On the long path of saṃsāra,<br>Suffering was caused by you.<br><br>O mind, you yourself made<br>This person that I am —<br>You made me become<br>A brahmin,<br>A king, a royal,<br>One day a merchant,<br>Another day a servant,<br>Or a kind of deity —<br>All is due to you,<br>Made by you.<br><br>Due to your power,<br>We became asuras —<br>Due to you,<br>I fell to the bottom of hell;<br>Sometimes an animal,<br>Sometimes a hungry ghost —<br>All is due to you,<br>Made by you.<br><br>You will not deceive me<br>Again, many times more,<br>Like sorcerers<br>Performing magic tricks.<br>You played tricks on me,<br>Like playing with a madman.<br>O mind, tell me —<br>Where have I wronged you?<br><br>Formerly this mind wandered,<br>Went wherever it wished,<br>Went where it delighted,<br>Went where it enjoyed —<br>Now I will restrain it<br>With wise reflection,<br>As with a hook one restrains<br>A rutting elephant.<br><br>For me, the Teacher<br>Has declared that life is impermanent —<br>Life is not eternal,<br>Life has no core.<br>O mind, urge me<br>To leap into the Buddha’s teaching —<br>Make me cross the flood,<br>So very hard to cross.<br><br>I have now gone forth<br>In the Great Sage’s Dhamma —<br>Those like me<br>Do not accept loss.<br><br>Forests, oceans, rivers, land,<br>The four directions, above and below —<br>All are impermanent.<br>The three realms are perilous.<br>O mind, where will you go?<br>You will enjoy peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 19.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag19.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Mahā-Moggallāna:<br><br>With hut whose roof is made of bones,<br>Sewn together with sinews and flesh —<br>Foul, full of stench!<br>Carrying other people’s limbs<br>As my own body!<br><br>The container full of feces,<br>Covered over with skin —<br>O female demon!<br>With your breasts like boils —<br>Your body has nine streams,<br>Always flowing.<br><br>Your body’s nine streams,<br>Foul, creating bondage —<br>The monk avoids that body<br>As a clean person avoids feces.<br><br>If others knew you<br>As I know you,<br>They would avoid you<br>As one avoids feces in the rain.<br><br>It is truly so, O Great Hero,<br>As the ascetic said:<br>Here, some are stuck,<br>Like an old ox in the mud.<br><br>One who thinks he can dye<br>The sky with turmeric,<br>Or with any other color —<br>That one only fails.<br><br>My mind is like that sky —<br>Well concentrated internally —<br>Do not bring evil thoughts to it,<br>Like a bird falling into a pile of fire.`, ref: "Theragāthā 20.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag20.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Mahā-Moggallāna:<br><br>All conditioned things are impermanent —<br>Having arisen, they must cease.<br>After arising, they cease —<br>Their calming is bliss.<br><br>Those who see the five aggregates<br>As other, not-self,<br>Penetrate the subtle,<br>Like a dart piercing a hair-tip.<br><br>Those who see the formations<br>As other, not-self,<br>Penetrate the subtle,<br>Like a dart piercing a hair-tip.<br><br>As if struck by a sword,<br>As if his head were on fire,<br>Mindful, a monk should go forth,<br>Abandoning sensual lust.<br><br>As if struck by a sword,<br>As if his head were on fire,<br>Mindful, a monk should go forth,<br>Abandoning craving for existence.<br><br>Not with such weakness,<br>Not with such little strength,<br>Can one attain Nibbāna,<br>Liberation from all bonds.<br><br>This young monk,<br>This supreme man,<br>Conquering Māra and his army,<br>Bears this last body.`, ref: "Theragāthā 20.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag20.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Vaṅgīsa:<br><br>Sensual desire burns me!<br>My mind is on fire.<br>Good indeed, Gotama —<br>Out of compassion, speak<br>The Dhamma that extinguishes the blaze.<br><br>It is because of distorted perception<br>That your mind is on fire.<br>Abandon the sign of the beautiful<br>That leads to sensual desire.<br><br>See formations as impermanent,<br>Suffering, not-self —<br>Extinguish great sensual desire —<br>Do not be burned again and again.<br>Develop the mind on foulness,<br>One-pointed, well-concentrated.<br>Practice mindfulness of the body,<br>Practice much disenchantment.<br><br>Practice the signless,<br>Destroy the underlying tendency to conceit.<br>By thoroughly penetrating conceit,<br>Your practice will be at peace.`, ref: "Theragāthā 21.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thag21.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Another Elder Nun Dhīrā:<br><br>Dhīrā, be steadfast,<br>Hold fast to wholesome states.<br>O nun, with faculties developed,<br>Bear this last body,<br>Having conquered the forces of Māra’s army,<br>Having conquered Māra with his army.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Upasanā:<br><br>Upasanā, cross the strong flood,<br>The flood so hard to cross,<br>Subject to the King of Death.<br>Bear this last body,<br>Having conquered Māra and his army.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 1.10", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig1.10/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Abhirūpa Nandā:<br><br>Nandā, look at this body —<br>A collection of many diseases, impure,<br>Full of stench, rotting.<br>Develop your mind,<br>Contemplate the nature of foulness,<br>Achieve one-pointedness,<br>With mind well concentrated.<br><br>Practice the signless,<br>Abandon the underlying tendency to conceit.<br>By fully understanding conceit,<br>You will live at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Mother of Abhayā:<br><br>From the soles of the feet upward,<br>From the top of the head downward —<br>Contemplate this body —<br>This body is truly impure,<br>Truly foul, stinking.<br><br>Thus abiding,<br>All sensual desire is uprooted.<br>Fever is abandoned —<br>I am cooled, at peace.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.8", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.8/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Abhayā:<br><br>O fearless nun!<br>This body is so fragile —<br>Worldlings here,<br>Delighting, are often lustful.<br>I will abandon this body,<br>Mindful and clearly comprehending.<br><br>Without heedlessness, I will strive,<br>I will strive to escape the painful state.<br>With craving destroyed, I have attained —<br>Accomplishing the Buddha’s teaching.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 2.9", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig2.9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Selā:<br><br>You will not escape,<br>You will not escape this world.<br>What use is this practice of seclusion to you?<br>Enjoy sensual pleasures —<br>Do not have regrets later.<br><br>Sensual pleasures are like swords and spears —<br>They cut the aggregates to pieces.<br>What you call the pleasure of life —<br>For me, that sensual pleasure<br>Is no longer enticing.<br><br>Everywhere, delight is destroyed.<br>The mass of darkness,<br>The blinding darkness, has been shattered.<br>Know this, O Evil One —<br>You are Māra,<br>You are defeated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Māra:<br><br>You will not escape,<br>You will not escape this world.<br>What use is this practice of seclusion to you?<br>Enjoy sensual pleasures —<br>Do not have regrets later.<br><br>Elder Nun Selā:<br><br>Sensual pleasures are like swords and spears —<br>They cut the aggregates to pieces.<br>What you call the pleasure of life —<br>For me, that sensual pleasure<br>Is no longer enticing.<br><br>Everywhere, delight is destroyed.<br>The mass of darkness,<br>The blinding darkness, has been shattered.<br>Know this, O Evil One —<br>You are Māra,<br>You are defeated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 3.7", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig3.7/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Sundarī Nandā:<br><br>Nandā, look at this body —<br>Diseased, impure, stinking.<br>Develop the mind on foulness,<br>One-pointed, well-concentrated.<br><br>As this body, so that body —<br>As that body, so this body —<br>Foul, rotting —<br>Only fools delight in it.<br><br>Thus contemplate this body,<br>Day and night without fatigue.<br>With your own wisdom,<br>Therefore escape.<br>With your own wisdom,<br>Escape pride in beauty,<br>And see truly<br>What fools see.<br><br>This city is built of bones,<br>Plastered with flesh and blood.<br>Within dwell aging and death,<br>Conceit and hypocrisy.<br><br>Without heedlessness,<br>Rightly contemplate that body —<br>The true nature of this body<br>Is seen inside and out.<br>I am disenchanted with the body,<br>My mind is dispassionate.<br>Without heedlessness, free from bonds,<br>I am at peace, stilled.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 5.4", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig5.4/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Māra:<br><br>You are young and beautiful,<br>I am young and in my prime.<br>With the five-tuned lute,<br>Enjoy yourself, Khemā.<br><br>Elder Nun Khemā:<br><br>With this foul body,<br>Diseased and fragile —<br>I am disenchanted, disgusted.<br>Sensual desire has been uprooted.<br><br>Sensual desires are like swords and spears —<br>The aggregates are a chopping block.<br>What you call sensual pleasure —<br>I have now abandoned it.<br><br>Everywhere, delight is destroyed,<br>The mass of delusion is shattered.<br>Know this, O Evil One —<br>You are defeated, Māra.<br><br>You worship the stars!<br>You worship fire in the deep forest —<br>You do not know the truth —<br>Fools think it is pure.<br><br>But I pay homage<br>To the Awakened One, the Supreme Man,<br>Who has escaped all suffering,<br>Following the Teacher’s instruction.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 6.3", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig6.3/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Mother of Vaḍḍha:<br><br>Vaḍḍha, never fall into the realm of sensual desire.<br>My son, do not share<br>In repeated suffering.<br><br>Blissful is the sage,<br>Without desire, with doubt cut off,<br>Cooled, self-controlled,<br>Without any defilements.<br><br>That sage practices<br>The path leading to right view,<br>Putting an end to suffering.<br>Vaḍḍha, strive on!<br><br>With confidence, mother spoke<br>This purpose for you —<br>“My dear mother! I think<br>That you have no sensual desire.”<br><br>“Vaḍḍha, whatever conduct —<br>Low, high, or middling —<br>Not even a little sensual desire<br>Exists in me.<br><br>I have destroyed all defilements,<br>Not heedless, meditating.<br>The three true knowledges are attained —<br>The Buddha’s instruction is done.”<br><br>Wonderful, my mother,<br>Encouraging and urging me,<br>With verses of truth,<br>Out of compassion.<br><br>Hearing my mother’s words,<br>Her motherly instruction,<br>I practiced the Dhamma gratefully,<br>Attaining security from bondage.<br><br>I am energetic, striving,<br>Day and night not lazy.<br>Well encouraged by my mother,<br>I attained the supreme purity.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 9.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig9.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Uppalavaṇṇā:<br><br>“How tiresome are sensual desires!<br>Impure, foul, full of thorns —<br>Seeing the danger in sensual pleasures,<br>Renunciation is firmly secure.<br>I went forth from Rājagaha,<br>Leaving home for homelessness.”<br><br>I know my former lives,<br>The divine eye is purified.<br>I know the minds of others,<br>The ear-element is purified.<br><br>I have attained psychic powers,<br>The destruction of defilements is attained.<br>I have attained the six direct knowledges —<br>The Buddha’s instruction is done.<br><br>With mind well subdued,<br>The bases of psychic power well developed,<br>The six direct knowledges are attained —<br>The Buddha’s instruction is done.<br><br>Sensual desires are like swords and spears —<br>They cut the aggregates to pieces.<br>What you call the pleasure of life —<br>For me, that sensual pleasure<br>Is no longer enticing.<br><br>Everywhere, delight is destroyed.<br>The mass of darkness,<br>The blinding darkness, has been shattered.<br>Know this, O Evil One —<br>You are Māra,<br>You are defeated.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 11.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig11.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Subhā:<br><br>Here, people are lustful,<br>Heedless, with defiled minds,<br>They oppose each other as enemies,<br>They struggle in disputes.<br><br>Killing, binding, torturing,<br>Losing wealth, grieving, worrying —<br>Those who sink in sensual pleasures<br>Meet many calamities.<br><br>Why do my relatives,<br>Like my enemies,<br>Bind me into the circle of sensual pleasures?<br>Know that I have gone forth<br>Because I see that sensual pleasures are fearful.<br><br>Silver and gold cannot<br>Destroy the defilements.<br>Sensual pleasures are enemies,<br>Murderers, killers.<br>They are adversaries,<br>Darts, bonds.<br><br>Why do my relatives,<br>Like my enemies,<br>Bind me into the circle of sensual pleasures?<br>Know that I have gone forth —<br>Shaved my head, wearing the great robe.<br><br>Living on food<br>Accumulated by alms-round,<br>Robes made from discarded rags —<br>Living thus is suitable for me,<br>The basic life of homelessness.<br><br>Great sages have abandoned<br>Sensual desires, both divine and human.<br>Dwelling secure, liberated,<br>Unshaken, at ease.<br><br>Do not lead me to sensual desires —<br>There is no safety in sensual desires.<br>Sensual desires are enemies, murderers,<br>Producing suffering, like a heap of burning coals.<br><br>The path is dangerous, full of fear,<br>Full of suffering, with thorns —<br>The path of craving is rugged,<br>The path of delusion is vast.<br><br>Filled with terrifying calamities,<br>Sensual desires are like a snake’s head —<br>Fools delight in sensual desires,<br>Blind worldlings.<br><br>Beings sink in the muddy swamp —<br>Those who do not see the world,<br>They do not know<br>The end of birth and death.<br><br>People, because of sensual desires,<br>Go to evil destinations —<br>Most go that way,<br>Making themselves sick.<br><br>Thus, sensual desires produce enmity,<br>They burn, they defile.<br>Sensual desires belong to the body —<br>They bind people to death.<br><br>Sensual desires make one insane,<br>They cause disordered speech and mind,<br>They defile beings,<br>About to fall into Māra’s trap.<br><br>Sensual desires are endlessly perilous,<br>Full of suffering, a great poison —<br>Little sweetness, they create strife —<br>They wither the bright day.<br><br>Thus I decide —<br>I will not turn back because of sensual desires,<br>Which cause misfortune —<br>I will always delight in Nibbāna.<br><br>Fighting against sensual desires,<br>I wait, cool, calm —<br>I will live heedfully,<br>Destroying the fetters of sensual desire.<br><br>I follow that path<br>That the great sages have walked —<br>Sorrowless, stainless,<br>Safe, straight — the Eightfold Path.<br><br>See this Subhā,<br>Established in the true Dhamma —<br>A goldsmith’s daughter,<br>Attaining freedom from sensual desire,<br>Sitting in meditation,<br>At the root of a tree.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 13.5", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig13.5/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Sumedhā:<br><br>“What is this foul, stinking body,<br>Frightening,<br>A leather bag full of corpses,<br>Oozing impurities?<br><br>What is this body I know —<br>Disgusting, smeared with flesh and blood,<br>A dwelling for worms,<br>Food for birds —<br>This body is like that —<br>To whom should I give it now?<br><br>The body, thrown in a charnel ground,<br>Not long, loses consciousness —<br>Like a discarded log —<br>Relatives are disgusted.<br><br>That body thrown in the charnel ground,<br>Becomes food for others —<br>Formerly they washed it clean,<br>Now they are disgusted —<br>Even parents are like that —<br>What to say of ordinary people?<br><br>They are infatuated with a body without core,<br>Bound by sinews and bones,<br>Full of saliva and tears,<br>Full of feces and urine, foul-smelling.<br><br>If this body were cut open,<br>Its inner parts revealed,<br>Even one’s mother would be disgusted,<br>Unable to bear the stench.<br><br>It is because of aggregates, elements, and sense-bases<br>That this body is constituted —<br>The root of renewed existence, suffering —<br>They speak of it rightly —<br>They do not delight in it at all.<br>So who would I wish to marry?<br><br>Even a hundred spears every day,<br>Constantly piercing the body —<br>Though harmed for a hundred years —<br>That would still be better,<br>Because that suffering,<br>In the end, would be destroyed.<br><br>The wise would agree to such killing,<br>As the Teacher declared —<br>They wander on for a long time,<br>With minds given to killing,<br>Continually following one after another.<br><br>In the realms of devas and humans,<br>Animals, asuras,<br>Hungry ghosts, and hell —<br>They undergo endless slaughter.<br><br>In hell, there are many —<br>Those with defiled minds, fallen —<br>The heavenly realm is no refuge —<br>There is no Nibbāna-like happiness there.<br><br>Those who attain Nibbāna<br>Are intimately connected<br>With the teaching<br>Of the One with Ten Powers —<br>At ease, unruffled,<br>Striving to end birth and death.<br><br>Today, father, I am determined to leave.<br>These empty possessions<br>Are of no value.<br>I am disgusted with sensual pleasures,<br>I am weary of sensual pleasures —<br>They have been cut off,<br>Like a palm tree stump.”`, ref: "Therīgāthā 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig16.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Sumedhā:<br><br>Even if there were seventeen treasures,<br>Filling the ten directions completely,<br>Sensual desires are never satisfied —<br>One dies, still unsatisfied.<br><br>Sensual desires are like swords and spears,<br>Sensual desires are like a snake’s head,<br>Like a blazing torch,<br>Like a smooth-gnawed bone.<br><br>Sensual desires are not permanent,<br>Nor are they everlasting —<br>Much suffering, a great poison,<br>Like a red-hot iron ball —<br>The source of misfortune,<br>Resulting in suffering.<br><br>Sensual desires are like a fruit tree,<br>Like a piece of meat — trouble,<br>Like a dream, like a illusion —<br>Sensual desires are like borrowed goods.<br><br>Sensual desires are like swords, like stakes,<br>Disease and boils,<br>Misfortune and agitation —<br>Like a pit of glowing embers —<br>The source of misfortune,<br>Fear and destruction.<br><br>Fools, for a long time,<br>Weep in this wandering continuation.<br>From beginningless time until now,<br>They weep at being subject to death,<br>Weep for slain brothers,<br>Weep for being slain themselves.<br><br>Remember from beginningless time —<br>Tears, milk, and blood<br>Flow in saṃsāra,<br>Without ever stopping.<br>Remember the accumulation of bones<br>Of beings wandering on.<br><br>Remember the four oceans<br>Filled with tears, milk, and blood —<br>Remember the bones of one lifetime,<br>As high as Vepulla.<br><br>Remember from beginningless time —<br>Not enough to make<br>The whole Jambudīpa<br>As a heap of mustard seeds<br>Of mothers and fathers in saṃsāra.<br><br>Remember from beginningless time —<br>Grasses, trees, branches, leaves —<br>Not enough to contain<br>A four-fingered pot<br>For the fathers in saṃsāra.<br><br>Remember the image<br>Of the blind turtle in the eastern sea,<br>Poking its head into<br>The hole of a floating yoke —<br>To illustrate<br>How hard it is to be human.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig16.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `Elder Nun Sumedhā:<br><br>Remember this human body —<br>Compared to a water bubble —<br>Full of misfortunes,<br>Empty, without core —<br>See the aggregates as impermanent!<br>Remember the many dangers of hell.<br><br>Remember the great charnel ground —<br>Because of continuous rebirth —<br>Because of fear of crocodiles —<br>Remember the Four Noble Truths.<br><br>The deathless water is here —<br>Why would one drink a hundred bitters?<br>All sensual pleasures<br>Are truly a hundred thousand bitter.<br><br>The deathless water is here!<br>Why would one delight in feverish sensual pleasures?<br>All sensual pleasures burn,<br>Seething and blistering.<br><br>There are no enemies here!<br>Why delight in hostile sensual pleasures?<br>The king of fire, thieves, water, enemies —<br>Common enemies are many.<br><br>Here there is liberation!<br>Why let sensual pleasures kill and bind?<br>In sensual pleasures there is killing and binding —<br>Delighting in sensual pleasures brings much suffering.<br><br>A blazing grass torch —<br>If you hold it and don’t let go, you’ll be burned.<br>Sensual pleasures are like a torch —<br>They burn anyone who doesn’t escape.<br><br>Do not accept small sensual pleasures,<br>Abandoning great, expansive happiness.<br>Do not be like a fish swallowing a hook,<br>Then later suffering calamity.<br><br>Subdue sensual desire within sensual desires,<br>Like a dog tied with a leash.<br>Do not let sensual desires devour you,<br>Like a hungry man devouring a dog.<br><br>Suffering is truly boundless,<br>It causes much mental distress.<br>You are tied to sensual desires —<br>Abandon impermanent sensual desires.<br><br>Here, there is no aging!<br>Why pursue sensual desires that age?<br>Every birth, everywhere,<br>Is subject to disease and death —<br><br>Here there is no aging, no death —<br>This is the path without aging,<br>Without death, without sorrow,<br>Without enemies, without bonds,<br>Without stumbling, without fear,<br>Without burning, without falling.<br><br>This goal, many have attained —<br>This goal is the deathless.<br>Now it should be realized.<br>If one is rightly attentive,<br>Without exertion,<br>One cannot realize it.<br><br>This is the cause, the source —<br>This is the very root —<br>Endure the Teacher’s word!<br>This is the first link —<br>That is Nibbāna —<br>If we love the Dhamma.<br><br>Thus, with faith,<br>They spoke these excellent words,<br>Words full of wisdom —<br>Supreme, ultimate —<br>They are disgusted with renewed existence —<br>Through disgust, craving ceases.`, ref: "Therīgāthā 16.1", url: "https://suttacentral.net/thig16.1/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Thus, great king, a monk contemplates the five hindrances not yet abandoned as a debt, as a disease, as a prison, as slavery, as a desert road. And, great king, just as being without debt, without disease, freed from prison, freed from slavery, in a safe and pleasant land — so, great king, a monk contemplates the five hindrances when they have been abandoned.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 2 – Sāmaññaphalasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn2/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Poṭṭhapāda, I teach the Dhamma for the removal of gross personality view. If you practice accordingly, then defiling states are abandoned, pure states increase, and in this very life, by direct knowledge, you realize and abide in full, vast wisdom. Poṭṭhapāda, you might think: ‘Defiling states will be abandoned, pure states will increase, and in this very life, by direct knowledge, one realizes and abides in full, vast wisdom — yet suffering still remains.’ Poṭṭhapāda, do not think thus. When defiling states are abandoned, pure states increase, and in this very life, by direct knowledge, one realizes and abides in full, vast wisdom — then gladness arises, joy, tranquility, mindfulness, clear comprehension, and a pleasant abiding arise.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 9 – Poṭṭhapādasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn9/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Vāseṭṭha, there are five factors that cause the growth of sensual pleasure. What five? Forms cognizable by the eye — desirable, beautiful, delightful, enticing, connected with sensual pleasure and enjoyment; sounds cognizable by the ear … odors cognizable by the nose … tastes cognizable by the tongue … touches cognizable by the body — desirable, beautiful, delightful, enticing, connected with sensual pleasure and enjoyment. Vāseṭṭha, those five factors that cause the growth of sensual pleasure — the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas, attached, infatuated, bound, not seeing their danger, not understanding the escape from them, enjoy them. Vāseṭṭha, that those brahmins proficient in the three Vedas, abandoning the qualities that make a brahmin, following qualities that do not make a brahmin, attached, infatuated, bound, not seeing their danger, not understanding the escape from them, enjoying them, bound by the bondage of sensual pleasures, could after death be reborn in union with Brahmā — such a thing is not possible.”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 13 – Tevijjasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, while Prince Vipassī was going to the pleasure garden, he saw a sick person, suffering, gravely ill, wallowing in his own urine and feces, needing others to lift him, needing others to support him. Seeing this, the prince asked the charioteer: ‘Good man, what has this person done that his eyes are not like those of others, his voice not like others?’ ‘Your Highness, that is called a sick person.’ ‘Good man, why is he called a sick person?’ ‘Your Highness, he is called a sick person because he has not recovered from his illness.’ ‘Good man, then am I subject to sickness, not having fallen sick yet?’ ‘Your Highness, you and I as well — all of us are subject to sickness, even though we have not fallen sick yet.’ ‘Good man, then this visit to the pleasure garden is enough. Drive back to the palace.’ ‘Yes, Your Highness.’ Monks, the charioteer, obeying the prince, drove back to the palace. Monks, Prince Vipassī returned to the palace, suffering, grieving, and thought: ‘Shameful indeed is this birth! And anyone who is born must also age, must also be sick!’”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, the charioteer, obeying the prince, drove to a person who had just died. Monks, when he saw the corpse of a dead person, Prince Vipassī asked: ‘Good man, why is this person called dead?’ ‘Your Highness, he is called dead because now his mother, father, and other blood relatives no longer see him; and he no longer sees his mother, father, or other blood relatives.’ ‘Good man, then am I not dead — will I be subject to death? Will my father, mother, or other blood relatives not see me? And will I not see my father, mother, or other blood relatives?’ ‘Your Highness, you and I as well — even though we are not yet dead, we will die. Your father, mother, and other blood relatives will not see you, and you will not see your father, mother, or other blood relatives.’ ‘Good man, then this visit to the pleasure garden is enough. Drive back to the palace.’ ‘Yes, Your Highness.’ Monks, the charioteer, obeying the prince, drove back to the palace. Monks, Prince Vipassī returned to the palace, suffering, grieving, and thought: ‘Shameful indeed is this birth! And anyone who is born must age, must be sick, must die like this!’”`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 14 – Mahāpadānasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn14/en/sujato" },

{ text: `All conditioned things are truly impermanent,<br>They arise and then pass away —<br>Their nature is always thus.<br>They come into being,<br>Then they again are destroyed.<br>Blissful indeed when they<br>Are calmed and at peace.`, ref: "Dīgha Nikāya 17 – Mahāsudassanasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/dn17/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“And what, monks, is the peril in the case of forms? Here, monks, one might see that woman at another time — eighty, ninety, or a hundred years old — aged, bent like a roof, crooked, leaning on a staff, trembling as she walks, sick, her youth exhausted, teeth broken, hair grey, bald, wrinkled, limbs shriveled and pale. What do you think, monks? Has her former charm and beauty disappeared and peril become evident?” “Yes, venerable sir.” “Thus, monks, is the peril in the case of forms.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, monks, one might see that woman — sick, suffering, gravely ill, lying in her own urine and feces, needing others to lift her, needing others to lay her down. What do you think, monks? Has her former charm and beauty disappeared and peril become evident?” “Yes, venerable sir.” “Thus, monks, is the peril in the case of forms.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, monks, one sees that woman’s corpse thrown in a charnel ground — eaten by crows, or by hawks, or by vultures, or by dogs, or by jackals, or by various worms. What do you think, monks? Has her former charm and beauty disappeared and peril become evident?” “Yes, venerable sir.” “Thus, monks, is the peril in the case of forms.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Furthermore, monks, one sees that woman’s corpse thrown in a charnel ground — with skeleton still connected, still having flesh and blood, held together by sinews … with skeleton still connected, without flesh but smeared with blood, held together by sinews … without flesh, without blood, held together by sinews … disconnected bones scattered here and there — here a hand bone, here a foot bone, here a shin bone, here a thigh bone, here a hip bone, here a back bone, here a skull. What do you think, monks? Has her former charm and beauty disappeared and peril become evident?” “Yes, venerable sir.” “Thus, monks, is the peril in the case of forms.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" },

{ text: `“Monks, those ascetics or brahmins who do not know as it actually is the gratification as gratification, the peril as peril, the escape as escape in the case of forms — they will certainly not understand forms as they actually are, nor can they lead others to a similar position, namely, understanding forms as they actually are — such a thing is not possible. Monks, those ascetics or brahmins who know as it actually is the gratification as gratification, the peril as peril, the escape as escape in the case of forms — they will certainly understand forms as they actually are, and they can lead others to a similar position, namely, understanding forms as they actually are — such a thing is possible.”`, ref: "Majjhima Nikāya 13 – Mahādukkhakkhandhasutta", url: "https://suttacentral.net/mn13/en/sujato" }


        ];

